<DOCNO> AP881230-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0240EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ChemicalWeapons Bjt   12-30 0758</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chemical Weapons, Bjt,710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Trying To Reverse The Trend</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz, in one of
his last official acts, will undertake an international effort next
week in Paris to roll back the proliferation of chemical weapons
technology.
   He will represent the United States at a multinational conference
in the French capital that is expected to reaffirm a 1925 protocol
banning the use of chemical weapons and to encourage completion of
negotiations among 40 nations in Geneva of a new agreement
prohibiting production.
   Some 20 nations, by U.S. estimate, either have produced chemical
weapons or are capable of manufacturing them. Among them the State
Department includes Libya, whose leader, Moammar Gadhafi, is accused
by the department of supporting terrorism.
   Libya ``is one of the more recent ones, and one of the more
irresponsible ones'' to reach the edge of production, said a U.S.
official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   At one time, the civilized world abhorred poison gas. But Iraq
discovered in the Persian Gulf war that chemical weapons were
effective against numerically superior Iranian forces. And some
Third World countries resent interference with their chemical
industries.
   The United States stopped production in 1969, then resumed 17
years later on the grounds the Soviet Union and other potential
adversaries had chemical weapons programs. Currently, chemical
components and artillery shells to contain them are being produced
but stockpiled separately.
   President Reagan proposed the Paris conference in a speech to the
U.N. General Assembly last September. President-elect Bush said
during the election campaign in October that the United States must
take the lead in making sure that nations using chemical and
biological weapons are punished.
   ``The barriers against chemical warfare, breached as we've seen
during the Iran-Iraq war, must be repaired and raised even higher,''
he said. Bush vowed to make nations that use such weapons ``pay a
price.''
   Realistically, though, the 1925 protocol, to which 130 nations
are parties, has no enforcement provisions. Iraq, which denied using
the weapons, is one of them.
   Bush proposed a global ban in 1984 while twice casting
tie-breaking votes in the Senate to continue financing U.S.
production. An aide explained that Bush felt that as long as the
Soviets produced chemical weapons the United States should keep up.
   The Soviet Union acknowledged in 1987 possession of chemical
weapons, then claimed to have ceased production. A foreign ministry
spokesman said 50,000 tons would be stored, the rest destroyed.
   Officials of the two countries have held nine sessions in Geneva
to plan ways to restrict proliferation.
   So far, the United States and the Soviet Union are the only two
countries in the world to admit possessing chemical weapons.
   But in recent weeks the Reagan administration has accused Libya
of having a chemical weapons plant. Reagan, in a recent television
interview, said the government has not ruled out a military strike
against the plant.
   The Paris conference is expected to reaffirm the 1925 ban on
using the weapons and to urge adoption of a verifiable ban on
production, as well, by the 40-nation disarmament conference that
meets in February in Geneva.
   Two other steps may be taken in Paris: authorizing the
secretary-general of the United Nations to investigate allegations
of the use of chemical weapons, and some form of assistance for
victims.
   Nearly all the 159 nations that are members of the United Nations
are sending their foreign ministers or ambassadors to Paris. ``You
can expect an enormous turnout,'' said the U.S. official, who is
involved in preparations for the Jan. 7-11 conference.
   Whatever declaration emerges, there is no way to enforce it,
although sanctions may be discussed. And, the official said, ``there
is a great allergy, particularly in the Arab world, to pointing
fingers at their capabilities and their emerging capabilities. So
that becomes a bit sensitive.''
   Assuming the 40 nations in Geneva, which do not include Iraq and
Libya, decide to ban the production and possession of chemical
weapons, there still will be an enormous problem.
   ``We recognize that verification is a very complicated problem,''
the official said. ``When you are talking about not producing
chemical agents, that raises all kinds of very difficult issues. Any
chemical industry which can produce pesticides to kill insects can
probably produce chemical agents to kill people. And that's one of
the frightening parts of this whole business. They are relatively
simple to construct and to make.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Barry Schweid covers diplomacy for The Associated
Press.
</TEXT>
