<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Rajneesh-NameChange     12-30 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rajneesh-Name Change,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Guru By Any Other Name Would Be Just As Divine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   You can call him Shree. And you can call
him Rajneesh. But Oregon's former self-styled guru of wealth and
free love, Bhagwan Shree Rajneesh, says until further notice that
you don't need to call him God.
   Rajneesh announced Thursday he has dropped the honorific title of
Bhagwan, a Hindi word meaning God.
   Many Indians resented Rajneesh calling himself Bhagwan because,
in Hinduism, no mortal is equal to God.
   ``I have been calling myself `Bhagwan' just as a challenge to
this country,'' the 57-year-old who once taught philosophy in India
said in the statement from his new commune in Poona, western India.
   ``I don't want to be called `Bhagwan.' Enough is enough. The joke
is over,'' he said.
   Rajneesh was deported three years ago from the United States
after he pleaded guilty to immigration fraud and closed his
64,000-acre commune of Rajneeshpuram in central Oregon. Followers
had bestowed dozens of Rolls Royces on their revered guide of
Eastern religion, pop psychology and free love.
   After roaming in search of a new sanctuary for a claimed 500,000
faithful worldwide, he moved his cult to a six-acre commune in
Poona, a city of nearly 1 million residents about 80 miles southeast
of Bombay.
   But despite Thursday's announcement, the guru did not entirely
renounce claims to divinity.
   He told 10,000 people in Poona, ``From today onwards, you can
look at me as `Gautama the Buddha.' And by accepting Gautama the
Buddha as my very soul, I go out of the Hindu fold completely.''
   Gautama Buddha, born in India about 500 B.C., renounced a title
too. Born a prince, he gave up nobility to launch a new religion _
Buddhism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
