<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0328EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-NuclearSafety     12-30 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nuclear Safety,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Group Says Number Of Nuclear Accidents Rose Last Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The country's nuclear power plants reported
2,940 mishaps in 1987, a slight increase from the year before,
according to an anti-nuclear organization.
   A report Thursday by Public Citizen's Critical Mass Energy
Project said the accident figure represented incidents reported by
nuclear plant owners to the Nuclear Regulatory Commission and
classified by the NRC as ``potentially significant safety events.''
   The corresponding figure was 2,836 accidents in 1986, when there
were 99 reactors in operation. The number of operating reactors grew
to 109 in 1987, according to the report.
   Public Citizen, a non-profit research organization and longtime
critic of nuclear power, also said Thursday that in 1987 there was a
record number of more than 104,000 incidents in which nuclear
workers were exposed to measurable doses of radiation.
   In addition, it said there were at least 430 emergency shutdowns
last year and at least 492 violations of nuclear plant safety rules.
   The report was based on NRC data compiled and analyzed by Public
Citizen.
   Joan Claybrook, president of Public Citizen, said in releasing
the report: ``Public attention has recently been focused on the poor
safety conditions at the nation's nuclear weapons reactors.
   ``However, in 1987, badly managed commercial nuclear plants daily
threatened the safety of the public, particularly the 96 million
Americans who live within 50 miles of a reactor,'' she said.
   Public Citizen criticized the NRC for refusing to release key
safety data such as ``single-component failure'' records and a
comprehensive listing of all emergency plant shutdowns. It contended
that the commission's public records on safety violations are
incomplete and contradictory.
   Robert Newlin, an NRC spokesman, said he could not comment in
detail on specific allegations without first having a chance to
examine the Public Citizen report.
   ``I would say that in general the NRC makes data available to the
public on all safety issues,'' he said. Newlin added that based on a
variety of safety and operational criteria, ``the overall
performance at nuclear plants, we think, is improving.''
   Carl Goldstein, a spokesman for the U.S. Council for Energy
Awareness, a nuclear industry group, said in response to the Public
Citizen report: ``America's nuclear plants have just ended a
record-breaking year, producing 20 percent of the nation's
electricity.
   ``The NRC and the Institute of Nuclear Power Operations confirm
that, year by year, nuclear plants have improved their availability
and reduced the number of significant events, which are an important
measure of safe operation,'' Goldstein said.
   Here are key findings of the Public Citizen report:
   _In 1987 a total of 430 ``scrams'' or emergency plant shutdowns
were reported to the NRC. This worked out to an average of 4.4
shutdowns per operating reactor.
   Plants experiencing the largest number of scrams during the year
were Vogtle-1, Waynesboro, Ga., 27 shutdowns; Shearon Harris-1,
Newhill, N.C., 21 shutdowns, and Beaver Valley-2, Shippingport, Pa.,
17 shutdowns.
   _There were at least 2,940 mishaps at U.S. power reactors in
1987. That was the tally of ``licensee event reports'' submitted to
the NRC by utilities. According to NRC guidelines, they provide
descriptions of ``potentially significant safety events'' that
``might lead to serious accidents.''
   Reactors with the highest number of mishaps were Nine Mile
Point-2, Scriba, N.Y., 79 mishaps; Perry-1, North Perry, Ohio, 77
mishaps, and Vogtle-1, 75 mishaps.
   _In 1987 an all-time high of 104,458 incidents occurred in which
workers at nuclear reactors received measurable doses of radiation.
   _At least 492 violations of safety regulations at U.S. power
reactors were cited by the NRC in 1987. ``Inasmuch as NRC's data are
incomplete, the actual number is probably significantly higher,''
the Public Citizen report said.
   Plants at which the highest numbers of violations were reported
include Sequoyah-1 and 2, Daisy, Tenn., 37 violations; Browns
Ferry-1, 2 and 3, Decatur, Ala., 35 violations, and Turkey Point-3
and 4, Florida City, Fla., 33 violations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881230-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0328EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bush-Pintlala     12-30 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush-Pintlala,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rural Crossroads Giddy Over President-elect's Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KENDAL WEAVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PINTLALA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's not Kennebunkport South. It's not even
Plains.
   But the rural crossroads of Pintlala, which consists of little
more than a country store with gas pumps, took on the look of a
presidential retreat when George Bush arrived with his fishing
tackle.
   The president-elect, accompanied by a 17-vehicle entourage of
security and press, stopped by Thursday to fish for bass at Ray
Scott's 55-acre private lake in Pintlala's partly rolling, partly
swampy terrain 15 miles south of Montgomery.
   ``I haven't seen so much excitement since the milk truck turned
over a couple of years ago,'' said area resident Don Williamson.
   ``What Camp David and San Clemente have been to other presidents,
we hope Pintlala will be for the Bush administration,'' joked the
Rev. Gary Burton, pastor of the Pintlala Baptist Church, who
gathered with a dozen other people to welcome Bush.
   A few dozen more collected outside Scott's guarded gate Thursday
evening when the Bush caravan pulled out.
   ``Thank you all very much,'' said Bush, speaking through an
amplified car speaker. ``Happy New Year to everybody.''
   Scott, a Bush political ally and a Montgomery native who founded
the Bass Anglers Sportsman Society, arranged the afternoon of
fishing in the former Creek Indian settlement.
   Bush caught nine fish by day's end. The largest weighed three
pounds, and he threw them all back.
   Scott and Bush played a joke on the press, with Bush holding up a
huge bass as cameras rolled. The fish was actually a mounted trophy
from Scott's home.
   The welcoming group, with one little girl holding high a sign
that read ``Good Fishing,'' cheered as Bush arrived. The group then
went to Mosley's service station, which serves as a grocery, hot dog
stand and unofficial city hall for Pintlala.
   At Mosley's, a few dozen other people had gathered, thinking Bush
would pass by the junction of U.S. 31 and Federal Road, which
amounts to ``downtown Pintlala.'' But the Bush motorcade took a
faster route on Interstate 65, turning into the Scott farm from
another local road.
   Pintlala's population is ``less than a thousand, not counting the
deer and quail,'' said Constable Ben Alpert.
   ``Use the word `quail' advisedly,'' warned the Rev. Burton.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
