<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Bakkers-Television     12-30 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bakkers-Television,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jim And Tammy Bakker Plan Return To Television</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jim Bakker and his wife, Tammy, will
return to television for the first time in nearly two years Monday
with a live show broadcast from their living room, a newspaper
reported today.
   Six independent television stations across the nation will carry
the program, said The Charlotte Observer, quoting unidentified
sources.
   Bakker, who was indicted with three associates this month on
charges of misusing millions of dollars in PTL money, could not be
reached for comment Thursday.
   Bakker has not had a regular TV show since resigning from PTL in
March 1987 after widely publicized allegations of his 1980 sexual
encounter with church secretary Jessica Hahn and payments to keep
her quiet. He and Tammy Bakker were co-hosts of PTL's ``Jim and
Tammy Show.''
   The Bakkers' new show will be broadcast live from their living
room near Pineville Monday through Friday and will be carried on
stations in Albany, N.Y.; Atlanta; Chico, Calif.; Los Angeles;
Philadelphia; and San Diego, the Observer said.
   Bakker attorney Jim Toms of Hendersonville said in a telephone
interview Thursday night that the Bakkers had been preparing to
return to television, but could not confirm when the return would
take place.
   While at PTL, the Bakkers' show was broadcast by about 180
television stations.
   Asked what kind of program the Bakkers are planning, a source
replied, ``The same as before.''
   ``It's real important,'' the source said of Monday's show. ``It's
the first day back. It's not going to be any fly-by-night thing.''
</TEXT>
