<1ST_LINE>r i PM-India-Bomb     12-30 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-India-Bomb,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes In Punjab Neighborhood, Kills 5</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMRITSAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded in a crowded neighborhood
in Punjab state today as police tried to defuse the device, killing
at least five people and injuring 20, authorities said.
   The dead included a police inspector and two constables working
to detach the bomb, which had been placed in a tin box and attached
to a bicycle parked in a central Amritsar neighborhood, authorities
said.
   No one claimed responsibility for the blast, which occurred at
7:30 a.m.
   But police said they suspected Sikh militants waging a 6-year
guerrilla war against India's Hindu majority for a separate homeland
in Punjab, a prosperous farming state bordering Pakistan.
   According to a police spokesman, an anonymous caller warned
authorities of the bomb.
   Police Inspector Bhagat Singh and six assistants went to the
neighborhood and as they tried to defuse the bomb, it exploded,
killing Singh and constables Bachitar Singh and Kishan Lal, the
police spokesman said. Two men, a Sikh and a Hindu, also died.
   Twenty others, including several children on their way to school,
were injured, the spokesman said. At least 10 were in serious
condition, he said.
   Sikhs make up 2 percent of India's 880 million people, but they
are a slight majority in Punjab. Hindus comprise more than 80
percent of the country's population.
   Sikh militants, claiming discrimination by the Hindu community,
have been demanding an independent nation in Punjab since 1982. They
have been blamed for more than 2,400 killings this year alone.
</TEXT>
