<DOCNO> AP881230-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0510EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-FarmScene     12-30 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,666</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most Farmers Met Contracts Despite Drought, USDA Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The summer's devastating drought caused
relatively few farmers to renege on contracts for advance sales of
corn, soybeans and wheat, the Agriculture Department says.
   The report by the department's Economic Research Service said a
survey of 325 elevators, or warehouses, in 13 Corn Belt and spring
wheat states showed farmers would default on less than 1 percent of
their contracts.
   ``Only about 1 percent of these elevators expected that losses
from farmers failing to meet contract commitments would exceed 10
percent of the elevator's net worth,'' the report said.
   The report was ordered by Congress in this year's Disaster
Assistance Act, which provided aid to farmers hit by the drought and
hot weather during the spring and early summer months.
   Drought raised commodity prices sharply and left many farmers
with less grain and soybeans to deliver than they had counted on
when they entered into forward contracts early in the year.
   ``Many would have liked to get out of their contracts, if that
were possible, because market prices rose above the contracted
prices,'' the report said. ``Some farmers produced less than they
had sold forward and faced buying out their contracts at a loss.''
   If farmers defaulted, that would leave elevators or other buyers
to absorb the losses.
   The report was sent to Capitol Hill but has not been distributed
generally by USDA. A copy was made available Thursday to The
Associated Press.
   Most of the information was based on a telephone survey of the
325 elevators in September. The report said the survey results also
were consistent with information obtained in field interviews of
elevator managers, telephone interviews of bankers and brokers, and
from state grain marketing specialists.
   ``Severe drought and the associated grain and soybean price
increases hit farmers who priced forward in two ways,'' the report
said. ``Those who hedged by selling futures were the first to be
affected. To meet margin calls during the period when prices
increased, these farmers had to either tap financial reserves or
obtain increased credit.''
   But the study found in a ``small-scale survey of commodity
brokers and bankers'' that farmers and their brokers and bankers
successfully weathered the sharp commodity price increases and the
resulting calls for greater margins, or deposits, that occurred in
June and July.
   ``For farmers who entered into cash forward contracts, the
financial problem hit when it became necessary to buy back contracts
in lieu of making delivery,'' the report said.
   More than half of the elevators surveyed had forward contracts
with farmers for corn, soybeans or wheat produced in 1988. The
contracts covered about 15 percent of the corn, 22 percent of the
soybeans and 7 percent of the spring wheat that these elevators
bought this year.
   According to the survey, the elevators indicated that more than
95 percent of their outstanding forward contracts with farmers
likely would be fulfilled as originally negotiated, with between 1
percent and 2 percent renegotiated, and less than 1 percent in
default. The remainder were uncertain.
   Officials had expected higher rates of default and renogotiation,
but the report said many farmers realized the possible intensity of
the drought by early June and curtailed normal contracting activity.
   ``As a result, farmers incurred fewer contract obligations than
they might have incurred if the drought had not become apparent
until later in the season,'' the report said.
   Weather also was important during that period, the report said.
Many areas, particularly in Ohio, Indiana and parts of Illinois,
received rain in late July and early August, which improved yield
prospects in those areas.
   In those cases, improved yields helped farmers meet contract
obligations, compared with the uncertainties of only a few weeks
earlier.
   The 13 states included an eastern Corn Belt region of Illinois,
Indiana, Kentucky, Michigan, Ohio and Wisconsin, and a western Corn
Belt region of Iowa, Minnesota, Missouri, Montana, Nebraska, North
Dakota and South Dakota.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881230-0025 </DOCNO>
