<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Armenia-Nuclear     12-30 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Armenia-Nuclear,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Experts Say Armenian Nuclear Plant Must be Reinforced or Shut</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A nuclear plant in Soviet Armenia should be
strengthened against earthquakes as quickly as possible or closed,
experts were quoted as saying in an official report.
   Tass, the official Soviet news agency, said Thursday that
specialists hurried to inspect the plant near Yerevan, the capital
of Armenia, after the earthquake Dec. 7 that killed thousands of
people.
   They concluded that the plant was not damaged but needed
reinforcement against earthquakes ``within the shortest possible
time'' or it should be closed, Tass said.
   The report follows an announcement by Soviet nuclear power
officials last week that six nuclear power projects were scrapped
because of earthquake danger or because of tougher standards. New
rules were imposed after the Chernobyl nuclear disaster in April
1986 killed at least 31 people.
   Speculation abounded after the earthquake earlier this month that
the plant near Yerevan was damaged. The facility lies near a
geological fault.
   Soviet Premier Nikolai I. Ryzhkov told reporters in Yerevan on
Dec. 12 that the plant would be shut in two years.
   But the Tass story, quoting Yevgeny Velikhov, vice president of
the Soviet Academy of Sciences, mentioned no deadline.
   The facility generates more than one-third of the Caucasus
mountain republic's electricity.
</TEXT>
