<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Reagan     12-30 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan,405</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Vows To Bring Jet Bombers To Justice</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is pledging an
all-out effort to bring those responsible for the ``savage and
tragic'' bombing of Pan Am Flight 103 to justice.
   ``What we want to do is find out who did it and bring them to
justice,'' Reagan said in a statement Thursday before flying here
from Los Angeles to continue a two-week California vacation.
   When they arrived in Palm Springs, the president and Nancy Reagan
were greeted by the mayor of Palm Springs, entertainer Sonny Bono,
and his wife.
   The Reagans will be guests until Monday at the palatial desert
home of publisher Walter Annenberg in nearby Rancho Mirage,
continuing their custom of attending a New Year's party there.
   The Reagans then plan to return to Los Angeles to spend a few
more days in the Bel Air residence that will be their home after
Reagan's term ends on Jan. 20. They are scheduled to fly back to
Washington Jan. 5 for their final two weeks in the White House.
   Reagan's statement at the Los Angeles airport was his first since
British authorities announced more than 24 hours earlier that they
had determined the crash was caused by a bomb. The crash killed 259
people in the air _ mostly Americans _ and 11 on the ground.
   ``I think you all know that I have been following quite closely
the details of the Pan Am 103 tragedy, and now that we know
definitely that it was a bomb, we're going to make every effort we
can to find out who is guilty of this savage and tragic thing and
bring them to justice,'' the president said.
   Reagan, echoing comments made by officials in Washington, said
the Federal Aviation Administration ``is studying and making
recommendations as to additional things we can do at airports to
provide security for those who travel.''
   Asked whether he thought the bombing was the work of terrorists,
the president said, ``I can't comment on that. It seems to savor of
that, but we're going to have to have more details, and we're doing
everything we can to find them and working in connection with other
countries on that.''
   British investigators announced in London Wednesday they have
``conclusive evidence'' that a bomb, not structural failure, caused
the Pan American jumbo jet to break up Dec. 21 over southwestern
Scotland.
</TEXT>
