<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Markets     12-30 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0287</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Slips Against Yen In Last Trading Day Of Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar slipped today against the Japanese
yen in Tokyo, ending the year's final trading day at 125.90 yen.
   After opening at 125.75 yen, down 0.28 yen from Thursday's
closing, the dollar inched up but failed to regain its Thursday
level. It closed at 125.90 yen, down 0.13 yen, after ranging between
125.75 and 126.00 yen during the day.
   Dealers attributed the dollar's losses in Tokyo to its decline on
overseas markets Thursday.
   A dealer at a major commercial bank in Tokyo described trading as
``very thin'' ahead of the three-day New Year's holiday starting
Saturday.
   After beginning the year in Tokyo on Jan. 4 at 120.45 yen, its
lowest level since modern exchange rates were established in the
late 1940s, the dollar stayed mostly between 120 and 130 yen in the
first half of the year.
   However, in the second half it fluctuated between the low-120 yen
and mid-130 yen levels. After peaking at 136.75 yen on Sept. 2, the
U.S. currency began declining to a low closing of 120.88 yen on Nov.
25. Since then it has remained generally within the 120-126 yen
range.
   Currency dealers said more stability is expected in exchange
rates in 1989 unless President-elect Bush makes drastic changes in
his economic policy from that of the Reagan administration.
   ``But unless the United States succeeds in trimming its twin
deficits, the general tendency will be toward a weaker dollar
against a stronger yen,'' said a dealer at a U.S. commercial bank in
Tokyo, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange will reopen Jan. 4.
</TEXT>
