<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Marcos     12-30 0441</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Marcos,0459</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Philippine President Returns to Hospital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine president Ferdinand Marcos was
hospitalized in guarded condition with possible congestive heart
failure or pneumonia, hospital officials said.
   Marcos, who contends he is too ill to travel to New York for
arraignment on racketeering charges, entered St. Francis Medical
Center on Thursday for the second time in three weeks.
   ``They (the attending physicians) have diagnosed him as a
possible congestive heart failure or pneumonia,'' said St. Francis
nursing supervisor Cindy Miller. Marcos, 71, was listed in guarded
condition.
   A leading Marcos supporter, said a priest administered the last
rites to Marcos, but a Marcos spokesman could not provide
confirmation.
   Marcos is ``very, very seriously ill,'' said the supporter,
Friends of Marcos President Joe Lazo. ``We are preparing a telegram
to send to President Reagan and President-elect Bush, asking them to
let him (Marcos) go home. That is his dying wish.''
   Marcos spokesman Gemmo Trinidad said he did not know if a priest
had administered the sacrament of the sick, formerly known as
extreme unction.
   Marcos was brought to the hospital by ambulance at 4:55 p.m.,
said St. Francis spokeswoman Norma Kop.
   Trinidad said he was with Marcos when he was taken to the
hospital, but said he did not know why the decision was made to
return Marcos to St. Francis.
   ``You'd better ask the doctors,'' Trinidad said in a telephone
interview earlier Thursday. ``All I know is he is in serious
condition.'' He would not elaborate.
   However, Marcos' private physician Dr. Azucena Ignacio, asked if
his patient's condition was serious, replied, ``We don't know yet.''
   Ms. Ignacio said Marcos' wife, Imelda, was at the hospital with
her husband.
   Marcos returned to his Makiki Heights residence Dec. 18 following
a 9-day stay at St. Francis, where he was treated for congestive
heart failure, his doctors said.
   Ignacio and Marcos cardiologist Calvin Wong said upon his release
that Marcos suffered from congestive heart failure, which means the
heart is unable to pump the amount of blood required by the body.
   A federal grand jury in New York City indicted Marcos and his
wife, Imelda, on Oct. 21, on racketeering charges. They were accused
of looting more than $100 million from their homeland to buy art and
real estate in Manhattan.
   Mrs. Marcos later went to New York to plead innocent to the
charges and is free on $5 million bail.
   Marcos claimed he was too ill to travel to New York. His
arraignment has been postponed indefinitely.
   The Marcoses fled to Hawaii in February 1986 following his ouster
in a civilian-military revolt.
</TEXT>
