<DOCNO> AP881230-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0635EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Barry     12-30 0633</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Barry,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mayor Barry Says He May Take Drug Test</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Marion Barry admitted visiting an
acquaintance suspected of drug involvement ``caused some
embarrassment'' for the city but said he was innocent of wrongdoing
and would be ``extra, extra careful'' to avoid appearances of
impropriety in his personal life.
   The city's U.S. attorney, meanwhile, said Thursday that his
office had decided to conduct a full investigation of the incident,
in which the mayor visited a former city employee at a Washington
hotel just as police were preparing to attempt an undercover drug
buy from the man.
   The Washington Post, in today's editions, quoted an unidentified
source as saying the FBI may join the federal investigation.
   Police have turned over to U.S. Attorney Jay B. Stephens results
of an internal probe into why two detectives were stopped from
attempting a drug buy from former city employee Charles Lewis after
Barry turned up at Lewis' hotel room. The incidence occurred a week
ago.
   Earlier this week, federal prosecutors had said only that they
were reviewing what police investigators had found. But on Thursday,
Stephens said his office ``is conducting a full investigation of
this entire matter.''
   Barry, through spokesmen, has repeatedly denied any wrongdoing.
On Thursday he called a news conference to answer questions ``around
the controversy'' and he vigorously denied using or seeing drugs in
the hotel room.
   ``I believe that one is innocent until proven guilty,'' Barry
said. ``But since last Thursday, I have been tried, convicted,
sentenced and doing time, by some members of the media.''
   Barry has acknowledged making several visits to Lewis, whom he
described as an acquaintance, but denied any involvement with drugs.
   Asked in a separate interview on WJLA-TV whether he would submit
to a drug test, Barry responded, ``I would do anything necessary to
get this issue behind us.'' He said he would discuss it with his
doctor ``and he'll tell me what to do.''
   Asked if that meant he would take the drug test if his doctor
approved, the mayor said he would, ``absolutely.''
   However, Barry's spokesman, John White, said earlier that no
purpose would be served by such a test since ``he doesn't do drugs.''
   The police investigation, according to sources, was focused on
whether Lewis was involved in any drug activity, why the mayor was
in the hotel, and why the police officers did not search Lewis'
hotel room until after he had checked out Friday morning. Hotel
employees, police sources said, initially had complained that Lewis
had offered drugs in return for sex.
   ``The public needs to know what happened,'' Barry said. ``I still
have demanded and call for a complete investigation and a complete
disclosure of this report so this city can get on with its
business.''
   At the beginning of the news conference, Barry promised to
provide details on his relationship with Lewis, but he revealed only
that he met Lewis when Lewis worked for the district government. The
mayor refused to answer reporters' questions after finishing his
remarks.
   While city employees applauded Barry as he marched from the
council chambers, others were not impressed with the mayor's
comments.
   ``He had an opportunity to talk to the nation, and he missed that
opportunity,'' said City Council Chairman David Clarke. ``There were
a lot of unanswered questions.''
   Barry's latest controversy refocuses scrutiny on his personal
life.
   Barry, who is married, acknowledged last year he once had a
``personal'' relationship with a convicted cocaine dealer, Karen
Johnson. However, he denied buying cocaine from her or using drugs
with her, and denied reports she had been paid hush money.
   Johnson had been jailed on contempt charges three years earlier
after refusing to testify before a grand jury. Officials say the
case remains under investigation.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881230-0037 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0637EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Obit-Johnson     12-30 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Johnson,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Health Official And Early Critic Of Rocky Flats Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHEAT RIDGE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dr. Carl J. Johnson, an early and
outspoken critic of the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant, has died
of complications from heart surgery. He was 59.
   Johnson died Thursday at the Lutheran Medical Center in this
Denver suburb, his son, Frederick, said.
   Johnson was forced to resign as Jefferson County health director
in May 1981, following his publication of studies showing a higher
incidence of cancer in areas of Jefferson and Denver counties close
to the Rocky Flats plant 16 miles northwest of Denver.
   Johnson sued numerous county officials over the firing. He
received a $150,000 settlement in January 1985.
   ``They fired the messenger for the message,'' said John Holland,
the attorney who represented Johnson in the case. ``They killed off
the community's public health director for proving that the
community had a major illness.
   ``To me, Carl Johnson was truly a great man ... His death is a
tragedy in that it's too early.''
   Holland said Johnson ``accomplished a great portion of his
mission which was to revitalize the people's right to live in a safe
setting.''
   Johnson's supporters said the government is now starting to
acknowledge points he had been making for years.
   For example, the Department of Energy recently compiled a
modernization report which calls for improvements to the nation's
nuclear weapons facilities through the year 2010.
   According to a summary of the $250 billion Energy Department
plan, Rocky Flats' recycling buildings would be upgraded between
1990 and 1997 to continue operating safely as the plant is gradually
shut down and relocated.
   Johnson recently had been doing consulting work on the effects of
nuclear radiation, Holland said. He wrote and published articles,
including a Dec. 18 column in The New York Times, headlined ``Rocky
Flats: Death Inc.''
   ``If the nation is to be properly protected, all studies of
nuclear contamination and associated health effects should be
conducted primarily by independent scientists who are insulated from
cynical retaliation,'' he wrote.
   The Sims, Ind., native received his medical degree in 1965 from
Ohio State University College of Medicine. He also held a master's
degree in public health from the University of California School of
Public Health at Berkeley.
   He became Jefferson County health director in 1973.
   Following his resignation, he spent five years as a medical
officer with the South Dakota Health Department in Pierre, S.D. He
recently returned to Denver.
   As controversy surrounding Rocky Flats built over the past four
months, Johnson appeared and spoke at almost every public forum.
   He also served as a colonel in the medical corps of the U.S. Army
Reserve from 1970 until his death.
   Johnson is survived by his wife, Kathryn, and three sons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
