<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BaseClosingsTranscript 4Takes   12-30 0860</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Base Closings Transcript, 4 Takes,0873</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transcript of Pentagon Briefing on Base Closings Report</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a condensed transcript of the Pentagon
briefing Thursday on recommendations by the defense secretary's
commission on military base closings. Participants were Deputy
Defense Secretary William H. Taft IV and commission co-chairmen
Abraham Ribicoff and Jack Edwards.
   RIBICOFF: We believe the results reflect a balanced report to
eliminate unnecessary installation capacity without restricting the
flexibility of our national security managers during future
mobilizations, contingencies and changes in the international
political environment. The recommended changes reflect an
opportunity to improve the nation's defense position.
   EDWARDS: We would like to take this opportunity ... to thank the
department and the Congress for this opportunity to participate in a
unique effort, which will not only save taxpayers dollars, but also
improve our national defense posture.
   During the course of developing our recommendations, we used
improvement in military value of our domestic base structure as the
preeminent consideration. Our report presents an opportunity to
reduce training costs in terms of manpower, overhead costs and fuel,
to improve command and control, to consolidate training and improve
economies of scale, and to remove unnecessary administrative burdens
to our defense managers.
   Add to these improvements an opportunity to eliminate some future
military construction costs and to save almost $700 million a year
in base operating costs with a 20-year net present value of $5.6
billion.
   Despite these improvements, we do not anticipate any substantial
socio-economic disruption to the communities that are closely linked
with bases recommended for closure.
   In terms of environmental impact, we see little negative impact
from these recommendations, and in many instances, improvement for
the natural surroundings.
   RIBICOFF: There are 145 installations affected. There are 86 for
closure, five for partial closure, 54 bases have been realigned. The
estimation is $693 million saved per year in base operating costs
and $5.6 billion to be saved over 20 years on the net present value.
... There are about 20 major ones.
   EDWARDS: I guess generally you would look at the L.A. area _ Fort
George and the Air Force base in Norton. Generally, you would look
in Illinois at Chanute Field and Fort Sheridan. Generally, you would
probably look at Fort Devens in Massachusetts, the Washington
national capital region area which would include Meade, Belvoir and
Holabird. You would look at perhaps Pease Air Force Base up in New
Hampshire. I guess those are the big areas.
   RIBICOFF: It goes from page 52 to page 69 (in the report), and I
think you will find that to be a very accurate explanation of the
rationale and what is happening to those bases.
   EDWARDS: (Fort) Dix (N.J.) is going into what we call
``semi-active status.'' There will be a group of probably 500 or so
people there who will maintain it, have it available for Reserve
activity, have it available for active duty training from time to
time, have it available in the event troops are brought home from
some part of the world. It will be there to support McGuire Air
Force Base (and) the naval station at Lakehurst.
   We broke down all of the military facilities into various
categories. And in our breakdown, Dix came out at the bottom of the
list in a category where we had excess capacity _ basic training,
advanced individual training and these types of things.
   We have moved those kinds of activities from Dix to various
facilities in the country, some to Fort Knox, some to Fort Leonard
Wood, Mo., some to Fort Jackson, S.C. And in the process, we moved
some out of Fort Bliss in Texas, so all of it becomes compatible.
What we've tried to do is bring training areas together to the
extent that we could, where we could justify it.
   Q. You mentioned in your opening statement that you didn't expect
any of these (communities) to be adversely affected by this. I think
a lot of the communities will find that hard to swallow.
   EDWARDS: Of course they will. I said ``substantial socio-economic
impact.'' Of course they will have a hard time swallowing it. ...
There are some areas where the impact is obviously larger than
others. But we have a section in here ... that deals with ways in
which communities can help themselves when they feel this kind of
impact.
   The Office of Economic Adjustment in the Defense Department has a
great ability to move in and help a community work out its problems.
Where possible, we have not moved troops across the country but next
door, in the same state or in an adjoining state.
   Q. Perhaps you could tell me what sort of thinking went into your
decision to close the Presidio in San Francisco?
   EDWARDS: The Presidio sits in the middle of San Francisco or
thereabouts, and it can't grow. It can't do any more than it's
doing. There's no way it can expand. It's prohibited by laws of
California and other laws as far as expansion is concerned. It's in
a high-value area, and the operations at the Presidio can be done by
and large most anywhere.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881230-0041 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0633EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BaseClosingsTranscript 1stAdd   12-30 0866</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Base Closings Transcript, 1st Add,0882</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: most anywhere.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Q. To what extent does the property value of these bases that
you've chosen play a role in your decision ... and how many total
jobs are we talking about here being lost?
   EDWARDS: The first thing we looked at was military value, without
a doubt. I mean, that was our touchstone. And if a base had military
value, then we didn't bother it. If the base was lacking in military
value, then it became a candidate to look at.
   We obviously did not ignore cost savings. We used ... as our
guideline a six-year payback, as set out in the charter. And so if a
facility did not meet the six-year payback, then it's not in our
list. In some instances, we looked at estimates as to what we could
sell the property for, but it was not the cornerstone of our
activity.
   Q. How about the jobs question?
   EDWARDS: I don't know whether we actually totaled all that.
You'll see a column that talks about personnel out and personnel in,
both military and civilian. And I think if you'll ust run your
finger down the column to the area you're looking for, you'll see
the impact.
   Q. Is this the end of it, in your mind? Or can a year from now a
similar commission come back and recommend a similar number of
bases? I mean, a $5.6 billion savings over a certain number of years
is rather insignificant when you consider the total defense budget.
   RIBICOFF: We think the basic responsibility should be in the
hands of the secretary of defense. There should be an ongoing study
to see what changes should be made in the bases. We've recommended
that there should be a high-level, small group of people to go over
this with the secretary of defense, but I would hope that there
wouldn't always be a commission like ours that would be necessary to
do the whole job over again.
   The training is altogether different with the new technology.
We're going to have to acquire larger tracts of land. Many of the
present bases are limited because they have been surrounded by large
urban areas and their effectiveness has been destroyed. So I think
the country is going to have to take a good, hard look, and the
Defense Department, as to what future training will have to be for
future wars and the changes that are going to take place.
   Q. Can you tell us what the up-front costs of closing and
realigning these bases are?
   EDWARDS: Well, let's see, the Najavo Army Depot in Arizona, just
to pull one out of there. It's going to cost $11 million to make
that move. But it will pay back in annual savings $3.05 million. And
so it's going to take us four years to recover that initial cost of
the move before we start making annual savings. But then they are
annual savings forever.
   Q. As two former members of Congress, how do you think ... the
reaction on the Hill will be to this?
   EDWARDS: I believe the leadership of the Armed Services
Committees, of both the House and the Senate, favor this exercise
taking place. There's no question that many congressmen and senators
are going to be upset when they see this list, especially if it
affects (their) community.
   I would anticipate, from my own general conversations ... from
the time we were appointed to the present, that Congress will accept
it.
   Q. There are some lawmakers, especially from California, who have
already argued that the ... the state has been unfairly hit here.
Your reaction to that?
   EDWARDS: A lot of the activity in Southern California that is
reported in here has to do with Norton and George. They are both
encroached by air traffic congestion from the L.A. airport. They
can't train adequately because of that problem. They both have major
problems in attracting high-technology employees because of the
activity in that area in the civilian sector. And we felt that we
really just had no alternative but to deal with that.
   Mather (Air Force Base, Calif.), they are a good distance away
from their training area. They have to fly over 150 nautical miles
just to get to the area where they train their particular aircraft
and pilots. We have moved them into Mountain Home, Idaho, where
there is an electronic training range right there. ... I like to
think there's a rationale to what we've done.
   RIBICOFF: I think they (the Air Force) recognize the great
changes that have taken place in training with the present type of
equipment and the present time of aircraft and what has happened in
the urban areas, and they realize that changes have to be made. And
California ... is the fastest growing state in the Union, when it
comes to urban encroachment and the elimination of open spaces that
air forces need.
   Q. What happens if the list is rejected by Congress? Will
   you gentlemen start over?
   EDWARDS: We are a one-shot, unique kind of an organization. When
we hand this report over, we are finished.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881230-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0634EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BaseClosings-Transcript 2ndAdd   12-30 0867</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Base Closings-Transcript, 2nd Add,0883</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: are finished.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Q. Congressman (Les) Aspin (D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed
Services Committee) suggested that there was a loophole in this
whole procedure and that funds had to be appropriated annually to
close these bases and, by use of that loophole, bases could be
prevented from being closed. Did you address that question and what
did you do about it?
   EDWARDS: There is a problem, because the proceeds of the sales of
these facilities will go into the fund to carry out the purposes of
this law. And those proceeds are not going to start coming in on Day
One. It's going to take a while to come in. And so we have
recommended in this report that Congress in (fiscal 1990)
appropriate $300 million to put the first money in the fund so we
can start the process. And obviously, if Congress refuses to
appropriate enough money to get ... the process going, then it's
going to be very difficult.
   Q. It's often said that certain bases have remained open over the
years for political or pork barrel reasons. Did you find any
evidence of that in your study? And how far have you gone to
eliminating it, if that's the case?
   RIBICOFF: I don't think there was any influence or any attempt to
protect pork barrel bases. I don't think that was taken into account
at all. I don't think anybody on the commission felt any pressure.
We looked at these bases seriously. We looked at all the figures. We
spent a lot of time in discussion. Each and every base was voted on
unanimously, with the action taken.
   EDWARDS: You should understand first that we simply did not start
with a list. ... We started with a set of criteria which we applied
to all 4,300 installations in this country. ... And we took those as
we found them.
   Q. There are four states that are missing _ West Virginia,
Mississippi, Georgia and Wisconsin, all home states of the chairmen
of the Armed Services and Appropriations Committees. Were there no
bases in those states worthy of closing?
   EDWARDS: That's certainly not by design. We did take a little
something out of Fort McPherson in Georgia, I recall. I don't
believe we touched Wisconsin. West Virginia, I'm going to bet,
doesn't have a whole lot of military in the first place. ... We had
to deal with bases where we found them.
   Q. Could you please elaborate on some of the personnel changes
that are going to take place at Fort Devens and some of the other
bases that are getting increases of people?
   RIBICOFF: We found that certain missions were split between a
number of bases _ they didn't make any sense _ when they should have
been consolidated and put in one base. And what we did in many
instances, we just do that, and especially when you talk about Fort
Devens. ... You will find a shift from one fort to the other, one
base to the other, which will make it more effective, more
efficient, and be able to do a much better job with their mission.
   Q. I wonder if you had the opportunity to pass judgment on the
value of strategic home porting, to see whether dispersion of ships
offers protection in the nuclear age, or whether it's really just a
way of building local political support for various naval tasks.
   EDWARDS: I don't know anything that was discussed more than
strategic home porting. ... We concluded that our job was not to
deal with force structure. That's the military's job. ... Our job
was to try to deal with that force structure as we found it, and try
to accommodate it to the facilities that we were working with. And
so we had to live with the fact that there's going to be a 600-ship
Navy. Maybe there never will be... but we don't know that.
   So we had to look at the home ports with an idea where are you
going to put that other 150 ships that are building up from the
450-ship Navy. And we concluded that we could justify some home
ports, most of them.
   Q. If it were not for political constraints, could you actually
... expand your list? Are there a lot of other bases you consider
still vulnerable or could be effectively closed?
   EDWARDS: The biggest constraint ... is the six-year payback
constraint. We found a lot of facilities that had 10-year paybacks,
12-year paybacks, even 20-year paybacks, where we could have made
some major savings over a longer period of time. But we were
constrained by our charter, which had a six-year payback.
   RIBICOFF: Once you got over the six years, we had to stop. I
think wisdom and better planning would have been more meaningful if
we weren't stuck with that six-year payback.
   Q. In other words, some of these places survived because of
   their inefficiency?
   EDWARDS: No, I think it may cost a lot of money to move one
facility into another base and have to build all-new construction,
and your payback just simply won't make it.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
