<DOCNO> AP881230-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0635EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-BaseClosingsTranscript 3rdAdd   12-30 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Base Closings Transcript, 3rd Add,0536</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON: make it.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   RIBICOFF: It just goes to prove that there's still a lot of work
to be done, and it should be ongoing. And I would hope the next
secretary of defense would take this job very, very seriously. ...
There's money to be saved. And with tight budget restraints, you're
going to have to save it wherever you can for basic important
purposes in the defense establishment.
   Q. Some of the bases are under construction, such as the naval
station in Galveston, Texas. What's the rationale for closing that?
The state of Texas has already spent $8 million building a highway
to it.
   EDWARDS: My recollection is that we could save $8 million a year
forever. (Laughter.) We concluded that Galveston was primarily a
reserve center in the home port plan, that Lake Charles had only had
one oiler and one minesweeper, and that they could be moved to
Engleside, so that we would put together in one place in Texas the
carrier, the battleship and the support ships. That's the West Gulf.
Then on the East Gulf, you would have the
Pascagoula-Mobile-Pensacola complex. So you'd have two complexes on
the Gulf instead of whatever they were.
   Q. Some of the bases have been on hit lists. Things have changed
over the years. The base that led to the obstructing legislation was
Loring Air Force Base in Maine. What has changed over the years to
make that cold-weather base, which was considered obsolete in 1977,
necessary now?
   REP. EDWARDS: I can't give you chapter and verse, because it
didn't come through on our six-year payback. ... One of the things
we had to deal with was the fact that a lot of the bases that were
along the coast, such as Pease, the airplanes that would go in a
base like that are better centrally located in the United States
because of the time it takes for the Soviets or some enemy to get a
missile lobbed in. And you don't need them right up on the front
lines anymore.
   Q. Did you at all assess the impact on defense contractors that
support these facilities?
   EDWARDS: We did not.
   RIBICOFF: No.
   Q. I could not find Fort Monroe (Va.) anywhere. Who saved it?
   EDWARDS: Me. (Laughter.) I personally went to Fort Monroe to look
at it. And I saw the moat and ... the old historic buildings. ... I
also saw what would amount to around $900 million in cleanup costs
to get rid of the old shells that had been lobbed over on part of
that fort for the last 200 years or however long it was. I also saw
the cost of building new facilities to house all of those people _
3,000 or 4,000 people as I recall _ and it just didn't even come
close to our six-year payback. It was more like a 20-year payback at
best. And in part because there's no real market value for that
property. It would become, perhaps, a museum one day. ... I don't
know any developer in his right mind who would want to go in there
and buy that property.
</TEXT>
