<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0710EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     12-30 0747</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,745</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Labor Department Considers Lifting Homework Rules</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Department plans hearings early next
year to discuss lifting a World War II-era regulation that bars
apparel manufacturers from employing seamstresses in their homes.
   The department planned to publish in today's edition of the
Federal Register an advanced notice of proposed rulemaking as the
first formal step for lifting the ban, said Allan McMillan, a deputy
assistant labor secretary in charge of enforcing the prohibition.
   President-elect Bush urged the action last October after the
Labor Department won approval from the White House budget office to
remove homework prohibitions in five other apparel fields effective
Jan. 8.
   McMillan said the Labor Department will hold hearings on the
proposal in Miami on Feb. 22-23; in San Antonio, Texas, on March
2-3; and in Chicago on March 8-9.
   The prohibitions on apparel industry homework were imposed in
1942 to combat widespread exploitation of immigrants and other
low-wage workers. Lifting them has been the Reagan administration's
top deregulatory proposal in the labor relations area for the past
several years.
   The International Ladies Garment Workers Union, which represents
some 170,000 workers, said last week it will seek a court injunction
next week to prohibit the further removal of any of the remaining
bans on homework.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>-----</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gay Midshipman Sues For Reinstatement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gay midshipmen who says he was forced to
resign from the Naval Academy after admitting his homosexuality has
asked a federal court to order his reinstatement.
   Joseph C. Steffan, 24, of Moorhead, Minn., claimed in the suit
filed Thursday in U.S. District Court that his ``forced separation''
from the academy two months before his scheduled graduation violated
his constitutional rights of free speech, due process and equal
protection under the law.
   Steffan, now employed by a computer software company in Fargo,
N.D., acknowledged that he was aware of a provision in the
midshipmen's manual that homosexuals would be dismissed from the
academy.
   Jay Fromer, a spokesman for the Naval Academy, said the school
only abided by Navy regulations.
   ``Since we are a part of the Department of the Navy, we are bound
by Navy regulations which state homosexuality is incompatible with
military service,'' Fromer said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>-----</HEAD>
<HEAD>1988 Pontiac LeMans Seat Belt Buckles May Be Defective</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seat belts in 1988 Pontiac LeMans may be
defective and should be replaced, the National Highway Traffic
Safety Administration said.
   LeMans owners should contact their dealers to have the buckles
replaced ``as soon as possible,'' NHTSA administrator Diane K. Steed
said in a statement Thursday.
   There will be no charge for the replacements.
   ``To our knowledge, no one has yet been injured, but the
potential exists for safety belt failure at the worst possible
moment,'' said Steed.
   On Dec. 9, General Motors recalled about 85,000 of the cars to
replace the defective buckles because they may appear to be latched
when they are not.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>-----</HEAD>
<HEAD>Government Proposes New Controls On Pre-Cooked Meat Patties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department is considering new
federal labeling and processing rules to ensure that certain kinds
of meat patties, including pre-cooked hamburgers, are safe to eat.
   Lester M. Crawford, administrator of the department's Food Safety
and Inspection Service, said there has been ``increasing evidence
over the past several years'' that disease organisms survive in
products that many consumers erroneously believe are fully cooked
when bought.
   The proposal would affect fully cooked, partially cooked and
``char-marked'' ground meat patties.
   The proposed rule would establish requirements for the storage of
raw ingredients, processing times and temperatures, handling to
prevent contamination after processing, and labels that include
cooking instruction for final preparation.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>-----</HEAD>
<HEAD>Agriculure Department To Establish Offices At Black Schools</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department plans to open
offices at each of 17 historically black universities to help
encourage more minorities to enter agriculture and forestry.
   Deputy Secretary Peter C. Myers said Thursday the offices will be
``a focal point for all USDA activities'' at the universities,
collectively known as 1890 institutions because of land-grant
college legislation that year.
   A few department agencies have offices at some of those schools,
but Myers said this will be the first time that there will be an
on-campus link between USDA and each of the universities.
   Myers said the offices will help with curriculum development,
recruit and counsel students on employment opportunities in USDA,
and develop new ideas and approaches to help small-scale,
limited-resource and minority farmers.
</TEXT>
