<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-AfricanStudents     12-30 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-African Students,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Racial Strife Spreads To Hangzhou Over AIDS Rumor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Racial strife involving African students has
spread to a second Chinese city, with Africans at a university in
Hangzhou protesting rumors they were carriers of the disease AIDS.
   About 65 Africans attending Zhejiang Agriculture University in
Hangzhou have stayed in their dormitory since Monday, boycotting
classes and demanding to leave China, a student from Cameroon said.
   He said university officials have blocked attempts to leave the
eastern Chinese city.
   The student, speaking on condition of anonymity, said university
officials had implied they were carriers of the fatal disease AIDS.
``They treat us like criminals,'' he said.
   Further details of the dispute were inpeded by poor telephone
connections. University officials were not available for comment.
   Hangzhou is about 140 miles southeast of Nanking, scene of five
days of anti-African demonstrations stemming from a Christmas Eve
fight between African students and Chinese.
   Chinese officials have isolated about 140 African students and
other foreign sympathizers in a remote guest house outside the city
to protect them from Chinese demonstrators demanding Africans
responsible for injuring 11 Chinese be brought to justice.
   The Chinese side has refused the Africans' request to leave
Nanking, and only those students who agree to return to their
schools are being allowed to leave the guest house. Almost all the
Africans say they fear for their safety and will not return to the
city.
   The Xinhua Daily, Nanking's leading daily, ran a front-page story
today for the second straight day expressing understanding for the
anger of the Chinese youth and saying, ``The troublemakers, a
minority of foreign students, will be punished.''
   ``Africans come from developing countries and are struggling,''
the article said. ``This is not easy ... but China will not forgive
those students who break China's law.''
   The story also appealed for calm, and quoted professors from
Nanking Teachers College as saying, ``We mustn't turn a school's
problem into a social problem.''
   Yang Ruiju, president of Hehai University, said Thursday that no
Chinese would be punished for breaking windows and destroying
property at the African students dormitory during the Christmas Eve
brawl.
   Yang said seven or eight Africans were being investigated for
their involvement in the fight, which began when Africans refused to
register the names of their Chinese girlfriends they were taking to
a campus party.
   A Palestinian student in Nanking said today that Chinese who
visited the guest house the previous day had been told seven
Africans, the same ``troublemakers'' referred to by Yang, had been
separated from the other foreign students.
   There are an estimated 1,500 Africans from 40 nations studying at
Chinese universities.
   China has long provided scholarships for Africans in solidarity
with developing African states, but social tensions, which Africans
attribute to ingrained racial prejudices against blacks, have
occasionally flared out into violence between the Chinese and
Africans.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
