<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Refusenik 1stLd-Writethru   12-30 0537</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Refusenik, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0466,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Abe Stolar, Family Finally Given Permission To Emigrate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads throughout to UPDATE with quotes. No pickup. ADDS byline</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chicago-born Abe Stolar said today his family has
received permission to emigrate and that he would finally be leaving
the Soviet Union for the first time in more than a half-century.
   ``There's no feeling yet. It's just a big mess thinking of all
the things we have to do,'' Stolar said in perfect English in a
telephone call.
   The long struggle came to an end when Stolar's daughter-in-law
received word she would be allowed to join the rest of the family in
emigrating. Stolar, his wife and son received exit visas in 1975 but
his daughter-in-law was not given a visa, so the family decided not
to leave.
   Stolar's case has been the subject of negotiations between the
United States and the Soviets for years and its resolution was
another in a series of Kremlin moves to improve the country's human
rights record.
   Numerous prominent refuseniks, or Jews denied permission to
emigrate, have been allowed to leave since Mikhail S. Gorbachev took
power in March 1985.
   Stolar, a 77-year-old Jew, has not been out of the Soviet Union
since his parents, ardent American Communists, brought him here in
1931.
   His parents left the American Depression behind to help build the
new Soviet Union, but in 1937, his father disappeared in one of
dictator Josef Stalin's bloody purges.
   Stolar, who still holds U.S. citizenship, served with the Red
Army during World War II and afterward became an announcer and
translator for Radio Moscow.
   ``I have news now,'' an excited Stolar said in beginning the
phone call.
   He explained that he was numb after learning his family could
leave.
   ``They drag it out so long. It's been 13{ years. They try to drag
it out. The main thing now is to try to be calm and not to forget
anything, which is hard.''
   His 29-year-old son, Michael, said he was not very excited.
   ``I have no special feelings,'' he said. ``Perhaps in some time I
will feel happy, but now perhaps it's shock. I can't say I am happy
but I cannot say I am not happy.''
   The younger Stolar said he was probably reserved because he was
worried about friends who are having trouble emigrating, and who are
not getting the support like his family did from the U.S. government.
   Michael Stolar said his wife, Julia Shurukht, had telephoned
OVIR, the government agency that handles emigration matters, on
Monday and Tuesday. A deputy chief of the office said she would be
allowed to join the family in emigrating. A postcard confirming the
verbal notification is expected to arrive next week, and then the
family plans to fly to Israel, he said.
   After getting settled in Israel, the family plans to make their
first trip to the United States, to visit friends.
   The latest in a series of snags that held up Ms. Shurukht's
emigration was that her mother refused to sign a form saying her
daughter did not have any financial obligations to her. Abe Stolar
said the mother apparently has now signed the form.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
