<DOCNO> AP881230-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0716EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ChicagoMayoral     12-30 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chicago Mayoral,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Analyst Says Evans' Third-Party Candidacy Will Hurt Blacks' Chances</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A political analyst says Alderman Timothy Evans'
third-party bid for mayor may wind up accomplishing the very things
he hoped to avoid _ splitting the black vote and returning a Daley
to city hall.
   Evans announced Thursday that he was withdrawing from February's
Democratic primary to run in the general election as the candidate
of the Harold Washington Party, which he created and named after
Chicago's first black mayor.
   That leaves Mayor Eugene Sawyer, Evans' chief black rival, in a
primary showdown against Richard M. Daley, Cook County prosecutor
and son of the late Mayor Richard J. Daley, who ruled Chicago for
more than two decades.
   Evans repeatedly said he was not endorsing Sawyer in the primary,
but urged supporters to ``do whatever they can do to defeat Daley,''
who according to early polls is the front-runner among announced
candidates.
   Evans may ultimately regret both positions, said Eugene Kennedy,
a Loyola University professor, author of a biography of the elder
Daley and a veteran political observer.
   ``He urged black voters to keep away from Sawyer,'' Kennedy said.
``Then he made repeated references to Daley as though he were
somehow evil ... and that all whites, by implication, were somehow
`the enemy.'
   ``On the one hand, he weakens the very cause he purports to
support _ a black mayor for Chicago. On the other, he's galvanized
the (white ethnic) opposition,'' Kennedy said.
   Evans, 45, was Washington's floor leader in the City Council and
has tried since the late mayor's death to portray himself as heir to
Washington's legacy as a reformer.
   Sawyer, 54, was chosen to succeed Washington by many of the same
City Council members who were Washington's staunchest opponents. He
and Evans have waged a costly struggle for the loyalty of the black
community.
   Evans said some believed Sawyer should have withdrawn from the
primary ``because it is clear from all the available evidence I am
the choice of an overwhelming majority of our coalition.
   ``But as he has refused to do so, I will make that move _ secure
in the knowledge that I am at once serving, uniting and leading our
great coalition on a course that will result in a historic
victory,'' he added.
   The Daley and Sawyer camps expressed little surprise at Evans'
move Thursday.
   ``Mr. Daley has said all along that what's important are the
issues _ crime, education and health _ not who's in or who's out or
what the numbers are,'' said Daley spokeswoman Marj Halperin.
   ``Mayor Sawyer did not expect Tim Evans' endorsement in the
primary and he'd have been surprised if there was one,'' said a
Sawyer spokesman who refused to be identified.
   ``The mayor felt all along the important thing was to remove the
onus from both himself and Mr. Evans of splitting the black vote,''
the spokesman said. That was everybody's greatest fear and that has
now been removed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
