<HEAD>Rain Drenches Pacific Northwest; Atlantic Coast To Central Plains
Fair</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain drenched the Pacific Northwest and snow spread from the
Cascades into western Montana today as much of the nation from the
Atlantic Coast to the central Plains enjoyed fair weather.
   More than 2{ inches of rain fell Thursday at Astoria, Ore., as
snow caused major problems farther inland.
   A blizzard forced Oregon authorities to close part of Interstate
84, stranding holiday travelers along a 170-mile stretch of the
highway.
   Blowing snow reduced visibility to near zero, prompting the state
Highway Division to close the freeway about 9:30 a.m. Thursday.
Troopers patrolling the nearly deserted highway reported continuing
poor conditions 12 hours after the freeway was closed.
   Local officials said about 50 people spent the night at the local
armory, 60 to 75 stayed at a local Baptist church, a dozen stayed in
a local crisis action center, and an unknown number of private homes
were opened to travelers.
   Spokane, Wash., received 3 more inches of new snow Thursday
evening, leaving 8 total inches on the ground thus far.
   Snow and freezing rain advisories continued for the Cascade
mountains through the night. Up to 10 inches of new snow was
expected in the higher Cascade passes; freezing rain in the lower
passes.
   Snow spread into western Montana, and gusty winds up to 81 mph
also hit western and central Montana.
   Clouds and isolated rain spread across southern Texas and
Louisiana, and snow showers were scattered in the upper Mississippi
Valley and northern Great Lakes region. Snow showers also lingered
in parts of New York state.
   High pressure dominated from the Atlantic Coast into the central
Plains, providing fair weather.
   The nation's high Thursday was 84 degrees at Fort Myers and
Miami, both in Florida.
   Today's forecast called for rain in the Pacific Northwest, snow
in the northern Rockies and northern parts of the Great Basin and
northern Plains; showers and thunderstorms from eastern Texas across
the lower Mississippi Valley into the Tennessee Valley; snow showers
in Upper Michigan and southern Wisconsin.
   The remainder of the nation was expected to have fair weather.
   Predicted highs: single digits and teens in northern Maine; the
teens from eastern Montana across North Dakota and northern
Minnesota into western Upper Michigan; 20s and 30s in much of the
Rockies, South Dakota, the remainder of Minnesota and middle
Mississippi Valley, the Great Lakes and upper Ohio Valley, the
Middle Atlantic States and the remainder of New England; 60s and 70s
from south-central Texas across the Gulf Coast region to the
southern Atlantic Coast and northern Florida; the low 80s in
southern Florida. The rest of the country should reach the 40s and
50s.
   The nation's temperatures at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 12 degrees
below zero at International Falls, Minn., to 74 at Homestead, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 39 fair; Boston 29 cloudy; Buffalo 22 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C. 45 fair; Cincinnati 21 partly cloudy; Cleveland 9
fair; Detroit 14 fair; Miami 69 fair; New York 31 cloudy;
Philadelphia 29 cloudy; Pittsburgh 16 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine
15 partly cloudy; Washington 32 cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 5 snow; Chicago 18 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 43
cloudy; Denver 13 fair; Des Moines 26 fair; Indianapolis 15 cloudy;
Kansas City 28 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 10 foggy; Nashville 36
cloudy; New Orleans 56 cloudy; St. Louis 22 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 19 fair; Anchorage 23 cloudy; Las Vegas 28
fair; Los Angeles 45 fair; Phoenix 38 fair; Salt Lake City 20
cloudy; San Diego 45 fair; San Francisco 39 partly cloudy; Seattle
50 rain.
   _Canada: Montreal 10 partly cloudy; Toronto 19 cloudy.
