<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell in early European trading
today, losing more than 1 cent against the British pound. Gold
prices were mixed.
   Trading was thin on the last business day of 1988, giving some
transactions an exaggerated effect on rates, foreign currency
dealers said.
   ``The market is already semi-closed,'' said one dealer in Rome.
Banks have only skeleton staffs on duty and are limiting business to
postition-squaring and to serving corporate customers with some
last-minute requirements, he said.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.13 yen to close the year at 125.90 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 125.42 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.7798 West German marks, down from 1.7875
   _1.5065 Swiss francs, down from 1.5125
   _6.0795 French francs, down from 6.0975
   _2.0118 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0190
   _1,313.00 Italian lire, down from 1,314.50
   _1.1910 Canadian dollars, down from 1.191225
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8015, compared with $1.7900
Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $409.50 a troy ounce, up
from $408.25 bid late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $410.15.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $410.50, down from $410.75 bid late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $3.63 to close at a bid $412.44.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $6.03 a troy ounce,
down from Thursday's $6.04.
