<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Cholesterol-Cookies     12-30 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cholesterol-Cookies,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pepperidge Farm To Remove Tropical Oils From Crackers, Cookies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who spent $2 million to pressure the
food industry into making healthier products says he's pleasantly
surprised by Pepperidge Farm's decision to stop using coconut oil in
crackers and cookies.
   ``Ultimately Pepperidge Farms will have saved thousands of
lives,'' Phil Sokolof said Thursday.
   Coconut oil is a saturated fat that raises cholesterol levels.
People who have high levels of cholesterol run a higher risk of
clogged arteries that can lead to heart disease.
   Pepperidge Farm announced Wednesday that it would stop using
coconut oil in numerous products, including its popular ``Original
Goldfish,'' in response to ``strong consumer concern.''
   ``Frankly, I'm surprised, because Pepperidge Farm has a
multimillion-dollar undertaking on their hands to change their
products,'' said Sokolof, founder of the Nebraska-based National
Heart Savers.
   Pepperidge Farm will have to come up with new recipes for more
than 50 brands of cookies and crackers, said Sokolof, whose group
has campaigned against products using tropical oils.
   ``We must find oils that will proximate tropical oils in terms of
performance in the baking process, flavor, texture, mouth-feel and
shelf-life stability,'' Richard A. Shea, president of the
Norwalk-based company, said in a statement issued Wednesday.
   Coconut and palm oil are popular with food manufacturers because
they help extend the shelf life of food products, Sokolof said.
   Many products advertised as being free of cholesterol contain
tropical oils that can help cholesterol form after consumption, he
said. Coconut oil contains 100 percent more saturated fat than lard.
   Sokolof placed advertisments in newspapers in October depicting
nine products he says are portrayed as healthy foods, but are
``poisoning'' Americans with saturated fats.
   A 65-year-old multimillionaire who nearly died from a heart
attack in 1966, Sokolof has spent $2 million to pressure food
industry giants into making healthier products. His father and a
brother-in-law died of heart attacks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
