<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NoKorea-ChemicalWeapons     12-30 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NoKorea-Chemical Weapons,0478</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Mass Producing Chemical Weapons</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist North Korea is producing
chemical weapons at eight plants and organizing chemical warfare
units to help maintain superiority over South Korean and U.S.
forces, officials said today.
   A report by the South Korean Defense Ministry disclosed for the
first time that North Korea was producing chemical weapons,
including poison gas, at eight cities, including Sinhung and Sinuju.
   Chemical weapons would probably be used to knock out South Korean
and U.S. forces as part of lightning attacks if the North invaded,
officials said. The United States has 42,000 troops based in the
South under a defense pact.
   The report, part of an overview on South and North Korean
military forces, said the North also has six storage sites for
chemical weapons and three research and development centers.
   Storage centers are located near the South Korean border for
possible use in a war, the report said. Chemical weapons factories
are based in the north of the country, with many close to the
Chinese and Soviet borders, it said.
   U.S. military officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said they were aware of reports of North Korea's chemical warfare
capability, but declined to comment further.
   North Korea had formed chemical warfare units and attached them
to infantry regiments, officials said. The North is expected to
eventually deploy chemical, they said.
   The North is also producing Soviet-designed ``Scud'' and ``Frog''
missiles with ranges of up to 180 miles that could be used to
deliver chemical warheads, officials said.
   The officials could not say when chemical weapons might be
deployed by North Korea. They noted that the North had been
developing chemical weapons since the 1960s.
   South Korean and U.S. forces have anti-chemical warfare gear,
such as gas masks and chemical warfare suits. The two governments
decline to say if they deploy chemical weapons in South Korea.
   U.S. forces in South Korea reportedly possess battlefield nuclear
weapons, but Washington refuses to confirm or deny the reports.
   The South Korean report noted that Seoul is making advances in
building up its defenses and expects to end the North's military
superiority by the start of the next century.
   But it said that North Korea still has a substantial edge in
troops and weapons and was producing large numbers of tanks,
artillery pieces, rockets and other weapons.
   North and South Korea have been conducting talks aimed at easing
tensions, but the bitter rivals have hundreds of thousands of
heavily-armed troops poised along their border.
   The two nations were formed after U.S. and Soviet forces ended
the Japanese occupation at the end of the Second World War in 1945.
North Korea invaded the South in 1950, prompting the bloody
three-year Korean War.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881230-0059 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0717EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Playboy-Woodward     12-30 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Playboy-Woodward,0379</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woodward Says Late Justice Was Source For Supreme Court Book</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reporter Bob Woodward has revealed that the late
U.S. Supreme Court Justice Potter Stewart was the confidential
source for his best-selling insider's look at the high court, ``The
Brethren.''
   In an interview published in the February issue of Playboy
magazine, The Washington Post reporter said he was willing to
identify Stewart because the former justice is dead. Stewart died in
1985 at age 70.
   ``I'm revealing his name now, for the first time, because it's
worth showing that there really are sources, people do talk,''
Woodward said.
   ``It's not some reporter's imagination or some letter that comes
in the mail with no address, typed on a standard typewriter,''
Woodward said. ``You have relationships, you nurture them and they
pay off.''
   Woodward said he met Stewart at a party in the spring of 1977.
``The Brethren'' was published in 1979.
   Although Woodward was willing to identify his main source for
``The Brethren,'' which he wrote with reporter Scott Armstrong, he
told Playboy he was not ready to identify ``Deep Throat.''
   ``Deep Throat'' was the key informer Woodward and Carl Bernstein
used for their Pulitzer Prize-winning articles uncovering the 1972
Watergate scandal in Post and for their subsequent best-selling
book, ``All the President's Men.''
   ``As you know, I'm not going to discuss the identity of Deep
Throat or any other of my confidential sources who are still
alive,'' Woodward said.
   Woodward said Stewart turned out to have ``real intellectual
disdain'' for former Chief Justice Warren Burger and former Attorney
General John Mitchell, both appointees of President Richard Nixon.
   Woodward said Stewart's animosities became clear as he worked on
the book, and were probably the reason Stewart allowed him to have a
behind-the-scenes look at the high court.
   ``What also came across ... was Stewart's contempt for Richard
Nixon,'' Woodward said. ``He felt that what had happened with Carl's
(Bernstein) and my Watergate reporting was very important for the
country and for journalism and for subduing this rightist movement
in America, tamping it down and saying `Whoa.' The guys who had
proclaimed they were going to fight crime turned out to be the
criminals.''
</TEXT>
