<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Philippines-Explosion     12-30 0193</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Explosion,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>11 Killed In Explosion At Illegal Fireworks Factory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOCAUE, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eleven people were killed and 20
others injured when an explosion blew up a house where illegal
fireworks were being made, police said today.
   About 10 people were making firecrackers and sparklers late
Thursday in a house in this town 15 miles north of Manila when two
barrels of powder ignited, destroying the residence and four others
in the neighborhood.
   The explosion, heard several miles away, triggered a fire that
damaged five other homes before authorities could extinguish the
blaze.
   Police said five of the dead, including three who were
dismembered, were killed instantly, while the rest died in nearby
hospitals.
   Such explosions are annual occurrences in Bulacan province, the
center of the country's flourishing but illegal fireworks industry.
Two similar accidents killed 15 people last year.
   ``I am appalled by this kind of destruction,'' said Bulacan Gov.
Roberto Pagdanganan, who visited the scene early today.
   Pagdanganan said the explosion occurred only about an hour after
he warned Bocaue authorities to crack down on the industry, outlawed
in the mid-1960s after a series of deadly explosions and fires.
