<DOCNO> AP881230-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0745EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Crash-Lab     12-30 0471</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Crash-Lab,0484</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>High-Security Defense Establishment Site Of Pan Am Tests</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAGGIE JACKSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When baggage and wreckage from the Pan Am crash was
sent to Fort Halstead for forensic tests, some experts said they
believed even more strongly that a bomb destroyed the plane.
   They knew that Fort Halstead meant the Ministry of Defense's
leading bomb experts would be entering the investigation into the
Dec. 21 crash of the Boeing 747.
   Their work at the country's main center for developing explosives
and armaments proved crucial when it was determined that a bomb
caused the crash, and could help determine the bombers as well,
experts said Thursday.
   ``The tests were crucial in clinching the cause, i.e., that it
was a bomb,'' said a spokesman from the Department of Transport,
whose Air Accident Investigation Branch is heading the crash
investigation.
   Working closely with the Department of Transport, mainly civilian
experts at Fort Halstead will continue tests on wreckage from the
plane, he said.
   Fort Halstead is the high-security headquarters of the Royal
Armament Research and Development Establishment, the government's
center for research on defense projects ranging from new weapons to
bridges and computers.
   A Ministry of Defense spokesman, speaking on condition of
anonymity, refused to comment in detail about the explosives experts
among the 2,500 civilians and 200 military at Fort Halstead and
three other sites operated by the establishment.
   Explosives work centers around Fort Halstead, near Sevenoaks in
Kent about 20 miles southeast of London.
   ``It's a high-security installation, which is very expert in
matters of explosives and armaments research,'' said Paul Wilkinson,
a professor and terrorism expert at Aberdeen University in Scotland.
   ``Their reputation is extremely high,'' he said in an interview,
adding that Fort Halstead experts would have worked closely with
experts in the Scottish town of Lockerbie, which bore the brunt of
the crash, to get a ``broader picture'' of the crash.
   David Learmount, air transport editor of the respected aviation
journal Flight International, said that when investigators announced
they were taking a suitcase and pieces of wreckage to Fort Halstead
for tests, he knew they were looking for ``symptoms of an
explosion.''
   Investigators said the tests found residues of explosives in two
parts of a ``luggage pallet'' _ the metal rack in the baggage hold
in which luggage is stored. But they said they still didn't know
where the bomb was planted and how it was brought aboard.
   Ian Geldard, head of research at the privately funded Institute
For The Study of Terrorism in London, said establishment experts
would probably next try to find out where the bomb was planted and
what type of bomb was used as a clue to identifying the bombers.
   ``Many terrorist groups have a particular type of favorite
explosive they use,'' he said.
</TEXT>
