<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Israel-Bombs     12-30 0273</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Bombs,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes Near Newsstand, Ultra-Orthodox Jews Suspected</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded today near a newsstand in a Tel
Aviv suburb, and police said they suspected ultra-Orthodox militants
were trying to block the sale of papers they consider pornographic.
   The bomb exploded in Ramat Gan, causing no injuries but minor
damage to a store, and police demolition experts dismantled four
bombs in nearby Bnei Brak, police spokesman Dalia Gilad said.
   She said different types of bombs were used, but that at least
one was a firebomb. Israel radio described it as a firebomb equipped
with a timer.
   Gilad said no group claimed responsibility, but police suspect it
was the work of ultra-Orthodox militants.
   ``The bombs were all found in places where secular newspapers are
sold,'' Gilad said.
   Ultra-Orthodox Jews object to pictures that show unmarried men
and women together, or women in revealing clothing.
   The deputy mayor of Bnai Brak, Shmuel Weinberg, said the
attempted bombings were the work of ``disturbed people'' and were
not sanctioned by the religious community.
   ``According to our past experience, when the police did catch
somebody, they were disturbed people who saw the bombings as some
kind of a religious commandment,'' he said.
   Last August, five bombs were placed near newsstands in Bnei Brak.
Three of the bombs exploded, causing minor damage but no injuries,
and two were dismantled by police.
   The ultra-Orthodox Agudat Israel party condemned the latest
bombing attempts, saying they violated Jewish scriptures.
   ``Violence is not the way of the Torah,'' the party said in a
statement. ``We are convinced that it was done by radicals rejected
by the Orthodox public.''
</TEXT>
