<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0752EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LastGoodbye     12-30 0523</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Last Goodbye,0539</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grandfather Kills Handicapped Grandson, Then Himself</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debbie Day says her father was apparently
trying to relieve her of the hardship of caring for a handicapped
child when he killed his 2-year-old grandson, then took his own life.
   ``He was the kind of person who didn't want to be burdened in his
own life and didn't want me to be burdened by my child,'' Ms. Day
said Thursday.
   The Lewis County sheriff's department found the bodies of
75-year-old Hollis Day and little Dylan on Wednesday night in Day's
locked Jeep Waggoner. Grandfather and grandson had been missing
since Tuesday morning.
   The bodies were found on wooded, family-owned land 50 miles from
the Day home. The gun lay near the bodies. Both had been shot in the
head.
   Ms. Day said she began worrying a few hours after finding a note
that read, ``Gramps and Dylan have gone bye-bye together.''
   ``He was having dreams, you know, of he and my son floating off
into the air and reliving all these things in the hereafter _ the
... hunting and skiing and fishing trips,'' the 40-year-old woman
recalled.
   Her father had greeted her with an extra warm hug when she woke
up Tuesday morning, and told her that she was a wonderful girl and
mother, Ms. Day said.
   She asked him to take care of Dylan while she packed up Christmas
gifts to head home for Portland, Ore., and then learned the two had
taken off together in Day's vehicle, Dylan hastily wrapped in a coat
and hat over his pajamas.
   Ms. Day, Dylan and the boy's father, Al Berreth, had been
visiting her parents.
   She found the note and, a few hours later, the tenor of its words
suddenly merged with what her father had been saying in recent
months, and it hit her: ``Bye-bye'' meant eternity.
   She called police, indicating a suicide was possible.
   ``At this point, the evidence appears consistent with a
homicide-suicide theory,'' Lewis County Sheriff Bill Logan said.
   Day, the retired president of a clothing company, had been
scheduled for cataract surgery Thursday, and he was ``very very
disturbed about my child's condition,'' she said.
   Dylan, her only child, suffered from a mild form of cerebral
palsy, and was considered developmentally disabled, Ms. Day said.
   ``When you have a handicapped child, they're a little bit more
work and he thought that having a child like that would be a total
altering of my lifestlye that he didn't want to see imposed upon a
daughter that he loved dearly. But it wasn't in my wildest dreams
that he'd do this.''
   But her son was `` doing just fine,'' in a hospital therapy
program, she said.
   ``He was beginning to walk and talk... He was a gregarious,
outgoing, happy, loving, affectionate child. He was a beautiful
child. ... He would have been walking eventually. ... He was not
retarded _ he was a slow learner.''
   With more sadness than anger, she said her father was probably
just trying to help, but had been losing his ability to think
rationally.
</TEXT>
