<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EgyptianPaintings     12-30 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Egyptian Paintings,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boston Museum To Return Purloined Tomb Artifacts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Boston Museum of Fine Arts is returning to
Egypt some fragments of nine ancient paintings because curators have
concluded the art was stolen from a 15th century B.C. tomb.
   The museum bought the paintings from an art dealer in Amsterdam,
the Netherlands, in 1978 for an undisclosed sum and they are not
considered archaeologically significant, museum officials said
Thursday.
   The artifacts probably will be returned in the spring after a
representative of the Egyptian Antiquities Service comes to Boston
to supervise packing and shipping, said Museum Director Alan
Shestack.
   Shestack ordered research into the paintings last year, after the
museum's Egyptian art department expressed suspicions about the
legality of their origin.
   The museum decided to return the artifacts voluntarily because
they apparently were stolen, smuggled out of Egypt and sold into the
art world, museum officials said.
   The fragments came from the Theban tomb of Minnakht, an official
in the period of Thutmose III, and date to 1450-1420 B.C., said
Timothy Kendall, the museum's acting curator of Egyptian and ancient
Near Eastern art. The tomb is located in the Nobles Tombs at Luxor
in southern Egypt.
   Thutmose was considered the greatest pharaoh of the 18th dynasty,
known for conquests that extended Egypt to the banks of the
Euphrates River and the fourth cataract of the Nile River in what is
now the Sudan.
   The fragments depict men and women bearing offerings, but most of
the figures are only partly preserved, Kendall said. The largest
fragment is about 1 foot long and 10 inches high.
   The Amsterdam dealer who sold the objects to the museum has since
died, Shestack said.
</TEXT>
