<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CaveMarathon     12-30 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cave Marathon,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman To Remain in Cave Five Months in Experiment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARLSBAD, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Italian researcher will spend the first
five months of 1989 _ the time required to fly to Mars _ in a cave.
   Stefania Folini, 27, a member of a research team based in Ancona,
Italy, plans to descend Sunday into Lost Cave in southeast Carlsbad
in an experiment designed to simulate a space flight.
   ``What that does to you psychologically and physically is not
known,'' said Ron Kerbo, a cave specialist for nearby Carlsbad
Caverns National Park.
   Folini is a member of Pioneer Frontier Exploration and Research
Group of Ancona, said Jim Goodbar, cave specialist with the U.S.
Bureau of Land Management in Carlsbad.
   The Italian group will run the experiment with the help of NASA,
officials said. A team of four doctors, based in a mobile home at
the cave entrance, will monitor the woman using the computer,
microphones, a video camera and brain-wave sensors, Goodbar said.
   The cave's environment is constant, like that of a spaceship,
Goodbar said. The humidity always hovers just under 100 percent, and
the temperature remains at 69 degrees. The cave's central chamber is
about 150 feet by 30 feet, with a ceiling about 12 feet high.
</TEXT>
