<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PoliceTest     12-30 0256</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Police Test,0263</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Women Score Better Than Men On Revamped Police Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Women for the first time outperformed men on a
fitness test required for entrance into the Denver police academy,
following court-ordered changes that placed greater emphasis on
flexibility than raw strength.
   Denver Civil Service Commission records showed 77 percent of the
female candidates passed the fitness exam between August and
October, compared o 66 percent of the men.
   The test was revised in May 1987 after 75 female recruits who
failed the old exam charged it put too much emphasis on upper-body
strength and did not reflect the physical demands of police work.
The new test implemented as part of an out-of-court settlement
stresses flexibility and endurance.
   Men and women also must meet different standards and are measured
against national averages for people of the same age and gender.
   The new tests were administered between August and October to 13
women and 113 men vying for 25 openings at the police academy.
   Two women will be among the 25 recruits to start at the academy
Jan. 15, said Ed Gietl, executive director of the commission.
   Under the old fitness test, women failed an average of 67 percent
of the time.
   In approving the settlement between the city and the 75 female
recruits in May 1987, U.S. District Judge Alfred Arraj ordered the
department to revise the test.
   The new exam, developed by the Cooper Institute in Dallas,
includes a 1{-mile run, a bench and leg press, sit-ups and other
exercises.
</TEXT>
