<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-BankRobbery     12-30 0323</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Bank Robbery,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Masked Man Drives Off With Armored Car, $2.5 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A masked man jumped into a bank delivery van today
and drove it away, dragging a guard for 50 yards and fleeing with
more than $2.5 million in Japanese currency, police said.
   The heist outside the Taiyo Kobe Bank branch in the western
Japanese city of Suma was the second-biggest cash robbery in
Japanese history, officials said.
   The thief got into the van after it pulled up to the bank and the
crew prepared to make a delivery of cash, checks and promissory
notes, Hyogo Prefectural Police said.
   Police said the middle-aged man was familiar with the locks used
in the vehicle, and that a man of the same general build had
recently been seen loitering near the bank.
   ``The driver stepped out of the van for a second to close the
rear door ... and the man jumped in and started the engine,'' a
police official said.
   ``When the driver heard the sound of the engine, he rushed to the
driver's seat and grabbed the steering wheel, but the robber pushed
him back and drove away,'' the official said, speaking on condition
of anonymity.
   The driver, Shigetoshi Oe, 53, held on to the window of the
vehicle and was dragged for about 50 yards. Police said he was not
injured.
   The van, owned by Nippon Express Co., was found about two hours
later abandoned in a grassy parking lot less than a mile from the
bank with four empty cash boxes inside, the police official said.
   The van had carried 320 million yen, or about $2.54 million, and
about $1.4 million in checks and promissory notes, police said.
   It was the second-largest cash robbery in Japanese history,
police said.
   In 1986, a group of men wearing motorcycle helmets drove off in a
cash delivery truck containing 333 million yen, about $2.64 million
at current exchange rates.
</TEXT>
