<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines-Rebels     12-30 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines-Rebels,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fourteen Killed In Insurgency Flareup Before Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At least 11 soldiers and three
communist insurgents were killed in scattered clashes between two
holiday cease-fires, military reports said today.
   Reports released by military headquarters in Manila said six
soldiers were killed and six wounded when a band of rebels ambushed
an army patrol Thursday in Nueva Ecija province, 50 miles north of
Manila.
   On Samar island, 250 miles southeast of the capital, hundreds of
New People's Army guerrillas attacked a military detachment in the
town of Arteche early Thursday, killing at least five soldiers,
another report said.
   It said an undetermined number of civilian militiamen also were
killed in the fighting, which lasted two hours.
   The reports said that in both clashes, the rebels suffered
undetermined casualties.
   Three rebels were killed in Luzon island's southeastern Albay
province on Thursday, a report from military officials in the area
said. It gave no details.
   The latest fatalities brought to at least 31 the number of people
killed in fighting throughout the Philippines this week. Earlier
clashes, most allegedly initiated by the rebels, occurred on
Mindanao and Negros islands.
   President Corazon Aquino last week declared two 48-hour
cease-fires for Christmas and New Year's and the New People's Army
followed with a similar announcement. The New Year's cease-fire was
to go into effect at midnight.
