<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Sudan 1stLd-Writethru a0498 12-30 0662</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0498,0680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Reported Killed in Shooting; Airport Reopens</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with demonstrations and strike
continuing. Pickup 6th graf pvs, ``Two news...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMED OSMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunfire killed two people and wounded 28
during demonstrations over steep price increases and demands for an
end to Sudan's civil war, a senior official said today.
   Demonstrators took to the streets for a fourth consecutive day
today, even though the government canceled the price increases
because of the protests, and a general strike continued to paralyze
much of the country.
   Khartoum Commissioner Fatih Abdoun reported the shooting
incident, saying ``an unidentified gunman'' caused the casualties
when he opened fire on protesters near Cabinet offices Thursday.
Abdoun gave no details.
   Other reports conflicted with his account but did not mention
casualties.
   ``The action in the streets is taking on a definite
anti-government flavor,'' said a Western diplomat who closely
follows Sudanese affairs from Addis Ababa, Ethiopia's capital.
   ``It looks like the government is in serious trouble,'' he told
The Associated Press in a telephone interview. ``There is a lot of
talk about a coup attempt coming out of Khartoum ... There is
complete political chaos.''
   A crisis caused by an air traffic controllers' strike appeared to
have ended today. An air traffic controller in Cairo, Egypt, said
Khartoum International Airport, closed since Wednesday night as part
of the general strike, was reopened around 11 a.m.
   Two news dispatches received in Cairo on Thursday reported
shooting near the Cabinet offices. The timing of the reports
indicated there were two separate shootings. Neither mentioned
casualties.
   Egypt's Middle East News Agency, in an early afternoon dispatch,
quoted the official Sudan News Agency as saying Sudanese police
opened fire on demonstrators when they refused to disperse after
being told that an emergency Cabinet session had rolled back the
price increases.
   Reports said demonstrators also were chanting slogans calling for
government action to implement a tentative peace plan.
   In Baghdad, Iraq, the official Iraqi News Agency said in a
Khartoum-datelined report Thursday night that shooting occurred
shortly after dark in the Sudanese capital, ``especially near the
headquarters of the Council of Ministers.''
   Commissioner Abdoun's version of the shooting conflicted with the
Sudanese agency's report on the source of gunfire, and it was
impossible to tell whether he and the Iraqi news agency referred to
the same incident.
   Another version came from the British Foreign Office in London,
which based its reports on the Sudanese Ministry of Information.
   It said one person was reported injured Thursday in ``generally
peaceful'' large-scale demonstrations in Khartoum, some at the
university. Sudanese police used tear gas and ``warning shots'' to
disperse the protesters, it said.
   Strikes and demonstrations were prompted by a government decree
on Monday increasing sugar prices by 500 percent and cigarettes by
50 percent, and imposing a 15 percent sales tax on all commodities.
   Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi's Cabinet met in emergency session
Thursday morning and revoked the price increases.
   The Cabinet also considered the Democratic Unionist Party's
withdrawal from the governing coalition Wednesday night. The
Unionists held the second-largest number of ministerial and
parliamentary seats after Mahdi's Umma Party.
   The party quit the government to protest the price increases and
Mahdi's failure to act on a tentative peace accord that a Unionist
leader negotiated last month with rebel leader John Garang in Addis
Ababa.
   Mahdi did not submit the accord to the Cabinet or the Constituent
Assembly, Sudan's parliament, for endorsement because he feared that
would prompt the fundamentalist National Islamic Front to leave his
coalition.
   The front, led by Mahdi's brother-in-law, Attorney General Hassan
Turabi, opposed the peace accord's stipulation that Sharia, Islam's
legal and ethical code, be suspended during peace talks and that
alternatives be considered.
   The mainly Christian and animist southern rebels demand
revocation of Sharia, imposed in 1983 by President Gaafar Nimeiri 18
months before he was overthrown in a 1985 military coup.
</TEXT>
