<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0920EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAsian 2ndLd-Writethru   12-30 0732</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Asian, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0515,0747</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Asian Leaders Meet At Hillside Retreat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to UPDATE with second meeting, comments.
Pickup 4th graf pvs, ``Gandhi spoke...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Benazir Bhutto and
Prime Minister Rajiv Ganhdi of India held their second private
meeting today as they sought to end four decades of friction between
their countries.
   Sources said the meetings, which have overshadowed a summit
involving seven south Asian nations, have been amicable and
productive.
   ``They're getting along famously,'' an Indian source said.
``Their meetings are going well,'' said another Indian official.
Both demanded anonymity.
   The leaders met following a regular summit session with the
leaders of Bangladesh, Bhutan, the Maldives, Nepal and Sri Lanka.
   The fourth annual summit of the South Asian Association for
Regional Cooperation comes only four weeks after Ms. Bhutto took
office following Pakistan's first free election in 11 years. The
summit has kindled hopes of closer ties between India and Pakistan,
historically antagonistic nations.
   Gandhi spoke warmly of Ms. Bhutto in his speech at the opening
session Thursday night.
   ``I am particularly happy to be here when the people of Pakistan
have elected you, Madam Prime Minister, to lead your great country
forward to peace and prosperity, rooted in democracy. ... We rejoice
in the prospect of friendship and cooperation between India and
Pakistan,'' Gandhi said.
   After the 2{-hour opening session, Gandhi and his wife, Sonia,
met privately over dinner with Ms. Bhutto and her husband,
businessman Asif Zardari.
   Gandhi and Ms. Bhutto's session this afternoon was to last up to
two hours _ much longer than those she scheduled with other visiting
leaders. Gandhi and Ms. Bhutto are to meet again Saturday after the
summit ends.
   Although Ms. Bhutto did not refer to Gandhi in her inaugural
speech, she said last week that continued animosity between India
and Pakistan did not serve the interest of their peoples.
   The two countries have fought three wars since they were
partitioned in 1947 upon the demise of British colonial India.
   Relations have further been strained by a border dispute over
Kashmir, which was split between Pakistan and India when the
subcontinent was divided. India claims part of the territory in
Pakistan.
   Protesters have demonstrated daily in Islamabad against India's
claim. Sardar Qayyum Khan, president of the Pakistan-controlled part
of Kashmir, said the protests ``have mobilized Kashmiris on this
side of the cease-fire line and have shown our integrity and
solidarity with those suffering on the other side.''
   Other areas of friction between the nations include fears of each
other's nuclear capabilities and claims that Pakistan has supported
Sikh separatists who have killed 2,400 people this year in India's
border state of Punjab. Pakistan has denied the charges.
   So far, Pakistani and Indian officials have declined to comment
on the prospects of Ms. Bhutto visiting India soon. She has said her
first foreign trips will be to China and Saudi Arabia. She is
expected to make a pilgrimage to Mecca, site of Islam's holiest
shrine, in January, but no date has been set for a trip to Beijing.
   Today's summit session was at Daman-e-Koh, a white-domed retreat
on a hillside overlooking Islamabad.
   Police with rifles stood at intervals of 20 feet to 150 feet.
Other uniformed and plainclothes guards stood in clusters, on rocky
outcrops and among the trees and thickets.
   The security was a reminder of the region's potential for
violence.
   Both Gandhi and Sri Lankan President Junius R. Jayewardene have
escaped unhurt from assassination attempts in their capitals, while
Maldivian President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom was the target of an
unsuccessful coup less than two months ago.
   Another participant, former Gen. Hussain Muhammad Ershad of
Bangladesh, assumed power in a bloodless coup in 1982, although a
yes-or-no referendum subsequently proclaimed him president. The
other summit participants, King Birendra of Nepal and King Jigme
Singhe Wangchuk of Bhutan, rule through hereditary succession.
   Ms. Bhutto's avenue to power through popular election followed
the death of President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq, who in 1977 overthrew
her father, Prime Minister Zulfikar Ali Bhutto. Bhutto was
subsequently convicted in a murder case and executed. Zia, U.S.
Ambassador Arnold L. Raphel and 35 others were killed Aug. 17 in an
explosion that destroyed their aircraft over Pakistan. Officials
blamed sabotage but could not say who was responsible for downing
the plane.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881230-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0936EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Taiwan     12-30 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Taiwan,0375</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>China Calls for Direct Talks with Taiwan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Chinese official today marked the 10th
anniversary of a Chinese appeal for peaceful reunification with
Taiwan by renewing China's proposal for direct talks with Taiwan's
Nationalist government.
   ``We hold that the Communist Party and the Kumomintang
(Nationalists) should establish contacts and start negotiations at
an early date on the basis of equality,'' Vice Premier Wu Xueqian
said. ``We can talk about the reunification of the country, or carry
out consultations on the concrete issues concerning the relations
between the two sides.''
   Wu was speaking at a forum of 300 senior party and government
leaders held to commemorate China's ``message to Taiwan
compatriots'' issued on Jan. 1, 1979.
   The message called for the peaceful reunification of Taiwan with
the mainland and proposed direct transportation and postal links as
a first step toward easing tensions between the two nations.
   The official Xinhua News Agency, in a report on the forum, said
the 1979 message signified a historic turning point in relations
between the mainland and Taiwan.
   China has since then called for direct political and trade
contacts and has said Taiwan can keep its current political and
economic system if it rejoins the mainland.
   The Nationalists, who fled to Taiwan after their defeat to the
communists in 1949, have rejected all proposals for direct contacts
with the mainland. However, in the past year the Taiwan government
has eased travel and trade restrictions with the mainland.
   More than 400,000 Taiwan residents have traveled to the mainland
in the past year, and indirect trade is estimated at $2.4 billion in
1988, up from $1.5 billion in 1987.
   ``Such changes are in accordance with people's wishes and the
overall tendency of this historic development is therefore
irreversible,'' Wu said.
   He also expressed concern about Taiwanese advocates of
independence and those on the island who are in favor of ``two
Chinas'' or ``dual recognition'' concepts.
   Reunification is in the interests of both sides, he said. ``This
will not only help the whole country to quickly become prosperous,
but will also help maintain sustained development on the island,
which can then enjoy the prestige of the great motherland.''
</TEXT>
