<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0957EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i BC-Yugoslavia-Glance     12-30 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Yugoslavia-Glance,0442</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugoslavia At A Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Yugoslavia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some facts about Yugoslavia:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE LAND _ Yugoslavia covers 98,766 square miles, slightly larger
than Wyoming. It a federation of six republics: Serbia, including
the autonomous provinces of Vojvodina and Kosovo; Croatia, Slovenia,
Bosnia-Hercegovina, Macedonia and Montenegro. The capital is
Belgrade.
   Yugoslavia occupies the western part of the Balkan peninsula,
with a long coast on the Adriatic Sea. About half the country is
mountainous. A rich plain in the north and northeast, drained by the
Danube, is the most fertile area.
   Yugoslavia is bordered by Austria, Italy and Hungary in the
north, Romania and Bulgaria in the east, and Greece and Albania in
the south.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE PEOPLE _ Yugoslavia's population of just over 23 million
includes about 30 different nationalities. Serbs account for about
36 percent and the Croats for about 20 percent of the popoluation.
Other Slav groups are the Slovenes, 8 percent; and the Montenegrins,
3 percent. Ethnic Albanians, who live mostly in the tense province
of Kosovo, make up 9 percent of the population. An ethnic category
known as Moslems accounts for another 9 percent. Yugoslavia's ethnic
diversity has been a source of strife for centuries.
   The official languages are Serbo-Croatian, Slovene, and
Macedonian. An estimated 41 percent of Yugoslavs are Orthodox, 32
percent Roman Catholics and 12 percent are Muslims.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   THE ECONOMY: After President Josip Broz Tito's death in 1980, the
economy has deteriorated sharply, revealing the shortcomings of the
``self-management'' system officially giving workers the say in
running enterprises. In practice, Communist-dominated state planning
and widespread corruption have caused serious problems. Yugoslavia
now has a $21 billion foreign debt, 250 percent inflation and 15
percent unemployment. Mounting worker discontent has led to more
than 1,000 strikes in 1988.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   HISTORY: For about five centuries, much of the land that is
modern Yugoslavia was under Ottoman rule, shaken off in 19th century
uprisings. In December 1918, a Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and
Slovenes, including Bosnia Hercegovina, was formed. During World War
II, the Nazi invaders were fought both by royalists and Communist
partisans under Tito, who then became Yugoslavia's undisputed
postwar leader. Tito broke with Soviet dictator Josef Stalin in
1948, and Yugoslavia became a nonaligned communist country. Some of
its present problems are attributed to the system bequeathed by
Tito, including annual rotation of key offices and a weak federal
authority. The state-run press and Yugoslavs themselves have become
increasingly outspoken and liberal as the mounting social and
economic problems have dented the authority of the Communist Party.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881230-0078 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1002EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Yugoslavia 3rdLd-Writethru   12-30 0700</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Yugoslavia, 3rd Ld-Writethru,a0511,0722</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yugoslav Premier And Cabinet Resign Over Econonic Crisis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with potential effects of
resignation, government's next move, more details. Edits to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DUSAN STOJANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Premier Branko Mikulic and his entire
Cabinet quit today in the first resignation by a federal government
since the Communist Party took power after World War II.
   Mikulic told Parliament he stepped down because it refused on
Wednesday to pass an economic law needed to ensure continued support
from the International Monetary Fund for the debt-ridden country.
   The resignation could signal further liberalization of
Yugoslavia's one-party system as the ethnically divided country
struggles to solve unprecedented social and economic woes.
   Mikulic represented a hard-line faction within the party and his
resignation indicated that more reform-oriented forces are gaining
the upper hand in the party leadership.
   But the resignations also represent an attempt to shift blame for
the crisis away from the Communist Party to the premier and his
31-member Cabinet.
   Parliament and the nine-member federal presidency now will likely
consult on who will form a new government.
   In his speech, broadcast live on Belgrade television, Mikulic
refused to accept blame for the country's economic problems,
including a $21 billion foreign debt, 15 percent unemployment and
annual inflation of 250 percent.
   After the 35-minute speech, Parliament refused to take up an
option to discuss the resignation, in effect accepting it.
   Mikulic said Yugoslavia's economic problems were inherited ``from
past decades'' and that it was unrealistic for his government ``to
resolve them in only two and half years.''
   Mikulic began a four-year term after succeeding Milka Planinc as
premier in May 1986. ``It is more honorable for the government to
resign than to be blamed for all of the country's ills,'' Mikulic
said.
   In recent days, leading politicians criticized the government's
economic policies and state-run dailies had called for Mikulic's
immediate replacement.
   ``Poisonous arrows are being aimed at the government,'' Mikulic
said.
   He said the Cabinet decided to resign after Parliament on
Wednesday refused to pass a law that would have imposed curbs on
public spending. Mikulic said the law was needed to ensure continued
support from the International Monetary Fund.
   He told Parliament on Wednesday that agency insisted on austerity
measures limiting public spending before agreeing in June to grant
Yugoslavia a one-year standby credit of $416 million. About $260
million of that credit has been used, according to official
estimates.
   The loan was crucial to help Yugoslavia meet payments on its
foreign debt and reach separate agreements for loan rescheduling
with other Western banks and governments.
   The Communist Party daily Borba on Thursday quoted an
unidentified Cabinet minister as saying Parliament's refusal to pass
the law ``destroys the standby arrangement with the IMF...''
   In a bid to overcome the deteriorating situation, Parliament
adopted a new law Thursday to stimulate private enterprise,
liberalizing rules for establishing private businesses. The law was
adopted ``for the first step toward market economy,'' the state news
agency said.
   Yugoslavia has had a record number of strikes this year, with
workers protesting low wages and declining living standards.
   Mikulic survived a potential vote of confidence in May, when
deputies from the liberal northern republic of Slovenia and from
Croatia failed to gather support from the other four Yugoslav
republics to vote out the government.
   Mikulic's reputation has been tarnished further by a corruption
scandal involving hundreds of officials in his native republic of
Bosnia-Hercegovina.
   Yugoslavia also has been wracked by unrest among its various
ethnic groups.
   Mikulic is an economist who served as a presiding member of the
Yugoslav Communist Party in 1978 and 1979 under the late leader
Josip Broz Tito.
   Although he rejected blame for Yugoslavia's economic problems,
observers said his decision to step down was at least partly
intended to placate Yugoslavia's 23 million citizens, who are
increasingly angered by falling living standards.
   Although Mikulic has been accused of incompetence, Yugoslavia's
complex federal system also has hindered a solution to its economic
problems.
   The need for unanimity by the country's six constituent republics
and two autonomous provinces on all federal matters means that key
decisions are often watered down to ineffective compromises.
</TEXT>
