<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TowingIndictments     12-30 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Towing Indictments,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Head of Police Auto Theft Unit Among 18 Indicted in Towing Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six current or former police officers were among 18
people indicted in a towing scam that allegedly bilked at least 600
people from 1982 to 1987, authorities said.
   Police Sgt. William H. Kelley Jr., 51, chief of the department's
auto theft unit, was charged with six counts of conspiracy, perjury
and writing a false police report, according to indictments returned
Thursday by a Suffolk County grand jury.
   The suspects allegedly participated in several schemes to tow
legally and illegally parked cars and overcharge owners when they
came to retrieve them, said David Rodman, a spokesman for District
Attorney Newman Flanagan.
   The grand jury handed up 1,500 charges in the indictments, which
capped a two-year investigation.
   Police Commissioner Francis X. Roache vowed to continue probing
police corruption.
   ``The public should be outraged that a group of people conspired
to literally take 600 to 800 cars off the street with no authority,
in total violation of the rules and regulations,'' he said. ``I
think it's time to look at the whole towing industry.''
   Also indicted were three other police officers, one Metropolitan
District Commission police officer, one former police captain, two
employees of the city's abandoned car division, two former
inspectors at the state Registry of Motor Vehicles, a special agent
with the National Auto Theft Bureau and the owners of two city
garages.
   The defendants face charges including larceny, concealing stolen
motor vehicles, perjury, conspiracy and insurance fraud.
   Kelley and Officer William R. Cantin, 40, who was indicted on 535
charges, have been suspended without pay, police spokesman Jim
Jordan said.
   Two other indicted officers, Peter Doherty, 47, and John Ulrich,
44, were placed on administrative leave pending a departmental
hearing, Jordan said.
   Rodman said one alleged scheme profited from the different
charges levied on cars towed by police and those towed by the
Registry of Motor Vehicles, which charges more to drivers to
retrieve cars. He said police would tow a car that was parked
illegally but the defendants would tell the owner the car had been
towed by the registry ``and pick up the extra money.''
   Another scheme, Rodman said, would be to tow a legally parked
car, and wait several weeks after the owner reported it stolen to
collect daily storage charges _ often up to $600.
   The indictment does not say how much money was lost.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
