<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel     12-30 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel,0493</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Palestinians Killed, West Bank Schools Closed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli troops shot and killed three
Palestinians in the occupied Gaza Strip over the last two days, the
army said today.
   An army spokesman also said 1,194 Palestinian schools in the West
Bank will be shut for a week because of increased student violence.
   Two of the deaths in Gaza took place Thursday night in the Gaza
City neighborhood of Zeitoun, the spokesman said. He said the two
Palestinians were shot when they tried to escape after being ordered
out of their house. The two were suspected of throwing firebombs, he
said.
   ``They were ordered to come out,'' the spokesman said. ``Then
they tried to escape and were shot.'' He said one suspect died at
the scene, another died in an Israeli hospital and a third was
captured unharmed.
   The violence continued today with one Palestinian killed and nine
wounded in Gaza as army-imposed curfews confined at least 160,000
Palestinians to their homes in refugee camps and towns.
   An Arab reporter said the army broke up a protest that followed
noon Moslem prayers in the Sheikh Radwan neighborhhod of Gaza City.
He said soldiers used clubs, rubber bullets and live ammunition.
   Abdel Khalim Behid, 22, was shot in the lung during the
disturbance and died at Gaza City's Shifa Hospital, hospital
officials said. Five Arabs were wounded by gunshots, and a
4-year-old boy was hit in the head with a rubber bullet. The army
confirmed Behid was killed by army gunfire, and that four
Palestinians were wounded in the Sheikh Radwan clash.
   ``After prayers, they raised the Palestinian flag and threw
stones,'' the army spokesman said. He said troops opened fire to
disperse the crowd.
   Elsewhere in Gaza City, three Palestinians were wounded, among
them a 35-year-old woman hit in the abdomen, Arab doctors said. In
the Jabalya refugee camp, a teenager was wounded.
   The deaths raised to at least 342 the number of Palestinians
killed in the year-old rebellion against the 21-year occupation of
the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Fourteen Israelis have also been
killed.
   In the West Bank, Israel's military administration announced a
weeklong closure of all Palestinian schools because of ``numerous
incidents of disturbances by students,'' a spokesman said.
   The measure, which takes effect Saturday, prevents about 300,000
Palestinian school students from attending classes.
   Schools in the West Bank were closed by the army Feb. 3 for
nearly 10 months. Authorities gradually reopened the 1,194 West Bank
schools in December but made studies conditional on a halt to
student violence.
   Army officials say schools often become focal points for violent
demonstrations in the uprising. For that reason, four universities
and 16 junior colleges in the West Bank have been shut indefinitely.
   Palestinians have protested the closure, with educators arguing
that students were losing the discipline for study.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
