<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1044EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SouthAfrica     12-30 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-South Africa,0415</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Right-Wing Official To Lose Car Rental Franchise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A car rental company said today
it will take a franchise away from a member of a right-wing town
council that has reinstated hard-line segregation laws.
   Louis de Waal, executive director of the South Africa's Budget
Rent-a-Car, said in a statement that his company would sever its
ties in February with Billy Olivier, operator of a Budget franchise
in Brakpan.
   Olivier is a member of the far-right Conservative Party, which
won control of councils in Brakpan and dozens of other towns in
municipal elections on Oct. 26.
   The councils in Brakpan and Boksburg, both industrial towns on
the eastern edge of the greater Johannesburg region, have reinstated
``whites only'' status at parks and other public facilities that had
been opened to all races in recent years.
   The actions have been widely condemned, not only by
anti-apartheid groups but also by the government. However, the
governing National Party has given no indication it will repeal the
Separate Amenities Act, which allows racial segregation of local
facilities.
   ``We do not believe that Mr. Olivier's views and those of his
Conservative Party colleagues represent the outlook of the silent
majority of Brakpan voters,'' said de Waal.
   ``While the separate amenities legislation that is being enforced
was put in place by the government, it appears these measures were
dying an evolutionary death until the stance taken by the
Conservative Party.''
   In another development, the Rev. Allan Hendrickse, a politician
who has irked the government with his defiant tactics, says he has
accepted an invitation to attend the inauguration of President-elect
George Bush.
   Hendrickse told the annual congress of his Labor Party on
Thursday that he would attend the inauguration during a three-week
trip to the United States. He will miss the opening of South
Africa's 1989 parliamentary session on Feb. 3.
   The Labor Party controls the mixed-race chamber of Parliament,
which also has chambers for whites and for Asians but excludes the
black majority.
   Anti-apartheid activists criticized the Labor Party for deciding
to join the newly expanded Parliament in 1984, but in the past 18
months Hendrickse has taken an increasingly confrontational stance
toward the government.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
