<1ST_LINE>r a PM-GunmanHostages     12-30 0244</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gunman Hostages,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gunman Releases Seven Hostages; One Woman Remains Inside Beauty
Salon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE RUFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gunman who took eight hostages in a beauty
salon during a bungled robbery attempt had released all but one
woman today as police sealed off a three-block area, authorities
said.
   No shots were fired and no injuries were reported. The gunman
negotiated undisclosed demands with police, Sgt. William Muldoon
said.
   ``He is talking, so that's always a good sign,'' Muldoon said.
   The camouflage-clad man carrying a handgun took eight hostages at
about 3 p.m. Thursday in the Possibilities beauty salon but soon
released four people, including a young boy, police said.
   One woman was freed about 2:30 a.m. today and two others were
released shortly after 8 a.m. One woman remained in the salon,
police said.
   Authorities declined to say why the women were released, and did
not release the names of the freed hostages or the woman still being
held.
   Police Capt. Michael London identified the gunman as Michael
Fane, 21, of Mason City, Iowa.
   Police sealed off about three blocks in every direction.
Residents wishing to leave or enter the area were being escorted by
police, Capt. Robert Pfeffer said.
   The Rev. Mel Merwald, a Roman Catholic priest who spoke with
police about the gunman, said the man was ``not irritated.''
   ``The man is not really upset. He's really calm and that's a good
sign,'' Merwald said.
</TEXT>
