<1ST_LINE>r a PM-FatalCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0523 12-30 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fatal Crash, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0523,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Die, 10 Injured As Truck Plows Into Cars</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede, penultimate graf with officials now saying only 10
people were injured, two remain hospitalized sted one.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A truck cab plowed into a line of cars
at the end of an expressway, causing a fiery, chain-reaction crash
that killed four people and injured 10, police said.
   ``Apparently, ... the (truck) driver had been driving too many
hours and fell asleep,'' said Master Sgt. Jerry Bresnahan of the
Illinois State Police. The truck, driven by Richard Hall, 37, of
Warrenville, S.C., was in the northbound lanes where the Edens
Expressway turns into U.S. 41 in this northern Chicago suburb when
the crash occurred at about 9 p.m. Thursday, Bresnahan said. The
stop light at the end of the expressway had just turned green, so
the seven cars involved in the accident may have been moving a few
miles per hour.
   The four people killed _ two men and two women _ were in the
first car hit by the truck, Bresnahan said. The identities of the
victims have not been released.
   Ted Holleb, 31, a manager at Timbers Charhouse, a restaurant just
west of the highway, said he saw the accident from the building
where he works.
   ``The truck rolled over on top of two cars. It looked like a fire
in the middle of the truck. At first it was small, but it grew very
fast,'' he said. ``Flames engulfed two or three cars.''
   Kelly Hoxie, the general manager of the restaurant, said he
helped rescue the truck driver.
   ``The driver kept saying, `I hope they get out. I hope they get
out,''' Hoxie said.
   Hall was in fair condition today at Highland Park Hospital,
Bresnahan said. Another man was in fair condition with a rib
fracture and eight others were treated and released.
   No charges had been filed in the case, Bresnahan said.
</TEXT>
