<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LegionRecruiter     12-30 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Legion Recruiter,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Legion Recruiter Turned in Phony Registrations, Officials
Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American Legion commander allegedly
signed up 200 phony memberships, including a former German soldier
and several dead people, to win a Recruiter of the Year award, a
newspaper reported.
   Costa Mesa Post Cmdr. Robert Hanson, who was named the state
Legion's top recruiter in June, may have bought his way to the top,
according to a report detailed in Thursday's editions of The Orange
County Register.
   A three-member Legion committee issued its findings in a 13-page
report signed Dec. 5 by state Cmdr. Andrew J. Steffanic.
   The state American Legion awarded Hanson its Recruiter of the
Year award at its Sacramento convention after Hanson submitted 801
new memberships between July 1, 1987, and the 1988 convention.
   But the investigation found just 18 of the 801 applicants paid
dues by check, while Hanson wrote about 25 checks to the Costa Mesa
post for $8,250 from his own account.
   The report concluded, ``The question arises, was this an attempt
to simply buy a large roster of members? If so, it would constitute
an ominous attack on the integrity of The American Legion itself.''
   It recommended charging Hanson with violating the organization's
rules by using ``unorthodox and erroneous'' recruiting methods.
Hanson faces expulsion from the Legion, Steffanic said.
   Hanson, 67, declined to discuss the report.
   The investigation began after the Legion's national headquarters
received inquiries from people wondering why they were receiving the
American Legion Magazine.
   The report said one of the letters was from a disabled man who
had never served in the military, while another was from a man who
had been a soldier in the German Army during World War II and was a
prisoner of war in the United States.
   Investigators found 205 apparent phony memberships, according to
the report. Some of the people contacted did not know Hanson, and
denied wishing to join or being eligible to join. Many were dead,
the report said.
   The report said Hanson was unable to explain why his membership
applicants said they never agreed to join.
   To be eligible, applicants must have been discharged honorably
from the U.S. military and have served in World War I, World War II,
the Korean War or the Vietnam War.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
