<1ST_LINE>u a PM-SunkenShip 2ndLd-Writethru a0542 12-30 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sunken Ship, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0542,0740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Search Expanded For Crew From Cargo Ship That Sank In Stormy Seas</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf, `Two of ...' with memorial
today; Picks up 5th graf, `At first ...': DELETES now-outdated last
graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard expanded its search today for six
crewmen missing from a Bermuda-bound container ship that sank in
rough seas and gale-force winds in the North Atlantic, leaving two
seamen dead.
   ``We continue the search as long as there's a chance of finding
them alive,'' Coast Guard Petty Officer Ken Arbogast said Thursday
night. ``We haven't found the second life raft'' from the ship.
   Three crewmen were plucked from the sea Thursday after the
254-foot Lloyd Bermuda sank Wednesday night. A fourth was found dead
and a fifth died on the way to the hospital.
   Two of the rescued men were transferred to the Coast Guard cutter
Tamaroa and were helping searchers with information on what happened
to their ship, Arbogast said.
   The victims were remembered at a ceremony today in Port Newark,
N.J., as friendly men who went out of their way to help others. The
Lloyd Bermuda had visited the port weekly.
   ``We are full of admiration for every one of the seafarers who
have worked. ... We know how important the spirit of cooperation is
to them,'' said the Rev. Barbara Crafton, maritime chaplain and
Episcopal priest. ``A seafarer is a brother to every other
seafarer.''
   At first light today, two Coast Guard C-130 airplanes, one Air
Force C-130 airplane, a Navy P-3 Orion airplane, two Coast Guard
jets, two Coast Guard helicopters and a National Guard helicopter
joined the search, Coast Guard Petty Officer Paul Scharlacken said.
   The Lloyd Bermuda sank about 160 miles south of Nantucket and 200
miles east of New Jersey when its cargo shifted in weather that was
``nothing short of horrendous,'' said Coast Guard Lt. Paul Wolf.
   Wolf said there was hope for the missing crewmen because the ship
went down on the edge of the Gulf Stream, where warm currents mix
with frigid Atlantic waters. Two of the rescued crewmen did not
suffer serious hypothermia.
   The ship's captain was American and the crew was a mix of
nationalities, John W. Moore of the Meyer Agencies Ltd., the ship's
agent in Bermuda, said in a telephone interview from Hamilton.
   The Lloyd Bermuda, registered in Cyprus, made a run to Bermuda
every week, and had left Port Elizabeth, N.J., Tuesday night with a
cargo including food and building materials, Moore said.
   Powerful winds hit the East Coast on Wednesday as a cold front
moved swiftly through the area and out to sea.
   Around 7:10 p.m., the ship's cargo shifted. The captain issued a
distress call, then called back a few minutes later to say he was
abandoning ship, Wolf said.
   The ship capsized and began to sink within five minutes of the
order to abandon ship, said Coast Guard Lt. Mike Humphreys, who
spoke to one of the survivors. The men took to two life rafts.
   Rescuers began searching a 700-square-mile area for survivors but
were hindered by heavy rains, 40- to 45-mph winds and 25-foot seas.
   Shortly after midnight Wednesday, a Coast Guard jet spotted three
people in the water waving flashlights. Sailor aboard the merchant
ship Eagle pulled two men from the water, but the third ``slipped
from his life jacket, fell back into the water and was not seen
again,'' Wolf said.
   The two survivors were treated for mild hypothermia.
   Around 4 a.m., a Coast Guard frogman from a helicopter rescued
two men drifting in the water without life rafts.
   They were flown to Falmouth Hospital on Cape Cod, but one man was
pronounced dead, apparently of hypothermia, a hospital spokeswoman
said.
   The other man, identified as Dario Macio-Lopez, 35, was treated
for hypothermia, spokeswoman Marie Johnson said.
   At first light Thursday, a Navy pilot spotted what appeared to be
a man waving from a life raft. But when rescuers reached the raft,
they found nobody.
   Three hours later, rescuers spotted another man but, because of
choppy seas and floating debris, could not get close enough to tell
if he was alive. By the time a rescue helicopter reached him four
hours later, the man was floating face down.
</TEXT>
