<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1256EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-China-Africans Bjt   12-30 0763</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Africans, Bjt,0786</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>African Students Say Authorities Charge They Have AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NANKING, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Racial conflict between African and Chinese
students was reported in another city Friday, and more than 60
Africans were sequestered in a dormitory to protest allegations by
authorities that they have AIDS.
   The incident at the Zhejiang Agriculture University in Hangzhou
took place against the backdrop of continued anti-black
demonstrations in Nanking, where Chinese students are demanding that
African students involved in a Christmas Eve brawl be punished.
   Martin Ayuk, a student from Cameroon, said the problems in
Hangzhou, 143 miles southeast of Nanking, began Dec. 23 when a
university operator started telling all incoming Chinese callers to
the foreign students dormitory that all African students were
infected with AIDS.
   African students asked the university for an explanation but were
not satisfied by a meeting with a university official, ``so we began
our boycott,'' Ayuk said in a telephone interview from Hangzhou.
   On Wednesday, a school finance officer came to the dormitory and
students locked him in the office of the gatekeeper, Ayuk said. The
official escaped through a window at 5 a.m. Thursday after nine
hours in captivity when the African students were asleep, he said.
   Ayuk said he believed the Chinese were prejudiced against all
foreigners, but most strongly against Africans.
   He said the Africans had been given a nickname in Hangzhou:
``aizu bing,'' the Chinese words for AIDS.
   A student at the agricultural college from the Congo was sent
home in November after he tested positive for AIDS, but all the
other African students have tested negative for the disease, Ayuk
said.
   China, which has so far escaped the AIDS epidemic, requires all
foreigners who live in China to undergo a test for acquired immune
deficiency syndrome.
   An African student at Zhejiang University, also in Hangzhou, said
police were not allowing other African students to leave the city.
   ``Today I wanted to go to Shanghai but I wasn't able,'' said
Pierre Dujo, of Cameroon. ``The police are preventing us from buying
tickets.''
   Another African said he believed the Chinese were using the fear
of AIDS to restrict contact between Africans and Chinese.
   ``They can't stop the contact between us and the Chinese,'' said
the student from Zhejiang University, who spoke on condition of
anonymity. ``We have many very good, deep friendships so what
they're doing is using this to scare off the Chinese.''
   Ayuk said hot water had been turned off in the dormitory and the
canteen was closed. He said students were cooking in their rooms
with what little food they had.
   There are an estimated 1,500 Africans from 40 nations studying at
Chinese universities. China has long provided scholarships for
Africans in a show of solidarity with developing African states, but
social tensions, which Africans attribute to ingrained racial
prejudices against blacks, have on occasion erupted into violent
incidents between the Chinese and the Africans.
   In Nanking on Friday, about 140 African students continued to be
held at a guest house of a chemical fiber factory outside the city.
   City authorities forced the Africans to the guest house Monday
night, ostensibly to protect them from angry Chinese mobs. They have
rejected the students' requests to leave Nanking.
   During demonstrations Saturday and Sunday, thousands of Chinese
threw rocks at African students and destroyed property in their
dormitory rooms. The Chinese have demanded the Africans be brought
to justice for allegedly starting a fight on Christmas Eve at Hehai
University in which 11 Chinese were injured.
   Ye Chunsheng, vice director of the Jiangsu Provincial Educational
Committee in Nanking, said Friday the incident was under
investigation and that about seven African students would be
punished.
   He said the Africans were not cooperating in the investigation.
``They've locked their doors in the guest house and we can't get in
to talk with them,'' he said.
   Yang Ruiju, president of Hehai University, said on Thursday that
no Chinese would be punished for the clash and subsequent anti-black
demonstrations.
   As of Friday evening, the streets of Nanking were quiet for the
first time since the initial clash Saturday.
   On Thursday, seven Africans and one student from Bangladesh left
the Nanking Polytechnical Institute under police escort for the
train station, where they traveled to Shanghai, said a student from
the Comoro Islands. He would only identify himself by the name of
Bourhane.
   Bourhane said the Africans, from Sudan, Somalia and Congo, were
not involved in the incident, but felt endangered in Nanking and
wanted either to leave China or study in another city.
</TEXT>
