<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has refused for the
second time to dismiss a 47-count indictment against hotel queen
Leona Helmsley and her husband for conspiracy, extortion and tax
evasion.
   ``Her present appeal is nothing more than a repackaged version of
the first attempt,'' Judge Richard J. Cardamone of the 2nd U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals said in writing for the three-judge panel.
Their decision was released Thursday.
   Her lawyers said they were not prepared to comment.
   Mrs. Helmsley, her husband, building tycoon Harry B. Helmsley,
and two officers of the Helmsley Corp. were indicted in April for
allegedly using a large group of real estate, hotels and other
businesses to conspire to defraud the Internal Revenue Service.
