<HEAD>Investigators Find Nuclear Workers Improperly Demoted</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rights of two workers were violated when they
were demoted for insisting that Georgia Power Co. correct nuclear
safety violations at Plant Vogtle, federal investigators found.
   The Atlanta office of the U.S. Department of Labor said Gary
Yunker and John Fuchko were demoted in violation of federal laws
protecting whistle-blowers. Both men filed complaints Nov. 2.
   ``We found the complaints were correct,'' Richard Robinette,
regional director of the Labor Department's Wage and Hour Division,
said Thursday.
   But Georgia Power spokesman David Altman described the complaints
as groundless. ``We think the Department of Labor was rushed,'' he
said. ``It was incomplete.''
   Georgia Power appealed the decision and an administrative law
judge scheduled a hearing for Tuesday.
   The employees, after pointing out safety violations at the plant,
were told by superiors that it was not part of their responsibility
to make sure the problems were fixed, Robinette said.
</TEXT>
