<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hirohito     12-30 0121</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hirohito,0126</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hirohito Gets Large Blood Transfusion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Emperor Hirohiro was given a large amount of blood
Friday to boost his strength and compensate for continuing internal
bleeding, palace officials said.
   The 87-year-old emperor remained in stable condition, said
Imperial Household Agency spokesman Kenji Maeda.
   Doctors gave Hirohito 1.3 pints of blood in two transfusions
Friday, Maeda said. Hirohito has received more than 62 pints of
blood since his internal bleeding worsened on Sept. 19.
   Palace officials say the emperor still sleeps most of the time
and his strength continues to decline. Palace sources have refused
comment on reports he has cancer.
   The emperor has no political power but serves as a symbol of the
unity of Japan.
