<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Economy     12-30 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Economy,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Works On Comprehensive Economic Recovery Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new government, grappling with its first
crisis, has begun work on an economic program aimed at restoring
public confidence in the shekel and ending a speculative run on the
dollar.
   Finance Minister Shimon Peres was expected to ask the Cabinet on
Sunday to approve the outlines of an economic recovery plan that
will be the most comprehensive since the emergency anti-inflation
program of 1985, analysts said.
   Israel radio reported Friday that Peres was considering a $600
million cut in government spending, an increase in fees for
government services, a reduction in subsidies for food and other
necessities, and an end to automatic cost-of-living salary increases
for workers.
   The Cabinet also was expected to approve a further devaluation of
the shekel, perhaps as much as 10 percent, the radio said.
   The new government, a coalition of the right-wing Likud bloc and
the leftist Labor Party that is similar to the previous government,
was installed Dec. 22. Peres, leader of the Labor Party, is the
former foreign minister.
   The government has spent the past week trying to stem a massive
buying binge of foreign currencies by the public and large financial
institutions.
   The Bank of Israel, the nation's central bank, on Tuesday
devalued the shekel 5 percent by adjusting the exchange rate to
1.680 shekels to the dollar from 1.599 shekels.
   On Friday, the central bank halted all foreign currency trading
to stop further speculative buying. The markets are expected to
reopen Tuesday after the New Year's holiday.
   Michael Bruno, the bank's governor, predicted on Israel radio
that once the new economic program is adopted, ``the public will
calm down and the markets will stabilize.''
   In the three days before trading was stopped, Israelis responded
to rumors of an impending devaluation by purchasing $285 million
worth of foreign currencies, mostly dollars. They apparently hope to
sell at a profit after the shekel is devalued.
   The Israeli economy faces other major problems, including an
industrial slump, rising budget deficits and inflation approaching
20 percent a year.
   Efran Kleiman, chairman of the economics department at Hebrew
University in Jerusalem, noted that when the government introduced
its last emergency program in July 1985, prices were rising at an
annual rate of 440 percent or more.
   ``We don't have hyper-inflation anymore,'' he said. ``But the
government's idea now is the same _ not to do things unilaterally
but to get some kind of agreement, a social contract.''
   This will require support from Histadrut, the nation's massive
labor federation, which represents about 80 percent of Israel's
workforce.
   But Histadrut General-Secretary Yisrael Kessar said Friday that
workers can't be expected to relinquish their cost-of-living
guarantee unless they are assured of other compensation. Union
workers now get automatic pay increases equal to about 70 percent of
the inflation rate.
   But he added, ``This doesn't mean we don't want to be partners in
a comprehensive plan.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
