<2ND_LINE>AM-Rapist Foiled,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Woman Fights Back, Stabs Would-Be Rapist With His Own Knife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STANTON, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 34-year-old woman foiled a would-be
rapist who kidnapped her outside a laundromat by fighting back and
stabbing him with his own knife, police said.
   The woman, who officials declined to identify, was in fair
condition in a nearby hospital, Cypress police Lt. Bob Bandurraga
said Thursday.
   Thomas Edward Kuranda, 24, of Stanton, was arrested for
investigation of kidnapping, attempted rape and attempted murder,
Bandurraga said. He was held without bail in the Orange County Jail.
   Both the victim and her alleged assailant suffered stab wounds,
bruises and cuts, the lieutenant said.
   Kuranda allegedly forced the woman into her car at knife-point
outside the laundromat and had her drive to nearby Cypress, where he
attempted to rape her, said Orange County Sheriff's Lt. Richard
Olson.
   ``The man stabbed and choked the victim,'' Bandurraga said. ``She
resisted vigorously and screamed for help.''
   A Cypress resident overheard the woman's shouts and called
police, who caught Kuranda in a nearby back yard.
