<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1352EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash-Security 1stLd-Writethru a0576 12-30 0859</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Security, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0576,0879</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Security, Terrorists in Technological `Arms Race'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS last graf with 2 grafs to CORRECT that El Al has had a
hijacking.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Air terrorism has spawned a grisly ``arms race''
between the security establishment and the ever-increasing
sophistication of the terrorist arsenal.
   As bomb-detection machinery has grown more refined, explosives
have become easier to conceal. As one security gap closes,
terrorists find another.
   Because of lack of personnel and the expense of operating X-ray
equipment, ``we are always at least two steps behind the
terrorists,'' Brian Orrell of the British flight engineers' union
said Friday, eight days after a bomb blew up Pan Am Flight 103 over
Scotland, killing all 259 people aboard and leaving 11 on the ground
missing and presumed dead.
   But other experts say the quest for terrorist-proof air travel
has reached an outer limit beyond which it will become prohibitively
expensive or make flying unbearably uncomfortable.
   When air terrorism became a problem in the late 1960s,
authorities responded by transforming airports into fortresses.
   It now is routine for all passengers to go through metal
detectors while their hand luggage is X-rayed. Airlines especially
at risk, such as Israel's El Al, search all luggage by hand. At
Belfast airports, the Irish terrorist threat makes it necessary to
frisk not just the passengers but everyone else coming into the
terminal.
   Airlines insist that each piece of luggage match its passenger,
assuming that no bomber would travel aboard the targeted plane. So
terrorists have resorted to duping unwitting passengers into
carrying explosives onto planes. Passengers are regularly warned to
accept no baggage they haven't packed themselves.
   The search for suspicious objects has become much harder with the
advent of plastic explosives that give off virtually no detectable
odor. They are malleable enough to be shaped into a souvenir or
rolled wafer-thin to fit inside a suitcase lining. Detonators now
are small enough to fit into a suitcase lock.
   Moreover, the age of the metal-free handgun is looming. According
to David Kyd, spokesman for the International Air Transport
Association in Geneva, such a gun has been developed in Austria and
will be extremely hard to detect on X-ray screens.
   ``The sophistication and miniaturization of explosives has become
quite worrisome,'' Kyd said in an interview.
   According to David Learmount of the respected journal Flight
International: ``It's an arms race.''
   Bombs can be connected to barometric detonators that respond to
altitude changes. Airports have hit back by putting baggage through
simulated pressure to set off such bombs in safety.
   The terrorists, in turn, have come up with a double-device: the
pressure detonator goes off safely, but it activates a second timer
that will detonate the bomb in the air.
   The Times of London said Friday that this method was believed to
have been used on Flight 103.
   Kyd is optimistic that within two years, a highly advanced
explosives detector will become operational.
   Now being tested in U.S. laboratories, the machine bombards
objects with thermoneutron rays that detect telltale nitrogen
vapors. But to cover the vast amount of baggage moving through large
airports, it will have to be small, mobile and able to distinguish
explosives' vapors from those given off by aviation fuel, said Kyd.
   He said the biggest security hole now lies not in the terminals
where passengers arrive to catch flights but on the tarmac where the
planes are parked.
   Security, he said, is difficult to impose on the hundreds of
airport workers swarming about the tarmac. Many of the menial jobs
are held by low-paid immigrants who are vulnerable to bribery and
whose background is unverifiable in a security screening.
   ``We can put all the screens in place to check passengers and
luggage, but there's still the problem of direct access to aircraft
by people who are there to clean planes, fuel them and put food
aboard,'' he said.
   The weapons used in the hijacking of a Kuwaiti airliner by
Iranian extremists this year were probably smuggled aboard in
catering trolleys in Bangkok, Kyd said.
   ``A huge amount can still be done for security, but the fact that
it's possible doesn't mean it's feasible,'' Learmount said in an
interview.
   El Al is unique, he said, because ``Israel as a nation operates
in some respects under siege, under military conditions, and all its
citizens accept that. So its airline has to act in many respects
like a military operation.''
   El Al passengers have to check in three hours before takeoff,
their baggage is hand-searched, and the slightest irregularity in a
travel document can mean a polite but lengthy interrogation about
the passenger's origins, work, family, friends and purpose of travel.
   If another airline used such tactics on passengers, Learmount
said, ``I suspect they wouldn't keep on flying with you for very
long.''
   El Al has never had an aircraft bombed. But an El Al Boeing 707
was hijacked over Italian airspace by three armed members of the
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine on July 23, 1968. All
passengers and crew were freed over several days after the plane
landed in Algeria.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881230-0117 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1359EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hostages     12-30 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hostages,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Freed French Girls Celebrate Christmas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two French girls held hostage for 13 months
celebrated a belated Christmas on Friday with a party thrown by
their home town.
   But public rejoicing was tempered with suggestions that Libyan
leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi used the children to boost his image.
   ``This is the end of a nightmare,'' Pascal Betille, father of
7-year-old Marie-Laure and 6-year-old Virginie, told hundreds of
people gathered in the public square of Ollioules in southern
France. ``This is happiness.''
   The girls, held by an extremist Palestinian group, were handed
over to French officials Thursday in the Libyan capital of Tripoli,
six days after Gadhafi called for their release.
   The children's mother, Jacqueline Valente, five Belgians and a
baby sister born in captivity remained in the hands of Abu Nidal's
Fatah-Revolutionary Council, backed by Libya. The group, suspected
in numerous cases of terrorism, accused them of spying for Israel.
   Doctors at a Marseille hospital said Friday the girls were in
good physical and psychological health.
   The children and their father attended the town party in
Ollioules, near the Mediterranean port of Toulon, before leaving for
a vacation at an undisclosed location.
   The French press welcomed the return of Marie-Laure and Virginie.
But it gave equal space to what the conservative daily Le Figaro
called ``nausea'' at the motive for the release.
   ``At the close of this ignoble drama ... there remains an
after-taste of bitterness,'' Le Figaro wrote. Gadhafi ``today wants
to play the role of Father Christmas.''
   The girls' freedom is widely viewed here as Gadhafi's effort to
boost his image at a time when the United States, alleging Libya has
a chemical weapons plant, issued threats of a military strike.
   ``This gesture by the colonel is not gratuitous when, once again
the object of American threats, he urgently needs to fine-tune his
image as a `reasonable' man of state ...'' commented the daily Le
Monde.
   The press also noted a renewed effort by Libya to improve
relations with the European Economic Community, which reduced
diplomatic activity with Libya following the U.S. raid on Tripoli in
April 1986.
   French officials said no conditions were made for the the release
of the girls.
   The only exchange, Le Monde quoted officials as saying, was
allowing Gadhafi to make a nice gesture.
   Gadhafi called for the girls' release on Christmas Eve. Once
freed, Fatah-Revolutionary Council, in a statement issued in Beirut,
Lebanon, said the girls were a ``gift to France'' from the children
of the year-old Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied
territories.
   They were taken captive Nov. 8, 1987, when the Silco, a sardine
trawler turned yacht, was seized off the Gaza Strip, according to
the captors' announcement.
   There have been reports the boat was actually seized off the
coast of Libya, highlighting the mystery that has surrounded the
hostages from the start.
   Le Monde quotes French intelligence sources as suggesting the
Belgian hostages may never have left Libya and that the girls may
have arrived there long before the official announcement Thursday.
   The hostages, who have received little public attention over the
past year, have been referred to in the French press as the
``forgotten hostages.''
   The case is considered unrelated to the 15 Westerners held
hostage in Lebanon by pro-Iranian factions. They include nine
Americans. The longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent for The Associated Press who was abducted March 16,
1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
