<HEAD>Trucker Arrested After Accidents on Interstates</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with two seriously injured, 25 vehicles
hit, citizens surrounding man, other details.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN ANTONIO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A semi-truck driver was arrested today after
he raced through morning rush hour at speeds up to 90 mph, ramming
his rig into at least 25 other vehicles, police said. At least two
people were seriously injured.
   ``People said he was just pushing people off the road,'' a police
dispatcher said.
   Sheriff's deputies chased the Peterbilt tractor-trailer rig for
about 30 miles before he pulled into a rest area on Interstate 35
near Devine, southwest of San Antonio. A group of citizens there
surrounded the driver until officers arrested him.
   Police found a small amount of cocaine in his rig, said
Department of Public Safety trooper Marshall Milikien. The man was
taken to the Medina County jail in Hondo.
   The first hit-and-run incident was reported shortly after 8 a.m.
on Interstate 10 near Comfort in Kendall County, about 40 miles
northwest of San Antonio, said Department of Public Safety trooper
Alvin Schacht.
   The trucker sideswiped a vehicle driven by Robert Etlinger of
Boerne, who was run off the road. When the rig didn't stop, Etlinger
gave chase but was unable to catch him, Schacht said.
   The trucker ``was running between 85 and 90 and he (Etlinger)
couldn't catch him,'' Schacht said.
   The truck eventually hit at least 18 cars in San Antonio and
seven elsewhere, police said. Many vehicles were sideswiped and
rear-ended.
   At least two people were seriously injured, said Department of
Public Safety trooper Marshall Milikien.
</TEXT>
