<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Cuomo-Harris     12-30 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cuomo-Harris,0284</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Grants Clemency To Two; Denies It For Jean Harris</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Gov. Mario Cuomo today denied a
request for clemency from the woman convicted in the 1980 murder of
Scarsdale Diet author Dr. Herman Tarnower.
   Jean Harris, 65, is serving 15 years to life for the slaying of
her lover. Friends and relatives of Harris, a former headmistress at
an exclusive Virginia girls' school, had mounted a petition appeal
campaign on her behalf.
   They said as many as 10,000 letters had been sent to Cuomo and
that they had delivered petitions containing 25,000 signatures
seeking clemency for her.
   Neither Harris' lawyer nor family members could be reached
immediately for comment today.
   Other than to say clemency for Harris had been denied, Cuomo
spokeswoman Anne Crowley declined to discuss the matter.
   Harris has always maintained she meant to kill herself and not
Tarnower on March 10, 1980, when she drove to his house just north
of New York City from her home at the Madeira Girls School in
McLean, Va.
   Upset because he had taken up with a younger woman, Harris wound
up shooting Tarnower four times. She said the shooting was an
accident.
   The governor today granted clemency to two state prison inmates,
Bernice Lane and Emilio Vasgonez, who were serving 15 years-to-life
sentences on drug sale charges.
   In a statement issued with his clemencies, Cuomo said Lane and
Vasgonez were the only two inmates recommended unanimously, or even
by a majority of the lawyers who reviewed the clemency requests for
him.
   Inmates denied clemency can reapply after waiting one year.
</TEXT>
