<DOCNO> AP881230-0123 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1446EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     12-30 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Brite & Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURLINGTON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A retiree's dry sense of humor about the
1988 drought has earned him the title World Champion Liar.
   Roy Griesbach, a former home builder, received the honor this
week from the Burlington Liar's Club, which has been handing out the
annual award for more than half a century.
   His winning lie: ``The weather was so dry this past summer that
the only water one could buy was dehydrated in 16-ounce packages.''
   Sheree Bykofsky of New York City received an honorable mention
for a lie that she admitted was about herself: ``Last summer my wife
spent so much money in the shops of Woodstock, N.Y., that they have
renamed the town Out-of-Stock.''
   The dry weather led some people to send lies that have been heard
before, club Vice President Don Reed said.
   One of the most common repeaters was, ``The drought was so bad
that the trees were chasing the dogs.''
   In the interest of maintaining its amateur standing, the liar's
club has one rule: no politicians. ``They're professionals,'' Reed
said.
   ``We used to bar journalists,'' he added. ``But we feel
journalism has changed. They tell the truth most of the time.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One potato, two potato, three potato
more _ much, much more.
   CSX Transportation is giving away 250,000 pounds of potatoes
contained in two boxcars that derailed Dec. 22 in Jacksonville. The
spuds were on their way to Frito Lay Inc. in Orlando, where they
were destined to become potato chips.
   The boxcars are sitting in a freight yard in Jacksonville.
   ``I've been giving them to any charitable organization that would
come get them,'' said Tom Walker, freight damage prevention
supervivor for CSX.
   Social agencies are doing their best to pick up the potatoes
while they are fresh.
   City Rescue Mission workers spent all day Thursday transporting
the potatoes in a pickup truck and a delivery truck. The rescue
mission has started giving away 10- to 12-pound bags of potatoes.
   But Dan Ellison, manager of the mission's thrift store, said it
would take two to three weeks for the two trucks to empty the
freight cars.
   ``That's a pile of potatoes. I've never seen so many potatoes in
my life.''
</TEXT>
