<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua     12-30 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinista Paper Says Contras Tortured Prisoners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of 44 Sandinistas freed by
Contra rebels say they were tortured during their captivity in
Honduras, the official Sandinista party newspaper said Friday.
   The prisoners arrived Thursday in Nicaragua under tight
government control. Only the party newspaper Barricada, the
pro-government newspaper El Nuevo Diaro and Sandinista TV were
allowed to cover their arrival.
   Another 60 prisoners freed by the U.S.-backed rebels refused to
return to Nicaragua. They chose to remain in Honduras while seeking
permission to go to the United States, Mexico or Canada.
   Barricada said the 60 were ``false prisoners'' and El Nuevo Diaro
described them as ``mercenaries'' staging a Contra-directed
propaganda ``show.''
   Both Barricada and Nuevo Diaro said they interviewed some of the
44 who came home.
   ``They subjected us to hunger, torture and all kind of outrage.
They made me see death,'' Barricada quoted Natividad Matute Guillen
as saying.
   El Nuevo Diaro reported that 15-year-old Marvin Jose Palacio
Orozco said he was tortured ``with electric prods on my feet and
used like a punching bag.'' It said the Contras accused the youth of
being a Sandinista spy.
   Red Cross officials brought the prisoners across the border
Thursday, six days after the Contras freed them under pressure from
the Honduran government.
   The rebels say the prisoners were captured a year ago in combat
in the Nicaraguan provinces of Chontales, Matagalpa and Madriz.
   The Sandinistas have not said whether the freed prisoners
included members of the armed forces.
   Meanwhile, the government said nothing about the latest Contra
proposal for a new round of peace talks in Washington beginning Jan.
25.
   An uneasy truce has been in place in the 8-year-old war since
March.
   The U.S. Congress cut off military aid to the Contras in
February. About 10,000 rebels, the bulk of the fighting force, fled
to base camps just across the Honduran border, where they have been
supported by U.S. humanitarian aid.
</TEXT>
