<DOCNO> AP881230-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1502EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FreeFuneral     12-30 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Free Funeral,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cemetery's Annual Offer of Free Burial Services Has Had No Takers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-News Year's Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IKE FLORES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some may call it a publicity gimmick, but
Bob Neel believes that revelers find his annual offer to pay funeral
costs for anyone killed in a drunken driving accident on New Year's
Eve a sobering thought.
   For the past 10 years, Neel's funeral home and cemetery has
offered a free casket, funeral service and burial to anyone killed
in a drunken-driving accident during the end-of-year celebrations.
   So far, no one has collected, and Neel thinks his offer has made
a difference.
   ``I can't prove it with statistics, of course, but I get so many
calls and letters you wouldn't believe,'' Neel said Friday. ``They
tell me it's made them more aware of drinking. I know it has me and
my friends. The publicity, I'm sure, has done some good.''
   Neel, chairman of Woodlawn Memorial Park & Funeral Home, started
the practice in 1979, and he believes he was the first to do so.
   ``I've been challenged on that by other funeral directors,'' he
said. ``But I know of no one who offers all of the services that we
do _ the family would not have to spend one cent.''
   Neel said the casket, grave, funeral service, minister,
embalming, flowers and incidentals would cost about $3,500.
   Originally, Woodlawn required that those who planned to drink and
drive over the holiday had to sign up to take advantage of the
offer. Later, Neel dropped that stipulation and just had people call
in beforehand.
   But for the past two years, all that a relative or friend of the
deceased had to do was come in after the accident and request the
funeral.
   The victim does not have to be the person driving. He or she can
be a passenger or an innocent bystander killed in a smash-up caused
by a drunken driver.
   To dramatize the project this year, Woodlawn dug a fresh grave
Friday morning, provided a vault and chapel tent and had a minister
on hand for television cameras and reporters.
   ``We pray that it won't be used,'' said Neel. ``It's an unusual
thing to do and publicize, but if we save even one life, it's worth
it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881230-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1522EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Yugoslavia Bjt   12-30 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Yugoslavia, Bjt,0772</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Resigns, Major Changes Not Forseen</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY24; LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By IVAN STEFANOVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government resigned Friday in
reaction to mounting criticism of its handling of an economic
crisis, the first to do so since the communists took power after
World War II.
   The move, a sign of the liberalization creeping into Yugoslavia's
one-party system, represented a further break with the legacy of
President Josip Broz Tito, founder of communist Yugoslavia and its
undisputed leader until his death in 1980.
   Premier Branko Mikulic told Parliament he and the entire
31-member Cabinet stepped down because legislators refused Wednesday
to pass an economic law needed to ensure continued support from the
International Monetary Fund.
   Mikulic, a 60-year-old economist and Tito ally who took office in
May 1986, was seen as a hardliner in the ruling Communist Party. His
resignation indicated that reform-oriented forces eager to adopt
Western-style changes are gaining the upper hand in a protracted
political struggle.
   Few Yugoslavs, however, expected Mikulic's resignation to bring
any immediate solutions to an economic crisis that has reduced
living standards by 50 percent since 1980.
   Foreign debt stands at $21 billion, unemployment at 15 percent
and inflation at around 250 percent _ three times what it was when
Mikulic took office.
   In a speech to Parliament broadcast on live national television,
Mikulic firmly rejected responsibility for the country's economic
and social woes. Effectively blaming the system bequeathed by Tito,
he said difficulties created in past decades could not be solved in
the 2{ years he has spent in office.
   Mikulic will stay in office as a caretaker premier until the
nine-man federal presidency names a new government in January.
   The complex federal system bequeathed by Tito stipulates that all
federal decisions must be unanimously agreed on by Yugoslavia's six
constituent republics and two autonomous provinces.
   In practice, this has meant that federal decisions are watered
down to ineffectual compromises that each region interprets as it
wants.
   Referring to Yugoslavia's maze of federal, republican and local
bureaucracies and laws, Mikulic told Parliament that decisions about
the economy are made in 7,000 to 8,000 different places, suggesting
it was unfair to blame the government.
   Falling living standards have provoked more than 1,000 strikes
this year in a country once hailed as a worker-managed state.
Discontent also has eaten at the prestige of the Communist Party,
whose membership has fallen steadily.
   Two Belgrade residents who asked not to be named said they
expected little to change after the first fall of a Communist
government in Yugoslavia.
   ``Did they fall indeed?'' a travel agent asked upon being told
the news. ``So who is going to congratulate us (for) the New Year?''
she quipped.
   A housewife shopping before the three-day New Year holiday
lamented the difficulty of making ends meet each month.
   ``So what do you expect will happen now?,'' she said. ``They are
all of a kind. They cannot do anything, or do not want to, except
build seaside villas at the expense of the workers.''
   She was referring to a scandal in Mikulic's native republic of
Bosnia-Hercegovina, where hundreds of party officials have been
accused of securing illegal loans to build themselves homes in the
Adriatic resort of Neum.
   Mikulic survived an attempted vote of confidence in May, when
parliamentary deputies from the liberal northern republic of
Slovenia and from Croatia failed to gain support from four other
republics for Mikulic's ouster.
   But criticism had mounted in recent weeks. Government minister
Oskar Kovac, who oversaw Yugoslavia's negotiations with its debtors,
resigned Dec. 5, citing unidentified pressures that hindered
market-oriented reform.
   Ironically, parliament on Thursday passed a package of economic
reform laws that should allow mixed ownership and greater foreign
investment _ measures economists have long prescribed for
Yugoslavia's economic ills.
   Increasing poverty has exacerbated traditional ethnic conflicts
among the more than 30 ethnic groups who make up Yugoslavia's 23
million citizens.
   But parliament on Wednesday defied Mikulic's warnings about the
need to live up to its obligations to the International Monetary
Fund, refusing to pass a law curbing public spending.
   Such austerity measures are a condition of IMF aid to
inflation-ridden countries such as Yugoslavia. Mikulic said the IMF
had demanded the law as a condition for granting the Belgrade
government a one-year, $416 million standby credit in June.
   Some $260 million of that credit has been used to date, according
to official estimates. The loan also encouraged Western creditors to
reschedule payments on Yugoslavia's mounting foreign debt.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
