<DOCNO> AP881230-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1525EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-Honors Bjt   12-30 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Honors, Bjt,0716</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beekeeper, Rothschild Honored by the Queen</HEAD>
<HEAD>Embargoed For Release 7:01 p.m. EST _ Time Set By Source</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AUDREY WOODS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   From a beekeeper and a mailman to a Rothschild and
three Olympic gold medalists, the humble and the powerful were
rewarded Saturday for good works and political loyalty in that grand
old British tradition, the queen's New Year honors list.
   Sculptor Eduardo Paolozzi is knighted, as is Leon Brittan, the
former Trade and Industry secretary who resigned in controversy in
1986. Michael Holroyd, biographer of George Bernard Shaw, becomes a
Commander of the Order of the British Empire, as do actor Ian
Richardson and Christopher Hogwood, director of the Academy of
Ancient Music.
   Queen Elizabeth II bestowed 907 titles and medals _ most of them
to people selected by Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government
for the twice-yearly expression o gratitude. They will be joined in
June by hundreds more from the queen's birthday list.
   Although critics say the ancient honors tradition has been
tarnished by political patronage, a barony, a knighthood or a
British Empire Medal is still a glittering prize to be treasured for
life and remembered with pride by one's descendents.
   Barons and baronesses are addressed as lords and ladies and can
sit in Parliament's unelected House of Lords in the company of
Britain's ancient aristocratic families. Knights are addressed as
sir, and their female equivalents are dames. An Officer of the Order
of the British Empire gets to add OBE after his or her name.
   There is no cash reward but to many the rise in status is
priceless. For the public at large, it is an occasion to reflect on
heroes both sung and unsung, like Domingos Joseph Diago Teodoro
Pinto. The Northern Ireland doctor got an OBE for leading the
medical team that treated casualties in an Irish Republican Army
bombing that killed eight soldiers.
   This power to pander to vanity prompts accusations _ firmly
denied _ that prime ministers use the honors to repay political
cronies and party fund donors.
   Political loyalty is warmly rewarded each year. Brittan, awarded
a knighthood, was a close Cabinet ally of Mrs. Thatcher before he
resigned for approving the leak of a controversial letter during a
government crisis. He is now one of Britain's two commissioners on
the European Economic Community's administrative body.
   The government, underlining Mrs. Thatcher's new commitment to
conservation, recommended honors for several guardians of the
environment this year. The highest goes to Cambridge University
chemistry professor Jack Lewis, who chaired a commission on
environmental pollution. He becomes a life baron.
   Evelyn de Rothschild, chairman of N.M. Rothschild and Sons and
member of the British branch of the illustrious banking family,
becomes a knight, as does Geoffrey Owen, editor of the respected
Financial Times newspaper.
   Following the peerages and knighthoods, the highest honors belong
to the Order of the British Empire and its Commanders (CBE),
Officers (OBE), and Members (MBE).
   Michael McIntyre and Philip Vaile, yachting gold medalists at the
Seoul Olympics, receive MBEs, while Richard Dodds, captain of the
gold-medal-winning hockey team gets an OBE.
   An OBE goes to Bob Littlewood, 57, who masterminded the four-year
reconstruction of the badly burned south transept of York Minster,
the medieval cathedral where his family has worked for three
generations. Littlewood supervised the craftsmen who worked in
stone, wood and stained glass and the queen celebrated the completed
work this year, 12 months ahead of schedule.
   William Hooper, vice-chairman of the British Beekeeping Society
becomes one of 306 new MBEs. Leslie Quantrill, postman, wins a
British Empire Medal.
   An MBE also goes to darts champ Eric Bristow, one of Britain's
most recognizable sportsmen. The rotund ``Crafty Cockney,'' reckoned
the greatest darts player in history, becomes the first in his field
to win such an honor.
   Actress Penelope Keith, known to U.S. TV audiences for her role
in ``To The Manor Born'' and ``The Good Neighbors,'' and actor
Richard Briers, who also appeared in ``The Good Neighbors,'' receive
OBEs, as does horror film actor Peter Cushing.
   Richardson, honored with a CBE, portrayed spy Anthony Blunt in
the BBC-TV play ``Anthony Blunt'' in addition to many film and stage
roles.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
