<DOCNO> AP881230-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1544EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CopComplaints     12-30 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cop Complaints,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Residents Complain Traffic Police Lacked Holiday Spirit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENWICH, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some residents of this southwestern
Connecticut community where even Santa Claus received a warning are
complaining that police were too quick with the ticket pad this
holiday season.
   The ticketing incidents that have provoked complaints _ and even
one poem _ included a warning given to a youth dressed as Santa
Claus that his makeshift sleigh was a traffic hazard.
   Jorgen Sabinsky, the maitre d' at the Greenwich Country Club,
fired off a poem to the police with the $10 payment for the parking
ticket he received at 4:30 a.m. two days before Christmas for
illegally parking on a dead-end street.
   The poem reads in part:
   ``I'll remember your deed at the `Policemen's Ball,'
   You'll attend this winter in the Country Club hall,
   For that's where I work, so this should be fun,
   Your soup will be cold, and your steak overdone.''
   Sabinsky said he was surprised when he received his $10 check
back from the police department.
   ``I really had not expected it,'' Sabinsky said. ``I just wanted
to have a little fun.''
   Chief William Andersen said police face a no-win situation since
other residents are concerned that traffic enforcement is not strong
enough.
   ``We are paid by the taxpayers to enforce the law,'' Andersen
said.
   From Nov. 25 to Dec. 24, police issued 1,114 summonses for all
traffic offenses, including speeding, drunken driving and moving
violations, Andersen said. During the week before Christmas,
officers issued 93 written warnings rather than writing tickets
bearing fines, he said.
</TEXT>
