<DOCNO> AP881230-0132 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1547EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Reform 1stLd-Writethru a0592 12-30 0473</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Reform, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0592,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reformers Decry `Dictatorship of Mediocrity'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf with 1 graf to ADD another signer of letter;
picks up 8th graf pvs: ``Speeches by...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Churbanov, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leading supporters of President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's reforms said in a letter published Friday that his
policies are being bogged down by a Communist Party ``dictatorship
of mediocrity'' that ought to resign.
   Six artists, directors and editors, in an open letter to
Gorbachev, said elections for a new government structure, a Congress
of People's Deputies, will determine real power in the Soviet Union.
They pledged all-out support for Gorbachev.
   But they said that a campaign begun after the June party
conference in Moscow to review nearly 20 million party members with
a view toward their support for Gorbachev's reforms had been
hampered by too many directives.
   They said that experience made them doubt whether the elections
would firmly implant reformers throughout the Soviet system.
   ``Can it be said that we are entering the new year and moving
toward elections with full confidence in the irreversibility of the
democratic renewal of society?'' they asked. ``One would very much
like to answer that question positively. But a feeling of sensible,
realistic responsibility holds us back from such an evaluation.''
   The writers said a ``dictatorship of mediocrity'' was rampant,
not only among individual conservatives who remain in the party
apparatus, but throughout the entire Communist Party headquarters.
   The letter was published in the Jan. 1 edition of the weekly
Moscow News, which was released Friday. It was signed by Grigory
Baklanov, editor of the monthly literary journal Znamya; playwright
Alexander Gelman; author Danil Granin; film producer Elem Klimov,
actor Mikhail Ulyanov; and space scientist Roald Sagdeyev.
   Speeches by Baklanov and Ulyanov both caused sharp disputes with
conservatives at the June party conference.
   Gorbachev has sought to get the party out of day-to-day
management, leaving that to local economic and government officials.
But the party retains final authority and has shown no sign of
tolerating any opposition.
   The writers said that there undoubtedly must be opponents of
Gorbachev's reforms in Soviet society, and that they must be able to
state their ideas. But it said party members who oppose Gorbachev's
reforms must be judged severely.
   ``Those who do not agree with the new course must retire,'' they
said.
   The six also appealed for more tolerance of informal political
and social organizations that have sprung up in the freer atmosphere
fostered by Gorbachev's reforms.
   ``If we don't find the path toward cooperation with dissidents, a
temptation to rush to repressive measures probably will arise _ and
already has arisen _ with all the anti-democratic consequences that
flow from this,'' they said.
   Cooperation with dissidents ``not only doesn't weaken, but on the
contrary, strengthens the authority of restructuring'' they said.
</TEXT>
