<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Crash-Czechoslovakia     12-30 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Crash-Czechoslovakia,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Czechoslovakia Offers Explosives Experts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Crash, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Czechoslovakia on Friday offered to
send experts to help identify explosives that blew up Pan Am Flight
103 following reports a Czech-manufactured explosive may have been
used.
   A Foreign Ministry statement categorically denied that
Czechoslovakia ever provided explosives to terrorists.
   British authorities said Wednesday that the residue of explosives
recovered from the debris of the Boeing 747 that crashed in
Lockerbie, Scotland, on Dec. 21, was ``consistent with the use of a
high-performance plastic explosive.''
   That led to speculation the bomb may have been made of Semtex, an
orange-colored plastic explosive manufactured in Czechoslovakia.
   Terrorism experts and U.S. State Department officials have said
that Syria and Libya obtained Semtex from Czechoslovakia and passed
it on to surrogate terrorist groups.
   So far, no group or individual has been identified as a prime
suspect in the bombing.
   ``Czechoslovakia again emphasizes that it condemns categorically
all acts, forms and methods of terrorism and that it complies
consistently with the appropriate international commitments,'' said
the Foreign Ministry statement, carried by the state news agency CTK.
   ``It has never supplied and does not supply explosions to
terrorist organizations,'' the statement said.
   CTK said the Ministry issued the statement in response to reports
Semtex may have been used in the Pan Am disaster.
   ``We are ... prepared, should this help the identification of the
explosive used, to send any time Czechoslovak experts for the
appropriate expert consultations,'' the statement said.
</TEXT>
