<1ST_LINE>r i AM-AmazonKilling     12-30 0353</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amazon Killing,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Slaying of Ecologist Nearly Solved, Police Say</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal police said Friday they are
close to solving the slaying of an ecologist who angered ranchers by
fighting to protect the vast Amazon jungle.
   ``The murder is still not solved, but the investigation is
heading in the right direction and is close to the end,'' said
police spokesman Paulo Marra in Brasilia.
   Francisco Mendes, 44, was shot to death Dec. 22 outside his home
in the jungle town of Xapuri, 2,660 miles northwest of Rio, near the
Bolivian border.
   Marra said the body was to be exhumed ``so there will be no
doubts when we reach our conclusions.''
   Mendes, honored by the United Nations for his defense of the
environment and his belief that the Amazon jungle could be developed
without being destroyed, had said before his death that big
landowners had made threats against his life.
   Federal agents sent to far-off Acre state to work on the Mendes
case detained five ranchers Thursday for questioning but did not
formally arrest them, Marra said.
   Remaining in custody in Acre were Darcy Pereira da Silva, 21,
Oloci Alves da Silva, 22, and Aleci Alves da Silva, 23, all sons of
ranch owner Darly Alves da Silva.
   Mendes told a Rio newspaper Dec. 9 that Darly da Silva was one of
those who most wanted him killed because of his efforts as an
ecologist and as head of the local Rubber Tree Tappers Union.
   Darcy da Silva said on Tuesday he had killed Mendes. But police
said the confession could have been a smokescreen to protect others.
   The deputy justice minister, Luis Fernando Eichenberg, told the
privately owned Rio station Radio Jornal do Brasil on Friday, ``If
Darcy wasn't the author of the crime _ and it seems he wasn't _
there is some indication he was at the scene.''
   The issue of how to develop the Amazon jungle, an expanse of rain
forest about two-thirds the size of the continental United States,
has often erupted in violent conflicts between landowners, landless
peasants, politicians, clergymen and ecologists.
</TEXT>
