<1ST_LINE>r w AM-MeatImports     12-30 0183</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meat Imports,180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Increased Meat Imports Not Expected To Trigger Quotas Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Meat imports are not expected to rise enough in
1989 to trigger mandatory quotas on shipments from foreign
suppliers, Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng said Friday.
   The annual estimate is required by law and is subject to revision
every three months during the calendar year. It was the first
estimate for 1989.
   Lyng said a formula in the law calls for maximum imports of
slightly less than 1.438 billion pounds in 1989, down 87.7 million
pounds from the 1988 trigger level.
   But Lyng said total 1989 imports are not expected to exceed 1.425
billion pounds, or about 13 million pounds below the quota trigger.
   The law covers imports of fresh, chilled or frozen meat of
cattle, sheep (except lambs) and goats, and certain prepared and
preserved beef and veal products.
   Most is low-grade beef used to make hamburger and other processed
meat items. Australia and New Zealand are the principal suppliers,
although about a dozen countries are eligible to ship quota-type
meat into the U.S. market.
</TEXT>
