<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1634EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Closing-Aftermath     12-30 0532</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Closing-Aftermath,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alabama County Still Reeling From 1977 Air Force Base Closing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SELMA, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It has been 11 years since Craig Air Force
Base furled its flag in the nation's last round of military-base
closings, a blow the mayor says hurt Selma more than the tumultuous
civil rights era.
   In just one day _ Oct. 1, 1977 _ the city and surrounding Dallas
County lost 2,500 military and civilian jobs, a $40 million payroll
and untold millions in economic spinoffs, the kind of fiscal future
other communities may face under the list of 34 recommended base
closings released Thursday by a government panel.
   Joe Smitherman, mayor of Selma then and now, said Friday that
gains have been made in converting the former flight-training base
to private use. But the mostly black, rural area still has not
recovered, he said.
   ``We haven't got it developed like we hoped it would be. It's
mostly turned into a housing project,'' Smitherman said.
   While the nation remembers Selma for civil rights benchmarks like
the Bloody Sunday clash on the Edmund Pettus Bridge and the Rev.
Martin Luther King Jr.'s subsequent voting rights march to
Montgomery in 1965, Smitherman said the loss of Craig was ``the
biggest single impact ... we've had on the area.''
   ``People do adjust to civil rights changes. But it's hard to
adjust to an economic loss like the base,'' he said.
   Hugh Allen, head of the authority that oversees what used to be
the base, said Dallas County's unemployment rate temporarily doubled
to about 20 percent when Craig shut down.
   ``But it was a lot more than that. There was the real estate. And
people who were used to having a lot of military business lost it,''
said Allen.
   State statistics showed Dallas County's unemployment rate at 8.6
percent in 1976, the last full year of record-keeping before the
closing. The rate rose to 9.3 percent in 1979, but that number
reflects only the number of residents seeking employment. Rather
than try to find work in the county, Allen estimates that 3,000 to
3,700 people out of a town of 27,000 simply left.
   In the decade since Craig's closure, local authorities have
fought tooth-and-nail over the field, Smitherman said.
   ``We got word one time that (federal officials) were considering
putting Cuban prisoners out here. We stopped that. The state prison
people were going to put a minimum-security prison out here, and we
stopped that,'' he said.
   What does exist at Craig is a municipal airport, a training
school for state police officers and prison guards, several
companies, warehouses and housing. While as many as 700 people
worked at Craig two years ago, Allen said the recent closing of a
Beechcraft Aircraft plant reduced that number to 275 to 300.
   Of the 500 military housing units on the property, the federal
government controls 50, the Craig Field Airport and Industrial
Authority sold about 50, about 330 are rented and 70 remain vacant,
Allen said.
   Allen had some advice for communities that stand to lose military
facilities under the panel's recommendations:
   ``They need to go after that property. I think you need to plan
your work and then work your plan.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
