<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Clemency     12-30 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Clemency,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Criminal Records of 120 Convicted After 1956 Revised</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary's presidential council Friday
revised the criminal record of 120 people convicted after the 1956
anti-Soviet uprising, the state news agency MTI reported.
   They were among 174 people who were excluded from a broad amnesty
in September for those imprisoned for participating in the revolt.
   The people who were not covered by the amnesty had been told at
that time to sumbit a proposal to the presidential council on
granting individual pardons until Nov. 30, 1988.
   Katalin Gaspar, head of the Justice Ministry's amnesty
department, said Friday that those not granted clemency involved
cases ``when manslaughter was committed ... amid inhuman
circumstances in a dastardly manner, like the killing of wounded
persons,'' MTI reported.
   Clemency was also not granted to those convicted of robbery,
shop-breaking or when ``vengeance motivated the actual or attempted
killing of persons because of their political persuasion or office
held,'' MTI quoted Gaspar as saying.
   He said those not included in the present clemency act can
petition the Justice Ministry again next year.
   According to the amnesty ruling, those convicted for their role
in the 1956 revolt had their criminal record erased. A criminal
record is one reason for denying the issuance of a passport in
Hungary, meaning those granted clemency would likely be permitted to
travel under Hungary's liberalized travel laws.
   The September amnesty covered those sentenced to imprisonment for
crimes against the state, ``counterrevolutionary activities,'' or
persons whose death penalty was commuted to imprisonment.
   The amnesty did not extend, however, to those convicted of high
treason or espionage, or those who, in ``cumulation of offenses,
committed homicide, robbery and caused public danger.''
   The revolt began Oct. 23, 1956, with mass demonstrations for a
new government amd demands that Soviet troops leave Hungary. On
Nov.4, 200,000 Soviet troops and 2,500 tanks struck at Budapest to
quell the uprising.
</TEXT>
