<2ND_LINE>AM-Mexico-Infant Deaths,0321</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reports Infant Deaths Linked to Contaminated Milk</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As many as 20 infants died after drinking
powdered milk in rural Veracruz state in the last two weeks,
prompting authorities to seize boxes of the milk and test water
supplies, Mexico City newspapers said Friday.
   El Nacional, the government newspaper, said Red Cross and federal
officials began investigating this week after a local newspaper said
20 children had died at a clinic in Perote.
   Perote is 20 miles west of the state capital of Xalapa, where the
first report about the deaths was published in the daily Grafico de
Xalapa. It said the children ranged in age from 18 months to 3
months.
   They died after suffering fever, sharp stomach pains, diarrhea,
vomiting and convulsions, the Mexico City daily El Universal said.
   It said health authorities seized boxes of powdered milk from
local stores and took water samples to check for contamination.
   El Universal said parents were alarmed by the reports, despite
denials by local officials.
   Pedro Coronel Perez, the state health and welfare secretary,
toured the villages of El Conejo, Frijol Colorado, Los Pescadores,
El Limon, Totalco and Escobillo to check the reports.
   Coronel Perez said at least nine infants in the area had died
from intestinal troubles in the past two months. But he said
officials had not determined if their deaths were linked to
contaminated powdered milk.
   He said the infants were from poor, rural families and could have
died from a variety of intestinal illnesses.
   ``They lived in extreme poverty, without proper food and care,''
he said.
   El Nacional quoted Perote Mayor Jaime Roldan Roa as saying that
if there had been contaminated powdered milk in the area, thousands
of children would have died.
   Many people in Mexico drink powdered milk because it is cheaper
and more easily obtained than fresh milk.
</TEXT>
