<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1656EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Resolutions     12-30 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Resolutions,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Research Shows Not Many Keep New Year's Resolutions</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-New Year's Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SCRANTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly half of more than 200 people studied
failed to keep their New Year's resolutions for a month, and less
than one in five followed their pledges for two years, a researcher
said.
   ``Sticking to your resolution takes more than willpower, it takes
careful planning both before and after the new year,'' said John C.
Norcross, head of the University of Scranton's psychology department.
   Norcross headed a research team that showed only 55 percent of
213 people kept their New Year's resolution for a month. Only 19
percent kept their pledge for two years, he said this week. The
study ran from Jan. 1, 1986, through Jan. 1, 1988.
   People who make New Year's resolutions need to take them
seriously and follow a systematic strategy for keeping them, or not
make them at all, said Norcross, who is also a clinical psychologist.
   ``More than half a million American adults routinely make New
Year's resolutions, and year after year they fail,'' he said. ``Not
because they lack desire. Rather, they are poorly prepared to change
and are under-educated in the complex process of self-change.''
   Norcross suggested several steps before the new year to improve
chances of a resolution succeeding, including:
   _Define an attainable goal.
   _Solicit the cooperation of family and friends.
   _Have a substitute for the behavior to be changed.
   A social worker in Owensboro, Ky., doesn't recommend resolutions
at all.
   ``You're really setting yourself up for a fall with these
things,'' said Tom Mudd, a social worker at Green River
Comprehensive Care Center.
   ``That's because we usually set things up that are way beyond our
reach. I just don't believe in making them at all.''
   The key to keep from giving up and saving yourself from the guilt
that usually accompanies failure, Mudd said, is setting your sights
on one or two small, specific goals and then working on them as soon
as possible.
   Norcross said environmental control, self-reward and willpower
were the keys to self-change.
   ``For example, smokers who want to kick the habit could remove
ashtrays from their home and avoid situations that would tempt them
to smoke,'' he said. ``They also could devise self-rewards, such as
complimenting themselves or treating themselves to a night out for
staying off cigarettes.''
   Norcross said people also should be persistent, even if they slip
along the way. His research showed successful resolvers slipped an
average of 14 times during the two years of the study.
   ``Meaningful behavior change is a lifelong pursuit. It takes the
average smoker five to seven tries to quit for good,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881230-0144 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1658EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TotRescue 1stLd-Writethru a0606 12-30 0493</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tot Rescue, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0606,0505</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>3-Year-Old Uses Phone for First Time To Save Mom's Life
^Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 13th graf, ``He never...' to UPDATE with
comment from operator. Picks up 14th graf, `Now Jason's ....'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHREVEPORT, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 3-year-old boy, using the telephone for
the first time, saved his bleeding mother's life by calling the
operator and asking her to reach his father at work.
   ``The doctors said if I had laid there much longer I wouldn't be
here today,'' Liz Pendleton, 29, said Friday from her hospital room.
   Mrs. Pendleton said she felt sick Tuesday and woke up early
Wednesday in severe pain and unable to move, hemorrhaging from a
ruptured fallopian tube.
   She called to her son, Jason, who was sleeping on the couch near
the telephone and told him he would have to get help.
   ``He told me, `Oh, Mommy, you can just wait until tomorrow to go
to the doctor,''' Mrs. Pendleton said. ``He just couldn't see it.''
   She convinced him she needed help right away, and he followed her
instructions. She made an ``O'' with her thumb and forefinger and
explained where the button for the operator was on the telephone
dial.
   ``Tell her your mama's very sick,'' she told Jason.
   Then Jason told the operator that his daddy worked at Arkla Gas
in the computer room. Mrs. Pendleton told Jason the phone number and
spelled their last name and he repeated it to the operator, she said.
   When the operator got Randy Pendleton, 33, on the line, Jason
said: ``Daddy, mama's very sick. You're going to have to come home.''
   Pendleton called for an ambulance and rushed home. Mrs. Pendleton
was taken to Schumpert Medical Center where she had emergency
surgery. Doctors said she had lost three pints of blood and was near
death.
   Mrs. Pendleton said Jason had never used the telephone before but
handled the situation like a veteran caller.
   ``He knows his numbers. But he's only in 3-year-old preschool,''
she said. ``He catches on real quick. He's 3 but he acts like he's
about 7.
   ``He never got nervous. I was trying not to get him upset. He
took it like a pro,'' his mother said proudly.
   Bonny Baker, the South Central Bell operator who took the call,
said she doesn't often get emergency calls from children.
   ``A lot of times when you do, it's children playing a prank which
at first I thought he was doing,'' Baker said Friday.
   But, she said, it quickly became obvious that the situation was
serious.
   ``You could tell there was definitely something wrong,'' she said.
   Now, Jason's enjoying the attention that comes with heroism.
   ``Yesterday, when the newspaper was up here he was telling them
all about it _ shaking their hands and everything,'' Mrs. Pendleton
said. ``He's going to think his picture should be in the paper every
day.''
   Mrs. Pendleton said she hopes to go home Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
