<HEAD>Rebels Firebomb Lima Restaurants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Masked leftist guerrillas broke into
candlelight dinners at three stylish Lima restaurants, forced
patrons and staff out into the street and then firebombed the
establishments, authorities said Friday.
   The incidents late Thursday night followed a noontime vigil in
which top church and political authorities asked Peruvians to pause
to pray for a peaceful end to insurgency violence, which has claimed
more than 12,000 lives since 1980.
   No one was hurt in the restaurant raids, police said.
   Armed members of the Tupac Amaru Revolutionary Movement, in units
ranging from two to five, simultaneously seized the restaurants;
ordered everyone out and then doused the premises with gasoline and
exploded firebombs.
   Flames heavily damaged Las Trece Monedas, a former colonial home
in downtown Lima converted into a popular tourist restaurant; the
seaside steakhouse Rincon Gaucho, and the suburban restaurant La
Puerta Roja, police said.
   The Tupac Amaru group, active since 1984, endorses a Cuban-styled
Marxism. It is smaller and considered less violent than the Maoist
Shining Path, blamed for most of the insurgency casualties.
Officials say the two groups are not linked.
</TEXT>
