<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-Torture     12-30 0255</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Torture,0260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Official Accuses Turkey Of Widespread Torture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior U.N. official has accused
Turkish police of routinely torturing detainees despite government
efforts to polish up Turkey's human rights image, a Dutch newspaper
reported Friday.
   The Rotterdam newspaper NRC Handelsblad said Pieter Kooimans, UN
special rapporteur on human rights, also charged Turkey with
frequently denying suspects legal assistance and keeping them in
total isolation after their arrest.
   Turkey, which has signed several U.N. and European conventions
banning the use of torture, is eager to improve its human rights
reputation after filing an application to join the European Economic
Community.
   The newspaper quoted Kooimans as saying in an interview, however,
that ``in my experience, torture is still being used on a large
scale especially at police stations'' throughout the eastern
Mediterranean nation.
   Kooimans, a Dutch citizen, recently visited Turkish prisons and
police facilities. He said he will discuss his findings in detail in
his annual report to the United Nations Human Rights Commission,
scheduled for publication in early 1989, the paper said.
   Reports of torture by Turkish police and soldiers abounded in the
early 1980s, when Turkey was ruled by a military junta under Gen.
Kenan Evren. Premier Turgut Ozal became head of a civilian
government in 1983. Evren is still president.
   Under Turkey's legal practice, ``Pretrial detention without the
possibility of legal assistance and with the detainees being kept in
total isolation for periods of about two weeks is a virtual
invitation to torture,'' Kooimans was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
