<1ST_LINE>r a AM-InmateAccess     12-30 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Inmate Access,0334</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contract That Gave Credit Card Numbers to Inmates Canceled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal contract that gave prisoners
processing mortgage applications access to credit card and bank
account numbers has been canceled.
   ``I can't run the risk. It's just too high a risk,'' Warden
Patrick Kane of the Federal Correctional Institution in Lexington
said Thursday. ``No one in their right mind is going to allow this
stuff in an institution.''
   The U.S. Secret Service is investigating whether any inmates
might have misused the information.
   The contract between the federal Department of Housing and Urban
Development and the prison called for inmates to type information
from completed mortgage applications into computers. Since the work
began as a pilot project in July, more than 60,000 applications have
been sent to the prison.
   About 600 of the applications contained either credit card or
bank account numbers.
   The decision to discontinue the contract between HUD and the
prison was made during a meeting of HUD and Bureau of Prisons
officials in Washington, according to Kane.
   An inmate at the institution, Beverly Hirsch, first sounded the
alarm about the credit card numbers, the Lexington Herald-Leader
reported Friday. Kane said Ms. Hirsch, serving a 40-year sentence
for bank and credit card fraud, told him that some inmates had
copied the credit card numbers and that some of the information had
been passed out of the institution.
   Secret Service agent Bill Cravens of Lexington, who is heading
the investigation, said Friday there was no evidence the information
was being used illegally.
   ``So far as we know now, none of the card numbers have been
compromised,'' he said.
   A spokesman for the Bureau of Prisons said the HUD mortgage
applications did not ask applicants for their credit card or bank
account numbers.
   ``Some overzealous lending officers added the information to the
application in an effort to overdocument the applications,'' said
John Pendleton, a Bureau of Prisons spokesman.
</TEXT>
