<HEAD>Egyptian Paper Accuses Israel; Mubarak: Anti-PLO Group Planned An
Attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel on Friday denounced as ``repugnant
libel'' an editorial in an Egyptian government newspaper saying the
Israeli secret service may have been responsible for last week's
bombing of Pan Am Flight 103.
   Also Friday, Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak was quoted by a
West German magazine as saying an anti-PLO group ``that may be
working with certain Israeli circles'' planned a large-scale attack
to discredit the Palestinians.
   Mubarak did not identify the group and did not draw any links
between the planned attack and the Dec. 21 bombing of the Pan Am jet
over Scotland.
   In an unsigned editorial Friday, the Egyptian newspaper Al Akhbar
said it was possible Israel's Mossad intelligence service carried
out the Pan Am bombing that killed 270 people.
   The editorial claimed Israel had a ``past record in masterminding
such sort of crimes which aim at casting suspicion on Palestinian or
Arab elements.'' It did not elaborate.
   Israeli Foreign Ministry spokesman Alon Liel said his government
is ``amazed by the fact that an official Egyptian newspaper has
published an injurious article of this kind.
   ``Israel rejects the repugnant libel ... attributing to Israel, a
victim of PLO aviation terrorism, the same terrorist methods used
against her during the last 25 years,'' Liel said in a statement.
   Mubarak was asked in an interview by the magazine Der Spiegel
what would happen if Arabs opposed to peace in the Middle East
activated terrorists such as Abu Nidal's group.
   ``By Allah, one must reckon with this. Certain groups have surely
hammered out such plans,'' the news weekly quoted Mubarak as saying.
   ``I don't want to name any names, but there is one group that
wanted to let Arafat speak before the U.N. General Assembly ... and
then start a large-scale terrorist action in order to turn public
opinion against the Palestinians,'' Spiegel quoted Mubarak as saying.
   ``These criminal elements that are trying to prevent peace may be
working with certain Israeli circles, I don't know,'' he was quoted
as saying.
   The Spiegel article did not say when and where Mubarak was
interviewed.
   The reports come at a time when Israel's prime minister, Yitzhak
Shamir, is seeking Mubarak's help in launching a new Middle East
peace initiative.
   Egypt, which signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1979, is the
only Arab nation to maintain diplomatic ties with the Jewish state,
but relations have often been strained.
   Arafat renounced terrorism at a news conference after a speech to
the U.N. General Assembly in mid-December in Geneva. The session was
moved to Geneva after the U.S. State Department refused to issue
Arafat a visa to speak at U.N. headquarters in New York.
   Arafat's statement led to the United States opening a dialogue
with the Palestine Liberation Organization.
</TEXT>
