<DOCNO> AP881230-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1830EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NavyDeaths     12-30 0696</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Navy Deaths,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressman Attacks Report That Navy Trying To Improve Safety
Record</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Hometowns of the other recruits not available</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Pentagon review of 17 accidental deaths in
Navy training over the past two years said the service was trying to
improve its safety record, but a Wisconsin congressman called the
report an ``insult'' and accused the Navy of stonewalling.
   ``If this wasn't so serious, it would be a joke,'' said Rep. Toby
Roth, R-Wis. Roth took interest in the issue after the death of a
constituent, Airman Recruit Lee Mirecki, 19, of Appleton, Wis.
   A Navy swimming instructor at the training base in Pensacola,
Fla., was convicted of negligent homicide last September in the
Mirecki case and sentenced to 90 days in jail.
   ``In Wisconsin, if you hit a parked car you get more of a penalty
than that,'' Roth said in a telephone interview Friday. ``This death
could have been prevented. It was negiligence. Things got out of
hand.''
   The paragraph dealing with Mirecki in the 10-page Pentagon report
said the only action taken had been review of training courses ``to
ensure maximum safety of students while retaining required realism.''
   The court record showed Mirecki had been dunked repeatedly while
other recruits were forced to stand with their hands against the
wall singing the national anthem.
   In a letter attached to the report, Assistant Secretary of
Defense Grant S. Green said ``the personnel casualties we have
suffered in training are few when compared to the number of students
undergoing training.''
   ``That is not to diminish the personal tragedy which is
represented by each training fatality,'' said Green, chief of
personnel for the Pentagon.
   ``Beyond the personal loss, accidents pose the greatest peacetime
threat to our warfighting assets. I assure you that we will continue
to pursue vigorously methods to reduce accident losses to our
personnel and equipment in our training activities,'' Green's letter
said.
   The Pentagon spending bill for the current fiscal year called on
the Navy to report on the training deaths to Congress by Dec. 31.
   ``We had been going around and around with the Navy and never got
answers,'' Roth said. ``I thought there had been some stonewalling.''
   The congressman said that after he met with Green on Friday
morning and complained about the report, ``Green said, `We will
consider this an interim report and we will try to comply''' with a
more complete version later.
   Green could not be reached at his office Friday afternoon.
   A Pentagon spokesman, Navy Cmdr. Mel Sundin, said he was not
familiar with the report, but read a statement: ``A letter
forwarding an interim report on the causes and circumstances of all
deaths of Navy personnel during Navy training since Jan. 1, 1986,
and on actions taken was sent today to the Speaker of the House, the
Hon. James C. Wright, (D-Texas), and the President Pro Tempore of
the Senate, Sen. John C. Stennis,'' D-Miss.
   Lt. Cmdr. C.W. Baumann, a Navy spokesman, said he had not seen
the report and could not comment.
   Spokesmen for Wright and Stennis said the report had not yet
reached their offices.
   Roth said he would raise his complaints shortly after the 100th
Congress convenes next Tuesday. The General Accounting Office, the
investigative arm of Congress, is due to report on the issue by Feb.
15, Roth said.
   The Navy report listed the deceased trainees and the dates and
causes of death as: Michael J. Gee, Aug. 19, 1988, drowning; Tasene
Epenesa, May 17, 1988, cardiac arrest; John J. Tomlinson, March 14,
1988, hypothermia; Kenneth M. Kundinger, Dec. 15, 1987, cardiac
arrest; Leo P. McSherry, Gregory McMichael, April 15, 1987, air
crash; Herbert E. McLemore, Jan. 31, 1987, overexertion while
suffering from sickle cell trait; Michael P. Thompson, Oct. 22,
1986, air crash; Jesus C. Paredes, Sept. 3, 1986, cardiac arrest;
Peter Martin, June 8, 1986, parachute jump; Frank W. Dahlinger,
Thomas R. Washington, April, 18, 1986, air crash; Sherwood Collins,
Don L. Bohorques, March 16, 1986, air crash; James B. Friend, March
26, 1986, overexertion while suffering from sickle cell trait; Alan
J. Higgins, Feb. 24, 1986, arrythmia.
</TEXT>
