<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Sudan 1stLd-Writethru a0597 12-30 0718</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sudan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0597,0734</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Demonstrations Continue Despite Price Concessions</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to RESTORE first reference to reporter
Mohamed Osman. Pickup 5th graf `Dispatches received...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. MANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-government protesters took to the
streets of Khartoum and other cities in Sudan for a fourth day
Friday despite government concessions on food price increases. At
least two people were reported killed.
   A Western diplomat reported rumors of an imminent coup attempt in
Sudan and said the East African country remained paralyzed by a
general strike. Communications were still disrupted.
   Khartoum Commissioner Fatih Abdoun, the capital's head of
government, told Associated Press reporter Mohamed Osman that ``an
unidentified gunman opened fire on demonstrators'' outside Cabinet
offices on Thursday, killing two and wounding 28.
   Osman, speaking by radio from Khartoum, also reported one dead
and 21 injured, including some victims from outside Khartoum in
eastern Sudan. It was not known whether the victims were included in
the previous report.
   Dispatches received in Cairo from the Egyptian and Iraqi news
agencies on Thursday reported what appeared to be two separate
shooting incidents, including one after dark with ``intensive
shooting'' near government headquarters.
   There were no reports of new violence Friday. But a Western
diplomat in the Ethiopian capital, Addis Ababa, reported ``complete
political chaos'' in Sudan.
   The diplomat, who watches Sudanese affairs and said he was in
contact with Khartoum, said the disturbances ``do not seem to have
subsided, despite the fact that the price increases which originally
sparked the trouble have been rolled back.''
   ``The action in the streets is taking on a definite
anti-government flavor,'' he said. ``It looks like the government is
in serious trouble. There's a lot of talk about a coup attempt
coming out of Khartoum.''
   Thousands of Sudanese began demonstrations and strikes Tuesday, a
day after the government increased prices of prime commodities by up
to 600 percent and imposed a 15 percent sales tax on all goods.
   On Thursday, in response to a call by the 2-million-member Sudan
Workers' Trade Union Federation, a general strike closed most
businesses and shut down communications and transportation
facilities.
   The government rescinded the price increases on Thursday, but it
was not known whether the tax also was eliminated.
   Officials in Cairo reported the first apparent loosening of the
general strike's grip on the country. Khartoum International Airport
sent a notice to area airports that it was back in business for the
first time since late Wednesday.
   But the national airline Sudan Airways' scheduled service to
Khartoum from Cairo was canceled Friday night because airline
employees remained on strike.
   The diplomat in Addis Ababa said Sudan still suffers from a
``complete paralyzation of transport, communications and everyday
life. ... The railway is down. Inter- and inner-city buses have
stopped rolling. Shops are closed.''
   It appeared that since the government backed down on the price
increases, anger has turned to Prime Minister Sadek Mahdi's refusal
to submit to the government and Parliament a tentative agreement to
end the country's 5{-year-old civil war.
   The head of the Democratic Unionist Party, junior partner in the
governing coalition, negotiated the pact with John Garang, a
renegade army colonel who heads the rebels in southern Sudan.
   The agreement called for a cease-fire and suspension of Islamic
law in Sudan until the matter can be discussed in a constitutional
conference, a major concession for Garang. He had vowed that his
mainly Christian and animist forces would continue to fight until
the Islam-based legal code was abrogated.
   Mahdi reportedly was concerned that endorsing the Islamic law
clause would prompt the fundamentalist National Islamic Front to
leave the government, removing a buffer that the prime minister has
used in disputes with the Democratic Unionists.
   Since the street protests began, the Democratic Unionists, who
dominate the trade union federation, have quit the government in
sympathy.
   Reports on Friday said Mahdi has accepted the six Unionist
ministers' resignations and will name Hassan Turabi, his
brother-in-law and attorney-general, to the key Unionist-held post
of foreign minister.
   That would make Turabi the government's peace negotiator with
Garang. As attorney-general Turabi drafted the Islamic legal code,
and as head of the Islamic Front he has spearheaded opposition to
the Unionist-negotiated agreement, so prospects for successfully
concluded talks would be virtually nil.
</TEXT>
