<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Solidarity 1stLd-Writethru a0662 12-30 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Solidarity, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0662,0432</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-6 UPDATE with protest banner at party building.
Picks up 2nd graf pvs, Adam Hodysz ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>Protesters Hang Banner on Communist Party Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two opposition activists on Friday hung a
protest banner reading ``Free the Politicals'' from a balcony at the
headquarters of the Community Party's Central Committee in the
capital.
   The banner was signed with the initials of the banned Polish
Socialist Party and the Warsaw regional council of the Solidarity
trade union movement.
   The protest was connected with a weeklong hunger protest taking
place in Warsaw through Sunday to draw attention to the detention of
anti-military activists in Poland and Czechoslovakia.
   Brief displays of opposition banners from public buildings are
fairly common in Poland. However, this appeared to be the first time
activists managed to place one on the guarded headquarters of the
Communist Party.
   Security workers seized the 15-foot-long banner after about five
minutes. The activists, Piotr Ikonowicz and Edward Mizikowski, were
led away into the building and detained, according to Jozef Pinior,
a Socialist Party spokesman.
   Authorities meanwhile freed a secret policeman Friday who was
sentenced to prison for helping underground members of Solidarity,
prison officials and opposition sources said.
   Adam Hodysz, 48, was arrested in 1984 and initially charged with
cooperating with Solidarity's underground. Authorities later
sentenced him to six years in prison on a more serious charge of
corruption, alleging he had taken money to pass police secrets to
Solidarity.
   Solidarity activists have denied any financial motive for
Hodysz's cooperation. They say he was motivated by sympathy for the
union movement, which authorities crushed in late 1981 and banned in
1982.
   Hodysz, a former captain in the state Security Service in Gdansk,
was released from a prison in Koszalin, in northwestern Poland,
according to a duty officer at the Regional Board of Penitentiaries.
The official refused to give his name.
   The former policeman was eligible for the parole, subject to good
behavior, because he had served two-thirds of his prison sentence.
   After his release, Hodysz went to St. Brygida's Church in Gdansk,
a northern port, to meet with Solidarity leader Lech Walesa and the
Rev. Henryk Jankowski, according to a Jankowski aide. Jankowski is a
Walesa adviser.
   At the time of Hodysz's arrest, authorities were trying to stamp
out any vestige of Solidarity, the first independent labor movement
in the East bloc. However, they have increasingly tolerated the
movement in recent years and even allowed Walesa to speak in an
uncensored television debate in November.
</TEXT>
