<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Austria-Bishop     12-30 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Austria-Bishop,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Austrian Catholics Choose New Archbishop, Criticize Vatican</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic leaders announced the
selection of conservative Georg Eder as Salzburg's new archbishop
Friday but complained of bias in the Vatican's list of candidates
for the post.
   In an official statement carried by the Catholic news agency
Kathpress, the 12-member Salzburg Cathedral Chapter said Eder
accepted the body's appointment Thursday. It must now be formally
made by Pope John Paul II.
   The announcement comes at a time when the Catholic Church in
Austria is suffering from widening divisions over the appointment of
conservative bishops and with contentious issues, including the
pope's stand on birth control and women's role in the Church.
   Eder is known as a conservative priest who says Mass in Latin
with his back to the congregation. The Second Vatican Council in the
1960s called for use of a new Mass in the vernacular with the priest
facing the faithful.
   The Salzburg chapter said it broke the traditional secrecy
surrounding such appointments because of advance media criticism of
the choice of yet another conservative for a top church post. Eder
was considered by commentators as the least conservative of three
candidates put forward for selection by local church leaders.
   An estimated 260,000 believers have left the church in the past
eight years. According to a critical Catholic journal, 30,917 left
the church in 1987 alone.
   The local church leaders also criticized the Vatican's three
candidates, saying the list was biased.
   ``The Cathedral Chapter had to recognize that the selection of
candidates for this triple proposal was not taken in such a balanced
fashion as could be expected,'' they said in a joint statement.
   The statement said they had ``exhausted every available
possibility'' to make the Vatican aware of ``the needs of the
diocese and the views of the area.'' They said they had sent a
letter on the issue to the Vatican.
   The appointments of conservative Hans Hermann Groer as archbishop
of Vienna in September 1986 and of ultra-conservative Kurt Krenn as
assistant bishop of Vienna five months later triggered open protest
and division in Austria's Catholic ranks.
   In the Vatican City on Friday, the pope nominated five new
auxiliary bishops in Hungary and another in the tiny central African
country of Rwanda.
   The pope nominated the Revs. Vilmos Dekany and Asztrik Varszeghi
to posts in Esztergom; the Rev. Istvan Acs in Eger; the Rev. Mihaly
Mayer in Pecs; the Rev. Nandor Takacs in Szekesfehervar; and the
Rev. Felicien Muvara in Butare, Rwanda.
</TEXT>
