<HEAD>Dynamite Explodes At Club Frequented by Americans</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Two grafs SUB for final graf pvs, the Italian-American ...
UPDATING with U.S. Navy reax</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PALAU, Sardinia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dynamite exploded early Friday at a
nightclub popular with U.S. sailors, but the building was empty at
the time and no one was hurt, police reported.
   The blast occurred at 6:30 a.m. at the nightclub Big in the town
of Palau, near the U.S. military base at La Maddalena.
   Authorities said, however, that the explosion did not appear
aimed at the Americans. It apparently was a protest of the noisiness
of the club, said a police officer, who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   The dynamite, placed at the entrance to the club, shattered
windows and bottles of liquor and damaged the furniture.
   Sardinia had planned a non-binding referendum for April on
whether residents of the island were in favor of foreign military
bases not approved by Parliament which service nuclear-powered
vessels or those carrying nuclear arms.
   The only base that fit the description was the one at La
Maddalena. However, Italy's Constitutional Court suspended the April
vote.
   The Italian-American agreement, which allowed construction of the
base on the Mediterranean island off the Italian mainland in 1972,
was never ratified by Italy's Parliament.
   In Washington, U.S. Navy spokesman Lt. Cmdr. C.W. Baumann said
shore leaves remained the same for sailors in the region following
the bombing.
</TEXT>
