<HEAD>Strike Cancels Holiday Performances</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A stagehands strike forced cancellation of the
National Ballet of Canada's last sold-out holiday performances this
year of ``The Nutcracker,'' officials said Friday.
   Four matinee and evening performances of the traditional ballet
and one of the farcical ``Nutty Nutcracker'' were canceled from
Thursday to Saturday.
   ``The union refuses to put stagehands on the job while mediation
talks are in session,'' Charles Cutts, general manager of the
O'Keefe Center, said in a statement.
   The O'Keefe's theater seats 3,000. The National Ballet has been
performing the holiday favorite annually since 1964.
   The International Alliance of Theatrical Stage Employees' local
and the center are in a dispute over use of outside technical
workers by touring productions.
   ``The Sugar Plum Fairy was felled by a labor dispute last
night,'' the Toronto Star wrote Friday in reporting on the strike.
