<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MiamiHomeless     12-30 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Miami Homeless,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Refuses To Block Homeless Busts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge refused Friday to block police from
arresting homeless people in pre-Orange Bowl weekend roundups,
denying an injunction sought by the American Civil Liberties Union.
   The ACLU accused Miami police of harassing the homeless in
advance of the Orange Bowl Parade on Saturday in an effort to make
the city look clean for tourists and national television audiences.
   ``When someone is sleeping on a piece of cardboard, they can be
arrested for littering,'' said ACLU attorney Valerie Jonas, seeking
a ban on enforcing misdemeanor laws she said were used selectively
to round up the poor and homeless.
   U.S. District Judge C. Clyde Atkins ruled on technical grounds,
said Assistant City Attorney Leon Firtel, who added the decision
probably did not allow time for an appeal before the weekend.
   ``The police are not restrained from enforcing the law, which is
all that the city asked,'' said Firtel, who argued against the ACLU
in court. ``The police are going to do their duty and follow the
law. If they have probable cause to arrest someone, they will go
ahead and do that.''
   Brother Paul Johnson, director of the private Camillus House
homeless shelter, says at any given time there are 10,000 homeless
people in Miami. The city offers no public shelters.
   ``We're going to have observers out in the streets tonight to
make sure nothing happens _ and if these sweeps continue we're going
to observe them,'' said Ben Waxman, another ACLU attorney.
   Waxman said the ACLU lost the fight for a preliminary injunction,
but he will continue to press the underlying class-action lawsuit on
behalf of the homeless.
   ``We're still convinced that the misconduct occurred and the
homeless are being discriminated against,'' he said.
</TEXT>
