<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Israel-Headaches     12-30 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Headaches,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Throb, Throb, Throb: The Legislators Are Meeting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israel's members of Parliament suffer from
headaches you don't get from guerrilla infiltrators, hostile Arab
neighbors, or even a Palestinian uprising.
   No, they have some real headaches: the kind that make your
temples throb, turn your brain to porridge, and transform a
political speech into medieval torture.
   Lawmakers blame the endemic headaches on their 22-year-old
Parliament building, whose poor ventilation and air conditioning
have earned it the nickname ``The Submarine.'' Doctors, in turn,
dubbed the lawmakers' physical complaints ``The Submarine Syndrome.''
   Parliament Speaker Dov Shilansky said Friday the problem has ``a
great influence'' on legislators' ability to function.
   ``This is not a joke; it is a serious problem. I know a lot of
legislators who suffer from headaches and dizziness,'' Shilansky
said on Israel army radio.
   Asked if this was why many of the 120 legislators often look
sleepy, Shilansky said: ``It's really hard to sit here for the whole
day. If you spend a whole day here, you leave with a headache.''
   The five-story Parliament building on a hilltop in central
Jerusalem was inaugurated in 1966. The two lower floors, including
parts of the main auditorium, are partly underground.
   The Submarine Syndrome can do more than give you a pounding
headache, said Shilansky, a member of the Likud bloc.
   ``When I was a new Knesset (parliament) member, I met a man who
told me that he was a Knesset worker, had a good job, and was happy
with it. But he resigned because of poor ventilation. He said a
doctor told him: `You have a choice between shortening your life or
resigning,''' he said.
   Raanan Cohen, a freshman legislator from the Labor Party, said he
has begun to suffer frequent headaches since the 12th Knesset opened
Nov. 21.
   ``Normally, I don't have headaches, and I think there's some
problem with the building,'' Cohen said.
   Throughout the building, it's either too hot or too cold, said
maintenance manager Shmaryahu Eckhaus.
   ``If we heat the first floor where people complain of cold, the
heat spreads to the second and third floors, and people there ...
feel suffocated by the heat. If we turn down the heat, people on the
first floor complain of cold,'' he said.
   Experts say the solution is to break down the air-conditioning
system into smaller systems with individual controls in different
parts of the building. But army radio said that answer is too
expensive.
   Parliament doctors advise legislators to walk outside from time
to time for a breath of fresh air, the radio said.
   But legislators cannot always heed that advice during long
debates that often deteriorate into shouting matches _ especially
unbearable to people suffering from headaches.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881230-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1949EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Venezuela-Massacre     12-30 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Venezuela-Massacre,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Court Orders 20 Held in Fishermen's Massacre</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military court on Friday ordered the
arrest of 20 members of a military-police task force implicated in
the massacre of 14 Venezuelan fishermen in October.
   ``There was no armed confrontation, but the loss of 14 innocent
lives,'' said Gen. Angel Zambrano, who overruled a lower military
court decision in November that the task force acted in ``legitimate
self-defense.''
   Zambrano presided over a War Council, the highest regional
military court, in San Cristobal, about 400 miles southwest of
Caracas.
   He ordered the arrest of the 20 Venezuelans _ 16 members of
special police forces and four members of the armed forces _ and a
Colombian man believed to be an informant for the brigade.
   Military spokesmen originally said the 14 men killed were
Colombian guerrillas shot in an Oct. 29 firefight with government
forces out to prevent them from blowing up oil installations along
the Colombian-Venezuelan border.
   But two survivors who jumped into a river and swam for their
lives denied those shot were guerrillas and said they were all
fishermen out on a picnic.
   A major factor in the military's reversal was evidence released
publicly, although never made official, that an exhumation of the 14
bodies showed most of the men were shot either in the back or in the
head at close range.
   The case attracted international attention. Government officials
received letters from human rights and church groups around the
world demanding justice.
   Townspeople of El Amparo, near the site of the massacre, backed
up the two survivors' claims in interviews with journalists.
   The two survivors, Wolmer Pinilla and Jose Arias, later sought
asylum in Mexico rather than face the military court for trial on
charges of ``military rebellion'' based on the official version of
events.
</TEXT>
