<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0587 12-30 0765</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0587,0790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three Killed In Gaza; Shamir Plans New Peace Moves</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 3 grafs at bottom UPDATING with Lebanese U.N. ambassador
to protest raid.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops raided a Gaza Strip hideout and killed
two Palestinians who tried to flee, and a third Arab was killed
Friday when soldiers fired at stone-throwing worshipers after Moslem
prayers, the army said.
   At least 10 Palestinians were wounded in clashes with Israeli
troops in the Gaza Strip, Arab hospital officials said. An army
spokesman confirmed four wounded.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir plans to launch a peace initiative
within two months and will seek Egypt's help in finding Palestinian
negotiators who are not tied to the PLO, said Shamir aide Avi Pazner.
   The worst clashes erupted in the Sheikh Radwan neighborhood in
Gaza City when dozens of people took to the streets after prayers at
the local mosque, the army and Arab reports said.
   ``After prayers, they raised the Palestinian flag and threw
stones,'' said an army spokesman. Arab reporters said soldiers used
clubs, rubber bullets and live ammunition to break up the protest.
   The army said troops killed one protester and wounded four.
   The dead man, Abdel Khalim Behid, 22, was shot during the
disturbance and died at Gaza City's Shifa Hospital, hospital
officials said. They put the number of wounded at six, and said a
4-year-old boy was hit in the head with a rubber bullet.
   Elsewhere in Gaza City, three Palestinians were wounded, Arab
doctors said. In the nearby Jabalya refugee camp, a teen-ager was
wounded.
   Late Thursday, troops tried to arrest three suspected firebomb
throwers who reportedly were hiding in a home in Gaza City's Zeitoun
neighborhood, the army said.
   ``Soldiers shouted for them to come out,'' the army spokesman
said. ``They tried to escape and were shot.''
   One man died at the scene, and the second at an Israeli hospital.
A third Palestinian was captured unharmed.
   The deaths late Thursday and Friday brought to 342 the number of
Palestinians killed in their yearlong rebellion against the Israeli
occupation. Fourteen Israelis also have died.
   The army, meanwhile, brought reinforcements to the occupied lands
in anticipation of increased violence on Jan. 1, known to
Palestinians as ``Fatah Day,'' Israel radio said.
   On that day in 1965, the mainstream Fatah faction of the PLO led
by Yasser Arafat launched its first attack against Israel.
   Along with increased troops, the West Bank's military government
ordered a week-long closure of all Palestinian schools, beginning
Saturday. The measure affects 300,000 students.
   Israeli officials consider Palestinian schools flashpoints of
violence, and West Bank schools were closed by the military
government for most of the period from February to December.
   Shamir, meanwhile, was quoted as saying Friday that his peace
initiative would be based on the 1978 Camp David accords, which call
for talks on Palestinian autonomy in the occupied lands preceding a
final settlement of the conflict.
   According to the Haaretz newspaper, Shamir said he would not
insist that the U.S.-brokered agreement between Israel and Egypt be
followed to the letter.
   ``It is also possible to speak to others,'' he was quoted as
saying, referring to Palestinian representation in peace talks.
   Pazner said Shamir envisioned ``a major role'' for Egypt in
helping find Palestinians acceptable to Israel, which has refused to
negotiate with the PLO. Israel refused to negotiate with the PLO.
   Arafat, who heads the PLO's mainstream Fatah faction, said
earlier this month that he recognized Israel and renounced terror,
and in return the United States reversed a longstanding policy and
opened talks with the PLO.
   In the Haaretz interview, Shamir reiterated his opposition to an
international peace conference under U.N. auspices, as demanded by
the PLO and most Arab nations.
   Shamir said he would accept direct talks under the sponsorship of
the United States and the Soviet Union, but said they should be
restricted to a ceremonial role ``to give international legitimacy
to direct talks.''
   Asked how he would respond if President-elect George Bush invited
him to an international conference with PLO participation, Shamir
said: ``I would notify him that I could not come.''
   Lebanon's acting prime minister meanwhile instructed his
country's U.N. ambassador, Rashid Fakhoury, to protest an Israeli
air raid on south Lebanon Thursday that wounded eight Shiite Moslem
militiamen.
   Salim Hoss, who heads the Moslem Cabinet in Lebanon's dual
government, told Fakhoury to ``lodge an urgent, strongly worded
complaint about Israel's latest aggression.''
   The raid by two helicopter gunships nine miles north of the
Israeli border was Israel's 25th in Lebanon this year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
