<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TruckerArrested 1stLd-Writethru a0677 12-30 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trucker Arrested, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0677,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Accuse Trucker of 80-mile Hit-and-Run Spree</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 6-9: `Trooper, police ..., to UPDATE with details
of citizens' chase, add that drug charge is felony. Picks up final
graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SEDENO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONDO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A trucker rammed his tractor-trailer into
more than 20 cars, seriously injuring at least two people, during an
80-mile chase Friday that snarled San Antonio morning rush-hour
traffic, authorities said.
   Stephen Odell Dillard, 41, of Coolidge, Ga., was charged with
possession of cocaine and was held in the Medina County Jail here
under $50,000 bond while authorities in other counties prepared
other charges against him, officials said.
   The chase began shortly after 8 a.m. on Interstate 10 near
Comfort, about 40 miles northwest of San Antonio, said state trooper
Alvin Schacht. The rig, carrying vegetables from California to
Florida, sideswiped a vehicle driven by lawyer Robert Etlinger, who
was run off the road but then pursued the fleeing truck, Schacht
said.
   The trucker ``was running between 85 and 90 and he (Etlinger)
couldn't catch him,'' Schacht said.
   ``He took the whole back end of my station wagon,'' said Donald
Kite, who was driving to work in San Antonio when he saw the truck
come up behind him. ``All of sudden, there was a KA-WHAM, and I
almost started going back under his trailer,'' he said.
   Troopers, police and at least 10 other drivers also pursued the
tractor-trailer before it finally stopped at an Interstate 35 rest
area near Natalia, southwest of San Antonio.
   The driver got out of the cab and citizens surrounded him until
the pursuing officers arrived to make the arrest, said trooper
Marshall Milikien.
   ``I was doing about 85 after him and I was about five car lengths
behind him,'' said Rene Davila, one of the citizens who followed the
trucker and kept him from leaving the rest stop.
   ``They just made sure he didn't run away,'' Milikien said of the
citizens, acknowledging that many sped to chase Dillard.
   ``He didn't say anything,'' said Lytle Police Chief Leo Thormann,
the first officer to arrive. ``To me he didn't appear that he knew
that anything had happened. He was very calm, very cooperative.''
   Troopers said they found 4 to 5 grams of cocaine in the cab, and
that narcotics officers planned to search the cargo. Dillard was
charged with possession of a controlled substance, a felony
punishable by two to 20 years in prison.
   Mary Herrera, 53, and Mercedes Loera, 62, injured when vehicles
were struck, were in serious condition at Wilford Hall Air Force
Medical Center at Lackland Air Force Base, said hospital spokeswoman
Lt. Col. Karen Wetzel. She would not release details of their
injuries.
</TEXT>
