<2ND_LINE>AM-Fatal Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0665,0465</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Die As Truck Plows Into Cars at Dangerous Intersection</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT location of crash.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX4</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID ROCKS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HIGHLAND PARK, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fiery chain-reaction crash that
killed four people and injured 10 others took place at the same
intersection where two fatal accidents occurred five years ago.
   A truck driven by Richard Hall, 37, of Warrenville, S.C., plowed
into a line of cars Thursday night at a stoplight at the
intersection of the Edens Expressway, also called U.S. 41, and
Clavey Road, about 25 miles north of Chicago, causing the crash and
a series of explosions, authorities said.
   ``Apparently ... the (truck) driver had been driving too many
hours and fell asleep,'' said Master Sgt. Jerry Bresnahan of the
Illinois State Police. ``I guess when you're on an interstate like
that, you don't expect to come to a stoplight.''
   Just after the light turned green, Hall's truck smashed into a
car, killing the two men and two women inside, Bresnahan said. The
car hit by the truck then smashed into others, a chain reaction that
involved seven cars in two lanes, he said.
   The identities of the four dead were not released Friday
afternoon. Hall was in good condition at Highland Park Hospital,
suffering from abdominal pain, said hospital spokesman Charles Block.
   Block said another crash victim, Marvin Whittaker, 44, of Zion,
Ill., was in fair condition with a rib fracture. Eight other people
were treated at the hospital and released, Block said.
   No charges had been filed in the case, Bresnahan said.
   State Department of Transportation figures show that at least 509
accidents have occurred at the intersection since 1976. In 1983, two
fatal accidents that left four people dead spurred lawmakers to
press for the construction of an overpass.
   ``I think it can be characterized as the most dangerous
intersection in Illinois,'' said Daniel Pierce, mayor of this
suburban town.
   The mayor added, ``I don't know how many deaths we have to have
there before the state thinks it's a dangerous intersection.''
   Charles McLean, an operations engineer for the state
transportation department, said the 45 accidents at the intersection
in 1987 ranked it sixth in Lake County and 25th in the Chicago
metropolitan area.
   ``In terms of the number of accidents (the intersection) doesn't
rank high. It's just the type of accident,'' he said.
   He said the department had been planning the $8.5 million
overpass since 1983, and that construction should begin next fall
and be completed in late 1990.
   But the lengthy process was costly, Pierce said.
   ``Finally it's going through, but not in time to save the lives
of those people,'' he said.
</TEXT>
