<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     12-30 0502</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Front Brings Rain, Gales And Snow To Northwestern U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front crossing the Northwest brought rain and gales to the
coastal areas and snow to higher elevations Friday, while showers
ranged from east Texas through the lower Mississippi Valley to the
Carolinas.
   Snow has been falling across northern sections of the Sacramento
Valley, and up to a foot of snow was possible through Friday night
high in the Sierra Nevada range of Northern California and the Lake
Tahoe area of Nevada.
   Gale warnings were set for coastal Oregon and Northern
California, and a snow advisory remained in effect Friday for the
mountains of Idaho, the Cascades of Washington and Oregon, and the
Siskiyou mountains of Oregon.
   A snow advisory has been posted through Saturday for northwestern
Wyoming. Winter storm watches have been posted through Saturday for
central Montana.
   Rain developing north of a warm front over the Gulf of Mexico
extended from eastern Texas through much of the lower Mississippi
Valley to western parts of the Carolinas on Friday afternoon.
   Fog continued to shroud parts of Florida and the Gulf Coast
Friday afternoon, with advisories for dense fog posted for
southwestern Louisiana and the coastal bend area of Texas.
   Light snow fell on parts of North Dakota, northern Minnesota and
Upper Michigan, with Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., receiving 2 inches of
snow during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST.
   Sunny skies prevailed from the southwestern Deserts, across much
of the southern and central Plains and across the Northeastern
states.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from zero
degrees at Fargo, N.D., to 84 degrees at Fort Myers, Fla. The low
for the nation Friday was 19 degrees below zero at Houlton, Maine.
   The national forecast for Saturday called for rain on the
northern and central Pacific Coast, with scattered showers over
Southern California. Snow will prevail from the coastal mountain
ranges to the northern High Plains, with heavy snow expected in
higher elevations.
   Snow showers will be scattered across the North Central and
Northeast states, with snow likely over northern Maine.
   Rain will extend from the western and central Gulf Coast to the
Carolinas and the mid-Atlantic Coast, with thunderstorms over the
central Gulf. Rain will be most likely from Louisiana to Tennessee
and the Carolinas. Fair to partly sunny skies will prevail over the
rest of the nation.
   Temperatures will remain freezing all day over the northern and
central Rockies, and from the northern High Plains through the Great
Lakes region to northern New England, with highs in the teens from
northern Montana to upper Michigan, and across northern Maine.
   Temperatures will warm into the 50s and 60s from the southern and
central coast of California to southern Arizona, and from the
southern High Plains to the southern Atlantic Coast. Temperatures
will warm into the 70s in the lower Rio Grande valley of Texas and
will reach the 70s and lower 80s across the Florida Peninsula.
</TEXT>
