<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 2114EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0679 12-30 0992</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0679,960</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Off For Holiday Without Filling Two Key Jobs</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: TOPS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with subpoena in Iran-Contra
case; PICKS UP 4th graf pvs bgng, `No announcements;' Edits final 3
grafs to shorten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President-elect Bush departed Friday for a long
holiday weekend at Camp David, Md., after receiving a court subpoena
that could force him to disclose information on the Iran-Contra
affair that he previously has refused to divulge.
   Bush was subpoenaed along with President Reagan as a defense
witness in the upcoming Iran-Contra conspiracy trial of former White
House aide Oliver North.
   The trial is to begin Jan. 31, which is 11 days after Bush
becomes president.
   He has repeatedly refused to say what he discussed with Reagan
regarding matters involved in the Iran-Contra affair, other than
that he had reservations about U.S. sales of arms to Iran.
   Bush's legal counsel Boyden Gray informed the president-elect
Friday morning that the subpoena would be forthcoming, said press
secretary Sheila Tate. She added it was ``not unanticipated.''
   She had no reaction from Bush but said he planned no meetings on
the subject while on a three-day vacation at the presidential
retreat in the Maryland countryside with his wife Barbara.
   As Bush left Washington, he also left unfilled the two
Cabinet-level posts he has not yet named _ energy secretary and drug
czar.
   Tate declined to indicate directly whether Bush would fight the
subpoena, but noted constitutional and legal questions were being
examined by White House and Justice Department lawyers, along with
Gray.
   ``What they're saying is that it's unprecedented to do that,''
she said in reference to potential Bush testimony.
   North is charged with conspiring with former national security
adviser John Poindexter and arms dealers Albert Hakim and retired
Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard Secord to illegally divert more than $12
million in U.S.-Iran arms-sales profits to the Contra rebels in
Nicaragua.
   The Bushes planned to relax in seclusion until late Monday, and
were expecting to be joined by no friends or aides, said spokeswoman
Kristin Taylor.
   No announcements were expected before Tuesday on Bush's choices
for energy secretary and the new Cabinet-rank post of drug czar,
said David Prosperi, spokesman for the Bush transition team.
   While speculation continued to swirl around former Energy
Secretary James R. Schlesinger as a potential pick for that post,
the president-elect spent Friday meeting with his designee for
United Nations ambassador, Thomas Pickering, and with CIA Director
William Webster.
   Pickering, currently the ambassador to Israel, briefed Bush on
U.S.-Israeli relations and they discussed the current Middle East
peace process, said Taylor.
   Substance of his private meeting and luncheon with Webster was
not disclosed.
   While several names have been mentioned as possible choices for
energy secretary, those of Schlesinger and former Rep. Henson Moore,
R-La., were said by transition sources to be the leading contenders
at week's end.
   Air Force Lt. Gen. James Abrahamson, head of the Pentagon's
Strategic Defense Initiative program, who had been mentioned earlier
as a contender for the energy job, has told friends he would not be
selected.
   For the Cabinet-level post of drug czar, created last year by
congressional legislation, the name of Customs Commissioner William
von Raab has been mentioned in several reports. However, von Raab's
aide, Steve Dougherty, said Friday that the commissioner has
received no query from nor had any official contact with the Bush
transition team.
   Meanwhile, the Bush transition office is expected to announce a
flurry of White House staff positions, including Bush campaign
operative Jim Wray as political director.
   Many names have surfaced as candidates for energy secretary, and
sources said the decision is being held up in part by strong
lobbying within the transition office for one or another candidate.
   Bush has said he wants someone with capabilities to deal with the
pressing problem of nuclear waste disposal and other nuclear safety
questions.
   Transition sources said Schlesinger, who served as the first
energy secretary when President Jimmy Carter appointed him, and
earlier as secretary of defense under Presidents Ford and Nixon, was
getting serious attention.
   Schlesinger's Washington office said Friday he would have no
comment on the matter.
   Moore's office also refused comment, but a source in the office
of one of his key boosters, Sen. Alan Simpson, R-Wyo., said Moore
has remained one of the top two contenders for he post.
   The independent-minded Schlesinger would be a controversial
choice, given opposition to him by industry leaders and his
affiliation with the trouble-plagued energy policies of the Carter
presidency.
   He was energy secretary when gasoline lines reappeared in the
summer of 1979, and resigned thereafter.
   He helped shape policy against which Ronald Reagan and Bush
campaigned in 1980, and large parts of which they dismantled _ a
massive government effort to develop unconventional sources of
energy, a so-called windfall profits tax on crude oil, help for the
poor faced with higher fuel bills and continued price controls on
natural gas. Bush in his campaign urged complete decontrol of
natural gas.
   Moore, who represented a chemicals- and refining-intensive
district around Baton Rouge, is a lawyer who ran unsuccessfully for
the Senate in 1986. He is backed my many in the oil industry, which
lost 150,000 jobs in the price collapse of recent years.
   Also frequently mentioned for the energy post is Environmental
Protection Agency Administrator Lee Thomas, who revived the nearly
abortive ``superfund'' toxic waste cleanup program in 1983, and
presided over a quintupling of the program.
   Meanwhile, transition officials have told Dennis R. Patrick,
chairman of the Federal Communications Commission, that Bush is
``fully satisfied with his performance and has no intention of
replacing him,'' FCC spokesman John Kamp said Friday.
   Many had expected Bush to replace Patrick at the helm of the FCC
in order to improve relations with Congress. Patrick's deregulatory
approach to the telecommunications and broadcasting industries has
made few friends among Democrats on Capitol Hill.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
