<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--NorCalQuake     12-30 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--NorCal Quake,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Moderate Quake Shakes South Bay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake shook San Jose and
other South Bay communities Friday afternoon, but no injuries or
damages were reported, authorities said.
   The earthquake struck at 3:54 p.m. abou 15 miles east of San Jose
and measured 4.3 on the Richter scale, said Pat Jorgenson, of the
U.S. Geological Survey in Menlo Park.
   The quake occurred on the Calaveras fault and was felt as far
north as Palo Alto, about 15 miles north of San Jose and 45 miles
south of San Francisco, said Jorgenson.
   The Richter scale is a measure of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by ground motion recorded on a seismograph.
A single increase in magnitude, as in from 5.5 to 6.5, means a
tenfold increase of ground motion.
   A quake of 3.5 can cause slight damage in populated areas, while
a quake of 6.0 can cause severe damage. In March 1964 an earthquake
in Alaska hit 8.5 on the Richter scale, killing 114 people.
</TEXT>
