<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Contras-Talks     12-30 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contras-Talks,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contras Propose New Peace Talks in Washington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Contra rebels on Friday proposed a new round of
peace talks with Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government, to be
held in Washington under the auspices of the Organization of
American States.
   ``We believe that this could break the impasse,'' Contra director
Roberto Ferrey said at the Contra headquarters in Miami. ``We are
accepting one of their proposals.''
   Talks between the U.S.-backed rebels have been stalled since June
when negotiations broke up in Managua, and the Contras refused to
return to the country, saying they were being harassed.
   Since then, both sides have accused each other of violating the
shaky truce, and a cutoff of U.S. military aid has sent many Contra
troops across the border into refugee camps in Honduras.
   The Sandinistas have expressed willingness to meet in Washington
or Managua on previous occasions, said Ferrey. He said the OAS would
be a natural forum for the peace talks.
   The Nicaraguan Resistance, as the Contras are formally known,
sent a telecopy of their proposal to the Sandinista foreign ministry
in Managua early Friday, Ferrey said, but have not yet received a
response.
   ``The Resistance proposes that the point of departure of this
round be the same proposals presented in June,'' Ferrey said. ``The
democratization of Nicaragua followed by troops surrendering of
arms.''
   But he said the Contras were flexible and would be willing to
change that agenda.
</TEXT>
