<DOCNO> AP881230-0181 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 2339EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Grenada-Trial     12-30 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Grenada-Trial,0366</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bishop Murder Trial Appeal Left Up in the Air By Death of Presiding
Judge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the Grenada Appeals
Court, Justice J.O.F. Haynes, has died, leaving in limbo the appeal
of 14 defendants convicted in the 1983 murder of leftist Prime
Minister Maurice Bishop.
   Bishop was overthrown and shot by a firing squad as a result of
factional feuding in his government. A Marxist junta took power,
leading to an invasion of Grenada by the United States, joined by
seven Eastern Caribbean nations that provided token forces. The
junta in turn was overthrown.
   Haynes, 76, died Wednesday in his native Guyana. A former
chancellor of the judiciary in Guyana, he was admitted to Georgetown
Hospital this month after returning from Barbados, where he also was
treated for an undisclosed illness.
   He is to be buried in Georgetown on Monday.
   Legal sources here, speaking on the condition of anonymity,
predicted that the entire appeal proceedings will have to be held
from the beginning as result of Haynes' death and the need to
appoint a new appeal court president.
   Haynes had recently chided defense and prosecution lawyers for
tardiness in proceeding with the appeal.
   ``If one of the judges were to die, the whole appeal will have to
be heard again,'' the state-owned Guyana Chronicle had quoted Haynes
as saying.
   Haynes had not been in good health for some time and appeared to
have had a premonition of his death.
   He remarked during a hearing of the Bishop appeal on Dec. 9, ``I
am living on borrowed time.''
   Hearings began on May 30 on the appeal of 14 former members of
Bishop's New Jewel Movement and the revolutionary government who
were convicted in Bishop's murder. Since then, the hearings had
taken up a total of 27 days.
   Proceedings had been adjourned until Jan. 28. It was expected
that a judgment would be handed down by summer.
   Haynes' death means this timetable will have to be revised to
find a replacement for Haynes and to give the new president time to
study the court records of the murder trial.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
