<1ST_LINE>r i AM-EthnicAlbanians     12-30 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ethnic Albanians,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eight Sentenced for Hostile Activity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A district court in southern
Yugoslavia on Friday sentenced eight ethnic Albanians to prison
terms ranging from four to 11 years for ``hostile activity,'' the
official Tanjug news agency reported.
   It said the court found them guilty of organizing a demonstration
by hundreds of ethnic Albanian schoolchildren last October in the
Macedonian town of Gostivar to protest a decision by education
authorities to limit instruction in the Albanian language.
   Ajredin Kaza, 32, the alleged head of the group, drew 11 years in
prison; Nazif Zinani, 29, and Zulufchli Dalipi, 29, each received
eight years; Imrli Bektesiju, 19, was sentenced to six years and
four unidentified minors were meted prison terms ranging from four
to six years, Tanjug said.
   The southern republic of Macedonia has been the scene of
increasing ethnic strife between the majority Slav population and a
rapidly growing minority of ethnic Albanians, who have been moving
south from troubled Kosovo province.
   Hundreds of ethnic Albanians have been sentenced to long jail
terms in Kosovo since riots there in 1981, when some ethnic
Albanians demanded greater autonomy for the province and its ethnic
Albanian population.
