<DOCNO> AP881230-0194 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1459EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WeekendTV-RyanWhite Adv13-15   12-30 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-Ryan White, Adv 13-15,0764</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv13</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>$Adv15</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Jan. 13-15 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>ABC Movie Tells Story of Young AIDS Victim's Fight To Attend School</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In the ABC movie ``The Ryan White Story,''
look for a scene in a hospital in which the young AIDS victim talks
to a friend named Chad.
   Chad is played by Ryan White, the Indiana youngster who took on
fear, ignorance and the establishment in his determination to go to
school despite being diagnosed as having the deadly acquired immune
deficiency syndrome. Chad is a friend who died of AIDS.
   Lukas Haas (``Witness'') plays Ryan. Producer Linda Otto said it
was director John Herzfeld's idea to have Ryan play Chad.
   ``Ryan was a natural,'' she said. ``He just understands. He has a
sixth sense. I loved being around him. He's enriched my life.
   ``He's just turned 17, he drives a car. No one quite understands
why he's fine, but he is. Ryan has determined to do well and have a
good life. The lesson of the movie is overcoming adversity. It's not
about AIDS, although that's what he has.
   ``I didn't want to make a movie about a boy dying of AIDS. I
wanted to make a movie about a kid living with AIDS. Every movie you
see about AIDS, the person dies. Even if Ryan had died I wouldn't
have him die in the movie. But I knew he wouldn't die. I knew he'd
hang in there.''
   At the end of the movie, which ABC broadcasts Monday, there is
another look at Ryan, plus his mother, Jeanne, and his sister,
Andrea.
   Judith Light plays Ryan's mother, Nikki Cox his sister. George C.
Scott plays his attorney, George Dzundza and Sarah Jessica Parker
his doctor and nurse, Mitchell Ryan and Grace Zabriskie his
grandparents and Peter Scolari an attorney representing the school.
   ``People wanted to be in this movie because it was about Ryan and
about AIDS,'' said Otto. ``We were able to get music from John
Cougar Mellencamp, Michael Jackson and Elton John because they all
knew about Ryan.''
   ``The Ryan White Story'' is a ``feel-good'' movie.
   Ryan is a hemophiliac who learned in 1984 that he had contracted
AIDS through a blood transfusion. His school in Kokomo, Ind., barred
him. Many parents wrongly believed that their children could get the
disease through casual contact with Ryan.
   ``A lot of people were terrified,'' said Otto. ``That's why this
picture is important. You can't get AIDS by casual contact. The fact
that it polarized an entire town is a microcosm of America. Kokomo
is as apple pie as you can get. There were no good people or bad
people. People wanted to protect their children.
   ``Ryan was bound and determined to go to school. They were bound
and determined to keep him out. It could happen in any community.
What made this a special case is that Ryan went public with it. `I
can't go to school? Watch me.'''
   Ryan won a precedent-setting court decision and now attends
school at his new home in Cicero, Ind.
   Otto said it took nearly three years to get the movie made after
the project was dropped by NBC, then picked up by ABC.
   ``That's a long time to care about a movie,'' she said. ``But
more important, I was concerned about Ryan. His health went up and
down. I wanted to get it done so he could be a part of it.
   ``Many people called about the rights to Ryan's story. But nobody
went to Kokomo and said, `I want to make this movie,' except me.
They didn't say yes right away. I sent them tapes of `Adam' and
`Bill','' two other real-life movies she has produced.
   Ryan's story was filmed in North Carolina, the third movie Otto's
Landsburg Co., has made there. The others were ``A Stoning in Fulham
County'' for NBC and ``Quiet Victory: The Charlie Wedemeyer Story''
for CBS. Otto is now awaiting word from ABC on another picture to be
filmed there, ``Unspeakable Acts,'' about a child abuse case in
Florida.
   Otto's movie ``Adam'' was about the murder-kidnaping of Adam
Walsh, which caused his father to crusade for a law setting up a
national clearinghouse for missing children, and ``Bill'' was about
a mentally retarded man, played by Mickey Rooney, who was able to
make it on his own.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions Jan. 13-15</NOTE>
</DOC>
