<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators, rushing to complete more
sales of insolvent savings and loan associations, defended their
handling of the crisis against charges that the multimillion-dollar
bailouts don't represent the best deals available to the government.
   Officials of the Federal Home Loan Bank Board, which regulates
the nation's 3,100 S&Ls, insisted Thursday that the cost to the
government of simply closing the institutions and paying off
depositors would far exceed the sales it is arranging, using tax
breaks and direct federal assistance as a lure for private investors.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Industry should enjoy, at a slightly reduced
pace, a seventh consecutive year of rising sales in 1989, according
to the government's annual assessment of winners and losers in
American business.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday that many manufacturing
industries, particularly those producing electronics and other
advanced technology and capital equipment, will do well in the new
year as American producers continue to benefit from a boom in export
sales.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States should take a more focused
and flexible approach to export controls on computers, especially
since the existing curbs on many components and systems have become
virtually unenforceable, a scientific advisory panel says.
   The administration should concentrate instead on striving _
together with its NATO allies and Japan _ to control leakage to the
Soviet bloc of militarily valuable supercomputers and the most
advanced computer manufacturing processes, the National Research
Council said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Coca-Cola Co.'s troubles with new Coke showed what
happens when you change ingredients in a time-honored brew. Now
Adolph Coors Co. has found out the hard way what happens when you
keep the ingredients but change the label.
   After the brewery slapped a new ``Original Draft'' label on its
flagship beer last summer, some long-time Coors drinkers thought the
beer had changed, though it hadn't.
   At some taverns and liquor stores in El Paso, Texas, and Southern
California _ two Coors strongholds _ sales slowed. Next week, Coors
will begin selling the beer under its old label again in those areas
_ alongside its new label.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union continues to buy U.S. grain
under a recently extended long-term agreement between the two
countries, including a new deal for 420,000 metric tons of wheat at
subsidized prices, the Agriculture Department said.
   The wheat is part of 2 million tons authorized Dec. 23 under the
Export Enhancement Program, or EEP, Christopher E. Goldthwait,
acting general sales manager for the department's Foreign
Agricultural Service, said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Labor Department will hold hearings in
February and March on lifting a World War II-era regulation that
bars apparel manufacturers from employing seamstresses in their
homes.
   The department said Thursday it will publish in Friday's edition
of the Federal Register an advanced notice of proposed rulemaking as
the first formal step for lifting the ban.
   President-elect Bush urged the action last October after the
Labor Department won approval from the White House budget office to
remove homework prohibitions in five other apparel fields effective
Jan. 8.
</TEXT>
