<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If reservations and ticket sales are any
indication, would-be air travelers appear undeterred by the bombing
a week ago of Pan Am Flight 103.
   Spokesmen for TWA, British Airways and Pan Am said there has been
no appreciable change in ticket sales, reservations or telephone
inquiries.
   Kevin Murphy, an airline analyst with Morgan Stanley & Co.,
agreed the crash in Lockerbie, Scotland, has had no short-term
impact. He noted that in the post-holiday season, ``Trans-Atlantic
travel pretty much goes to sleep.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avery Inc. said it is discussing the possible
sale of its Uniroyal Chemical Co. subsidiary to a management-led
investor group for as much as $810 million.
   The group, which also includes the investment firm Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc., would pay $240 million to $250 million in cash for
Uniroyal as well as the assumption of the division's $560 million in
