<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 0956EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SouthKorea-Trade     12-30 0207</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-Trade,0214</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Korean Surplus With U.S. Shrinks, Deficit With Japan Narrows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The national trade surplus with the
United States in the first 11 months of this year decreased to $7.61
billion, down $890 million from a year ago, the Korea Foreign Trade
Association reported Friday.
   Under American pressure, Korea has eased import curbs and taken
other steps in efforts to reduce the trade excess.
   The association listed Korean exports to the United States in the
January-November period at $19.06 billion, up 16.5 percent from a
year ago, and imports from the United States at $11.45 billion
dollars, up 45.7 percent.
   In November alone, Korea recorded a surplus of $782 million with
the United States, an increase of $7 million from a year ago,
officials said.
   They said Korea's trade deficit with Japan in the first 11 months
of this year shrank to about $3.58 billion, down $1.285 billion from
the same period last year.
   Korean exports to Japan during the period soared 45.3 percent
from a year ago to $10.86 billion while imports from Japan rose 17.1
percent to $14.44 billion.
   However, Korea's trade deficit with Japan in November alone
widened to $364 million from $338 million a year earlier.
</TEXT>
