<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1027EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Prime-MAIBasic     12-30 0494</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Prime-MAI Basic,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Restrains Takeover Effort, Cites Drexel Case As One Reason</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge's decision stalling a $970 million
takeover effort is based on concerns about the deal's huge debt
financing and criminal sanctions hanging over its investment banker,
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   The order by U.S. District Judge David Mazzone late Thursday came
hours before MAI Basic Four Inc.'s $20-a-share bid for Prime
Computer Inc. was due to expire. MAI Basic extended the bid until
Jan. 11.
   Mazzone's ruling appeared to be the first time that concern over
Drexel's record settlement of securities fraud charges announced
last week had affected litigation in a hostile takeover fight.
   Mazzone said he wanted more information from Tustin, Calif.-based
MAI Basic, which is about one fourth the size of Prime, involving
``the ambitious, fragile and possibly illegal financial requirements
through which (it and other investors) propose to acquire Prime.''
   The judge said MAI Basic, controlled by New York financier
Bennett S. LeBow, and its investment banker Drexel, are proposing a
deal that will cost a total of $1.5 billion with ``virtually all of
this financing (taking) the form of debt.''
   Of the $1.5 billion, $875 million would be in the form of junk
bond financing from Drexel, which Mazzone noted has ``acknowledged
its guilt to six felony counts related to its involvement in
similarly heavily leveraged transactions.''
   ``Suggestions that Drexel's guilty plea improves its financial
stability, while not necessarily disingenuous, are not helpful,''
Mazzone said.
   Prime stock closed at $17.75, up 37.5 cents, in composite New
York Stock Exchange trading Thursday.
   Matthew Eluck, an attorney for MAI Basic, said he was optimistic
MAI Basic would address some of Mazzone's concerns about financial
disclosures and that MAI Basic would be able to satisfy his latest
concerns.
   The judge also said MAI Basic's offer requires the Delaware
courts to strike down Prime's ``poison pill'' anti-takeover plan or
for Prime's board to rescind it, which is unlikely. Prime is
headquartered in Massachusetts but incorporated in Delaware.
   ``The bidders acknowledge that the poison pill makes Prime
prohibitively expensive,'' Mazzone said. ``Yet, despite a Delaware
court decision refusing to enjoin the plan, the bidders continue to
assert with confidence that they can consummate the deal.''
   Eluck said MAI Basic intended to pursue efforts in the Delaware
courts aimed at overturning Prime's poison pill. Under the plan, if
a party acquires more than 20 percent of Prime, current shareholders
are entitled to buy shares at half price.
   Meanwhile, Eluck said MAI Basic would respond promptly to
Mazzone's latest queries for further details of the financing.
   ``We think we will be able to provide them and comply with the
judge's directions for further disclosures by the end of next
week,'' he said.
   Prime said in a statement: ``We are gratified by the district
court's order and its recognition of the serious economic and legal
questions raised by MAI's efforts to acquire Prime.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
