<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1109EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoQuality     12-30 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Quality,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Domestic Carmakers Narrow Quality Gap, Marketing Expert Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic carmakers should be able to close
the quality gap with their Japanese and European rivals in the next
five years, auto marketing expert J. David Power III says.
   ``Domestic (manufacturers) as a group are still five years behind
the Japanese, but we're projecting by '93 or '94 we'll have parity
in product quality, at least in consumer perceptions,'' Power,
founder of J.D. Power & Associates, told auto dealers at the
Indianapolis Auto Show.
   Power predicted slightly slowing car sales over the next two
years, followed by a brisk recovery.
   ``We're (projecting) an average of 10.3 million passenger cars
and 4.9 million trucks'' will be sold in each of the next two years,
he said Thursday. ``We see (sales) climbing back by '93 to about 11
million passenger cars and 4.8 million light-duty trucks.''
   He said he does not expect continuing growth in demand for
light-duty trucks, which have given domestic manufacturers a big
lift in recent years.
   ``One thing that concerns me about the truck business is the rosy
projections everyone is giving to it,'' Power said. ``I would
caution the industry ... to be looking at a realistic level of
sales. We cannot sustain a 5 million light-duty truck market
forever.''
</TEXT>
