<HEAD>Soybeans Open Higher; Grains Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices opened moderately higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in sympathy with a rally in the
soybean meal market, but grain futures were nearly unchanged.
   Volume was light and trading conditions were extremely thin with
many traders getting an early start on the long New Year's weekend.
The exchange was scheduled to close at noon CST and to reopen on
Tuesday.
   Analysts attributed gains in the soy complex to the
lighter-than-expected delivery notices posted today against the
soon-to-expire January soy contracts _ a sign of strong demand.
   But grain traders seemed more concerned about evening up their
positions before the end of the year.
   ``It's not going to be a real exciting day, to say the least,''
said Jerry Gidel, an analyst with the G.H. Miller Division of LIT
America Inc.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to { cent lower with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.36} a bushel; corn was \ cent
lower to { cent higher with March at $2.82\ a bushel; oats were
unchanged to { cent lower with March at $2.39{ a bushel; soybeans
were \ cent lower to 4\ cents higher with January at $7.93 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were narrowly mixed in early trading
on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .13 cent lower to .27 cent higher with February
at 73.77 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent to .20 cent
lower with January at 83.95 cents a pound; live hogs were .25 cent
lower to .10 cent higher with February at 46.60 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .02 cent lower to .13 cent higher with
February at 43.17 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Thursday.
