<HEAD>Soybeans End Year With A Surge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices surged mightily Friday in
an abbreviated session on the Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts
for drier weather in South America and more soybean meal purchases
by the Soviet Union.
   Grain futures also advanced.
   Some meteorologists said a high-pressure ridge was forming over
the South American soybean belt, which could mean a return to the
unusually warm, dry conditions that marked the recent planting
period in Brazil and Argentina.
   Additional buying was prompted by rumors that the Soviet Union
planned to buy more U.S. soybean meal, said Dale Gustafson, an
analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   ``The Soviets are on a very aggressive import program for both
grain and protein in an attempt to improve food supply and
availabilities,'' he said.
   Volume was light and trading conditions were thin in the session,
which ended at noon CST.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 3\ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in March at $4.40 a bushel; corn was 1 cent to
2{ cents higher with March at $2.84{ a bushel; oats were 2 cents to
4\ cents higher with March at $2.43} a bushel; soybeans were 7\
cents to 17 cents higher with January at $8.04} a bushel.
