<DOCNO> AP881230-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1819EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv31-01   12-30 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 31-01,0745</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 31</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Dec. 31-Jan. 1</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Volatile Year For Interest Rates</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The interest rate forecast for 1988 turned out to
be a bit like a long-range weather report, with few experts
accurately predicting what was in store for the borrowing public.
   ``Everyone was thrown for a loop,'' said Jay Goldinger, a
principal of the Hollywood, Calif., investment banking firm Capital
Insight Inc. ``It was a year that frustrated many.''
   Consumers and businesses generally saw short-term interest rates
soar while longer-term rates were little changed from the previous
year, a mixed blessing for both groups.
   As a result, the so-called yield curve, which illustrates the
difference between short- and long rates in the bond market, took an
unusual turn in 1988. First it flattened from the normal upward
slope, then started to invert for the first time in about six years.
   ``I think if you were to try to isolate one key factor of the
1988 fixed-income environment it was the pronounced flattening of
the yield curve,'' said William V. Sullivan, director of
money-market research for Dean Witter Reynolds Inc.
   On the last day of trading in 1988, for instance, the yield on
the one-year Treasury bill was slightly higher than that of the
bellwether 30-year bond, 9.00 percent vs. 8.98 percent. The
3-month-bill yield was still 0.64 percentage points lower than the
long bond, although normally the gap is around 2 percentage points.
   Long-term rates usually are significantly higher to compensate
investors for their increased risk. (For instance, it's more likely
that someone will renege on a 30-year debt than on one lasting three
months.)
   The last time the yield curve inverted, the stock market took a
tumble and the nation headed into a recession.
   Few economists, though, are predicting a similar scenario for
1989. In fact, it was fears of the opposite occurring that pushed
short-term rates as high as they are now.
   ``The short-end rise (in rates) came from the Fed tightening,''
said Sullivan.
   At the start of 1988, the Federal Reserve eased its credit
policies by keeping interest rates down, out of near-universal
concern the country was close to a recession from the previous
October's stock market crash.
   But the economy showed surprising resilience. The Fed then
started to worry about rising inflation, along with an unstable
dollar in foreign exchange, and switched gears by tightening credit.
   Inflation actually remained in check throughout the year, which
is partly why long-term interest rates and prices remained fairly
stable, economists said.
   The central bank took its biggest inflation-fighting stand in
August, when it raised the discount rate, the interest charged on
loans to member banks, a half percentage point to 6.5 percent. Other
indirect movements have been made known since.
   Commercial lending rates followed suit. Major banks lowered their
prime lending rates _ used to set rates on most corporate and
consumer loans _ a quarter of a percentage point to 8.5 percent on
Feb. 2, then raised them a half percentage point four times to 10.5
percent by year's end.
   There was a similar pattern for mortgage rates. For a
conventional 30-year fixed-rate mortgage, rates ranged from a low of
9.84 percent in mid-February to a high of 10.77 percent at year's
end, according to the Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
   The interest rate climate didn't have too much effect on the
volume of municipal and corporate issues.
   For the year, the volume of municipal issues totaled around $112
billion, compared with $101.5 billion in 1987. The volume of
corporate issues rose to around $275 billion from $272.19 billion.
   Many economists predict that rates will continue to rise during
the first half of 1989, with the 30-year Treasury bond yielding as
much as 9.5 percent. It was as low as 8.29 percent in February and
as high as 9.45 in August.
   During the second half, interest rates should decline as the
economy starts to cool down, economists predict.
   ``We expect Fed policy next year to be driven primarily by
inflation and inflation expectations,'' said Elliott Platt, an
economist with Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette Corp.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions Dec. 31-Jan. 1</NOTE>
