<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     12-30 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended the year weaker against most
major currencies in thin, abbreviated trading Friday.
   Gold prices recovered. Republic National Bank of New York said
gold bullion was bid at $410.00 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up
$1.60 from late Thursday, when it lost $5.10 an ounce.
   Foreign exchange dealers attributed the dollar's weaker tone
Friday largely to comments made by Bundesbank vice president Helmut
Schlesinger in an interview with West German newspaper Die Welt.
   Schlesinger said a further increase in U.S. interest rates could
cause the dollar to rise, making it more difficult for the United
States to reduce its high trade deficit.
   One dealer said the comments had an impact on the market because
they were intperpreted as a call by Schlesinger for a lower dollar
and a firmer mark.
   However, others said that since trading was thin on the last
business day of 1988 some transactions had an exaggerated effect on
rates. Trading also ended a few hours earlier than usual.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.13 yen to close the year at 125.90 yen. In London,
it was quoted at 125.10 yen. Later, in New York, the dollar stood at
124.95 yen, down from 125.625.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.8062, compared with $1.7900
Thursday. Sterling fetched $1.8115 in New York, up from $1.7905.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.7770 West German marks, down from 1.7875; 1.4995 Swiss
francs, down from 1.5140; 1.19245 Canadian dollars, up from 1.19205;
6.0480 French francs, down from 6.0965; and 1,306.00 Italian lire,
down from 1,315.00.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday: 1.7725
West German marks, down from 1.7875; 1.5025 Swiss francs, down from
1.5125; 6.0600 French francs, down from 6.0975; 2.0020 Dutch
guilders, down from 2.0190; 1,305.25 Italian lire, down from
1,314.50; and 1.1927 Canadian dollars, up from 1.19225.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold for current delivery
closed at $410.00 a troy ounce, up from $408.20 late Thursday.
   Gold closed in London at $410.05 an ounce, up from $408.25 late
Thursday. In Zurich, the late bid price was $411.00 an ounce, up
from $410.75.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $3.63 to close at a bid $412.44.
   Silver prices were mixed. On New York's Comex, silver closed at
$6.038 a troy ounce, up from $5.998 Thursday. Silver was quoted in
London at a late bid price of $6.04 an ounce, unchanged from
Thursday.
</TEXT>
