<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Koppers     12-30 0290</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koppers,0303</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Koppers Managers Purchase Three Units</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Koppers Co. Inc. managers on Friday purchased
the company's tar processing, wood preservation and coke operations
from Beazer PLC for more than $200 million.
   The sale is the largest single divestiture of Koppers since
British industrialist Brian C. Beazer acquired the Pittsburgh-based
firm for about $1.8 billion in June, according to Beazer.
   However, Beazer said it was retaining a one-third interest in the
three businesses.
   Beazer also announced the sale of Koppers' 33-story headquarters
building in downtown Pittsburgh to a Miami real estate investment
firm for $45.5 million to United Trust Fund of Miami.
   The businesses sold Friday will be renamed Koppers Industries
Inc. and be headed by Robert K. Wagner, 57, former vice president
and general manager of the Koppers Tar and Wood Products Sector,
officials said.
   Koppers Industries said it expected to have revenue of more than
$400 million in 1989 with 20 plants in the United States and
interests in similar businesses in Australia and Denmark.
   The company will have about 1,900 employees.
   About 100 management investors own about 34 percent of Koppers
Industries' voting stock with the remainder shared equally by Beazer
and Koppers Australia, the company said. Koppers Australia is owned
by Koppers Industries, the Broken Hill Proprietary Co. Ltd. of
Australia and Hickson International PLC of Australia.
   Beazer said the sale of Koppers' assets has reached about $680
million thus far. The company has already sold Koppers' specialty
chemicals division and parts of its construction and construction
materials divisions.
   ``We expect to announce, within the next few months, the final
divestitures of our program,'' Beazer said.
   Proceeds of the sales are being used to pay down debt from the
Koppers acquisition, Beazer said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
