<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     12-30 0199</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0213</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market turned in a mixed performance
today as blue-chip issues sank, failing to sustain a run at a
post-crash closing high and fading as the last session of the year
drew to an end.
   Nonetheless, the market managed to post some sizeable gains for
the year.
   Analysts cited profit-taking in advance of the three-day New
Years holiday weekend, program selling by professional traders, a
rise in oil prices and weakness in the dollar for the stock market's
performance in the final session of 1988.
   ``It's the end of the year, and the last opportunity to sell,''
said Jack Solomon, a market technician for Bear Stearns.
   But Solomon also pointed out that the market had recovered more
ground than many people would have expected at the time of the
October 1987 market crash.
   ``So it ain't all bad,'' he said.
   In economic news today, the Commerce Department reported that its
Index of Leading Indicators fell 0.2 percent in November.
   But the government also revised upward its estimate of the
October gain in the leading indicators to a 0.4 percent rise rather
than the 0.1 percent increase originally reported.
</TEXT>
