<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1703EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-BankMerger     12-30 0282</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bank Merger,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yearlong Takeover Battle Ends With Formal Approval Of Bank Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of the nation's longest and most bitter
takeover battles formally ended Friday _ the last business day of
the year _ with the $1.48 billion merger of Irving Bank Corp. with
Bank of New York Co. Inc.
   The merger was approved by Irving's shareholders at a special
meeting, the Bank of New York said.
   Bank of New York said it expected that the principal banking
subsidiaries of the two holding companies, the Bank of New York and
Irving Trust Co., will be merged in the first half of 1989.
   ``All our efforts will now be directed to forging both
institutions into a major force in U.S. and worldwide banking,'' J.
Carter Bacot, chairman of the merged company, said in a statement.
   The two banks ended a year-long feud Oct. 7, when Irving's board
of directors voted to end its resistance and drop all lawsuits and
anti-takeover measures.
   In return, Bank of New York sweetened its offer by about $200
million by slightly increasing the stock portion of its bid and
adding stock warrants.
   The Federal Reserve Board removed the last formal obstacle to the
merger Nov. 28 by approving the deal. The board originally gave
conditional approval in February, extending it four times as Irving
battled the takeover.
   The merger will nearly double Bank of New York's size, vaulting
it close to the top 10 of the nation's largest banking companies.
The two banks had a combined $47.8 billion in assets as of June 30.
   Bank of New York's bid, launched Sept. 25, 1987, was the first
hostile takeover attempt among American banks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881230-0226 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-30-88 1719EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     12-30 0744</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0771</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans End Year With A Surge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices surged to a 10-week high Friday on the
Chicago Board of Trade amid forecasts of drier weather in the South
American soybean belt and rumors of more soybean meal purchases by
the Soviet Union.
   On other markets, energy futures rose sharply; precious metals
were higher; livestock and meat futures were mixed; and stock-index
futures retreated.
   Volume was uniformly light in thin trading conditions with many
traders away for the holidays. Most U.S. futures markets closed at
noon local time and will not reopen until Tuesday morning.
   Soybeans settled 7\ cents to 17 cents higher with the contract
for delivery in January at $8.04} a bushel, marking the first
settlement above $8 for a near-month soybean contract since Oct. 19.
   Some meteorologists said a high-pressure ridge was forming over
the central section of South America, which could cause a return to
the unusually warm, dry conditions that marked the recent soybean
planting period in Brazil and Argentina.
   Additional buying was prompted by rumors that the Soviet Union
planned to buy more U.S. soybean meal, said Dale Gustafson, an
analyst with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in New York.
   A Soviet purchase of at least 600,000 metric tons of U.S. soybean
meal earlier this week surprised traders and boosted optimism about
export sales of U.S. grains.
   ``The Soviets are on a very aggressive import program for both
grain and protein in an attempt to improve food supply and
availabilities,'' Gustafson said.
   Grain futures also closed higher. The wheat market was supported
by a new 90-day forecast for continued dry weather in the central
Great Plains, where winter wheat is grown, Gustafson said.
   Corn was buoyed by spillover buying from the adjacent wheat and
soybean pits, he said.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 3\ cents higher with March at $4.40 a
bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2{ cents higher with March at $2.84{ a
bushel; oats were 2{ cents to 4\ cents higher with March at $2.43} a
bushel.
   Crude oil for February delivery steamed through psychological
resistance at $17 a barrel and soared all the way to $17.30 on the
New York Mercantile Exchange before late profit-taking cut the gains.
   ``When it got past $17.15, a cold sweat gripped the shorts
(players who had bet that prices would fall) and they started to
buy,'' said Peter Beutel, an analyst with Elders Futures Inc. in New
York. ``It was a real buying frenzy in there.''
   The rally was almost entirely due to chart signals rather than
supply-and-demand factors, he said. But with OPEC's new
oil-production restraints scheduled to take effect Jan. 1, few
players were willing to go home holding short positions, he said.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 11 cents to 47 cents
higher with February at $17.24 a barrel; heating oil settled .50
cent to .84 cent higher with January at 53.48 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .77 cent to 1.05 cents higher with January at
47.88 cents a gallon.
   Gold and silver futures rose modestly on New York's Commodity
Exchange in a technical rebound after declining in each of the three
previous sessions.
   Platinum futures advanced slightly on the New York Mercantile
Exchange, but analysts were not encouraged by the rise in prices.
   ``Going into the new year, I've got to say the trend is a bit
down,'' said Richard Levine, a vice president of precious metals and
foreign exchange trading with Elders Futures.
   Gold settled $1.80 higher across the board with February at
$412.30 a troy ounce; silver was 3.5 cents to 4 cents higher with
March at $6.13 a troy ounce; platinum was 80 cents to $2.30 higher
with January at $516.60 a troy ounce.
   Livestock and meat futures finished narrowly mixed on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange in thin, directionless holiday trading.
   Live cattle were .10 cent lower to .15 cent higher with February
at 73.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .07 cent
higher with January at 84.15 cents a pound; live hogs were .30 cent
lower to .03 cent higher with February at 46.52 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .07 cent lower to .55 cent higher with
February at 43.05 cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,
where the contract for March delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
index settled 1.70 points lower at 280.40. Each point is worth $500.
</TEXT>
