<1ST_LINE>a f BC-InvestorIndex Adv02   12-30 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Investor Index, Adv 02,0230</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 02</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday Jan. 2</NOTE>
<HEAD>Small Investors' Portfolios Gained 10 Percent In 1988, Magazine
Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite predictions of gloom following the stock
market crash of October 1987, Money magazine's small investor index
recorded a 10 percent gain in 1988, the magazine says.
   The gain raised the value of the typical household's portfolio
from $70,956 to $78,019, the magazine said.
   The magazine's index is based on figures on individual investment
supplied by many sources, including the Federal Reserve Bank,
various investment houses and newsletters that follow the investment
field. Its household figure is derived by dividing the total amount
of individual investment by the number of U.S. households, said
Michael Sivy, a Money senior editor.
   The biggest winners of the year were stocks, especially blue-chip
issues, which racked up gains of 17.9 percent in the index, the
magazine said.
   Municipal bonds recorded an 11.4 percent gain for the year, it
said.
   Low short-term rates at the beginning of 1988 made money-market
funds and certificates of deposit poor performers, returning 6
percent and 8 percent for the year respectively, it said.
   Gold was the year's big loser, down in value 26.6 percent, it
said. But the metal represents less than 1 percent of individuals'
overall investments, it added.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday Jan. 2</NOTE>
