<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Wickes     12-30 0211</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Wickes,0221</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yorktowne Cabinetmaking Subsidiary Sold to Management Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Yorktowne Inc. cabinet-making
subsidiary of Wickes Cos. Inc. has been sold to a management group,
the second of several such sales expected to finance a leveraged
buyout of Wickes.
   Wickes, which announced the sale Friday, didn't reveal the price
paid for the Pennsylvania company.
   Yorktowne, a maker of kitchen and bathroom cabinetry, has offices
in Mifflingburg and Red Lion, Pa., and employs 700 people.
   No changes in management or workforce are planned, said Sam
Palazzolo, president of Yorktowne.
   A Yorktowne management group financed by Berkeley International
Capital Corp. is buying the company, Wickes said.
   It is the second element of the diversified company to be sold
since Wickes itself was bought by two New York investor groups,
Wasserstein, Perella Partners and Blackstone Capital Partners. That
deal is valued at $2.7 billion in cash, stock and assumption of
Wickes' debt.
   Last month, Wickes agreed to sell its WCI Financial Corp.
subsidiary to a management-led group for $300 million. Other units
are expected to be sold to help the new owners finance their
purchase of Wickes.
   Wickes, ower of the Builders Emporium home-improvement chain in
Southern California, has interests in retailing, auto products, wall
coverings and fabrics.
</TEXT>
