<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Tyson-HollyFarms     12-30 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tyson-Holly Farms,0400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Delaware Judge Blocks Poultry Maker Merger with ConAgra</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGDALE, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poultry giant Tyson Foods Inc. won an
important round Friday in its fight to acquire rival Holly Farms
Corp. for $1.1 billion when a judge blocked the target company from
merging with ConAgra Corp.
   The ruling by a Vice Chancellor Maurice Hartnett of the Chancery
Court in Delaware, where Holly is incorporated, evidently means
Tyson can proceed with its unsolicited $54-a-share cash tender offer
for the company.
   ``It's a major victory,'' said James B. Blair, counsel for Tyson.
``We are pleased and gratified with the court's decision.''
   Tyson is the nation's biggest poultry producer, ConAgra is No. 2
and Holly is No. 5. Together they control about 30 percent of the
ready-to-cook poultry market in the United States.
   Holly, based in Memphis, Tenn., has been resisting Tyson's
overtures and sought a merger with Omaha-based ConAgra to thwart an
unfriendly takeover. Under that deal, arranged in November, ConAgra
would acquire Tyson in a stock swap valued by securities analysts at
about $995 million.
   Hartnett had been asked by Tyson to set aside Holly' deal with
ConAgra. Tyson contended the target company's directors had not
considered getting the best price for their stockholders.
   Tyson also contended that the Holly's board was influenced by
managers who are unfriendly to Tyson's. Industry analysts have said
a Tyson takeover of Holly would likely lead to management changes at
Holly, while a merger with ConAgra probably would not cause such
turnover.
   ``Apparently, we won the case,'' Blair said from Tyson
headquarters in Springdale. ``We are now going to actively pursue
the acquisition. It means the playing field has been made into an
even ground.''
   Officials for Holly and ConAgra were in meetings and weren't
immediately available for comment.
   Earlier Friday, Tyson extended its tender offer until Jan. 6.
Nearly 3 million of Holly's approximately 20 million shares
outstanding had been tendered, Tyson said.
   Tyson produces more than 2 billion pounds of poultry a year,
ConAgra turns out about 1.5 billion pounds, and Holly Farms
processes about 1.2 billion pounds.
   The court announcement came after the conclusion of nationwide
stock trading. Holly stock closed Friday at $55.62{ per share, up
37{ cents. Tyson closed at $17.25, up 37{ cents. ConAgra closed down
12{ cents, at $29.
</TEXT>
