<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Zenith-Dumping     12-30 0482</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Zenith-Dumping,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Zenith Asks U.S. To Monitor TV Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLENVIEW, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zenith Electronics Corp. asked the
government Friday to invoke a never-used law to monitor imports of
televisions made by companies suspected of ``dumping'' in the United
States sets they assembled outside their home countries.
   Zenith, the only remaining U.S.-owned TV maker, said monitoring
by the Commerce Department would discourage foreign TV makers from
evading penalties imposed for selling their products in the United
States at unfairly low prices.
   The request stems from a provision in the 1984 trade law that
permits the Commerce Department to develop a 12-month monitoring
program in certain cases.
   ``We're simply asking the government to enforce the laws on the
books,'' Zenith Chairman Jerry K. Pearlman said in a statement.
   Commerce Department spokeswoman Claire Buchan said in a telephone
interview that before going ahead with a monitoring program, the
agency would have to find an ``extraordinary pattern of persistent,
injurious dumping'' that was causing a serious problem for the
domestic industry.
   She said the department also would have to decide how to monitor
imports _ a procedure presumably less complex than a full-scale
dumping investigation.
   ``Because it's a statute that's never been applied, it's
something we'll have to look at to determine what is the best way,''
Ms. Buchan said.
   Dumping refers to the sale of products in foreign markets at
unfairly low prices to get rid of excess production or to force
competitors out of business.
   Zenith, based in the Chicago suburb of Glenview, has not had an
annual profit since 1984, largely because of fierce competition from
cheap imports.
   Zenith's 378-page request asks the government to monitor imports
of color TVs, picture tubes and parts from Mexico, Malaysia,
Singapore, Hong Kong, China, Thailand and the Philippines. Those
countries have assembly plants established by television
manufacturers based in Japan, South Korea and Taiwan.
   Zenith claims that by assembling television sets in other
countries for export to the United States, the large Asian
television makers are evading anti-dumping duties imposed by the
Commerce Department that raise the prices of Japanese, South Korean
and Taiwanese-made sets at their borders.
   ``Even though a television produced at a Singapore plant may have
a Japanese picture tube and Japanese chassis and essentially is a
Japanese TV set, it's imported into the United States without any
anti-dumping duties assessed,'' said Zenith spokesman John Taylor.
   Anti-dumping provisions for picture tubes also are in place
against Japan, South Korea and Taiwan.
   Ordinarily, a dumping investigation is initiated when a company
or industry petitions the Commerce Department _ a cumbersome and
costly process.
   But the 1974 trade law also contains a provision for the Commerce
Department to initiate its own investigation if it determines
through monitoring that dumping is taking place.
   Taylor said Zenith hopes the Commerce Department will
``self-initiate'' an investigation in the latest case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
