<1ST_LINE>d f PM-OilPrices     12-30 0162</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Energy Futures Close Higher</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: for Saturday PMs</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil prices broke through the
psychologically important $17-a-barrel level in a yearend buying
spree.
   Analysts attributed Friday's rally to optimism that the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries would adhere to its
new production quotas starting Jan. 1.
   The 13-nation cartel agreed in November to slash daily production
to 18.5 million barrels to help prop up sagging worldwide oil prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange Friday, the February contract
for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
rose 43 cents to settle at $17.24 a barrel, after losing 20 cents on
Thursday.
   Among refined petroleum products traded on the exchange Friday,
the January contract for wholesale home heating oil rose 0.71 cent
to 53.48 cents a gallon. The contract declined 0.72 cent on Thursday.
   January wholesale unleaded gasoline, which lost 0.03 cent
Thursday, closed at 47.88 cents a gallon, up 0.87 cent.
</TEXT>
